pilation Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|103785}}\n* {{AllRovi person|267664}}\n* [http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/zach-braff Zach Braff at Emmys.com]\n\n{{Zach Braff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Braff, Zach}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Columbia High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Jewish American comedians]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University School of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Maplewood, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from South Orange, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People with obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8802:2900:b780:b8e7:b39:a078:2633", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zach_Braff"}
{"title_page": "Jean-Didier Vincent", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Jean-Didier Vincent''' (born on June 7, 1935 in [[Libourne]]).<ref>Cf. Acte de naissance n\u00b0 266 en date du 7 juin 1935 du registre des naissances de l'\u00e9tat-civil de la ville de Libourne pour l'ann\u00e9e 1935 ; ''Who's who in France'', \u00e9d. Jacques Lafitte, 41<sup>e</sup> \u00e9dition, 2010, page 2203, o\u00f9 encore ''Who's who in Sud-Ouest'', \u00e9d. Jacques Lafitte, 1<sup>re</sup> \u00e9dition, 1987, page 225, o\u00f9 les notices r\u00e9dig\u00e9es par l'int\u00e9ress\u00e9 lui-m\u00eame mentionnent bien sa naissance \u00e0 Libourne. Il n'est donc pas n\u00e9 \u00e0 Castillon-la-Bataille ou Sainte-Foy-la-Grande, comme l'indiquent \u00e0 tort divers auteurs de publications le concernant.</ref> in [[Gironde]], is a French [[neurobiologist]] and [[Neuropsychiatry|neuropsychiatrist]]. He was Professor of [[Physiology]] at the Faculty of Medicine of the [[University of Bordeaux]] II and then at the [[Paris-Sud University|University of Paris-Sud]]. From 1991 to 2004, he was also Director of the Alfred-Fessard Institute of [[Neurobiology]] at the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]]. He has been a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences|French Academy of sciences]] since 18 November 2003 and of the [[Acad\u00e9mie Nationale de M\u00e9decine|French Academy of Medicine]].\n\n== Biography ==\nJean-Didier Vincent is the only son of a [[Freemasonry|Freemason]] wine broker.<ref name=\"autobio gen\">{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent, neurobiologiste, publie son autobiographie g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Pour lui, \"La vie est une fable\". L'\u00eatre et le vivant|url=http://www.liberation.fr/portrait/1998/12/26/jean-didier-vincent-neurobiologiste-publie-son-autobiographie-genetique-pour-lui-la-vie-est-une-fabl_253452|author=Pascale Nivelle|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|date=26 December 2016|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe studied in [[Sainte-Foy-la-Grande]] (Gironde) at a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] college whose master intended him to study literature at the [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]], then at the Lyc\u00e9e Michel-Montaigne in [[Bordeaux]].<ref name=\"Autrement\">''Chercher - Jours apr\u00e8s jours, les aventuriers du savoir'', [[\u00e9ditions Autrement]], 2000, {{ISBN|9782746700550}}, {{p.|121-123}}.</ref> His parents, wine brokers and Protestants, and having experienced setbacks, encouraged him to undertake medical studies<ref name=\"Autrement\" /> at the \u00c9cole du service de sant\u00e9 des arm\u00e9es de Bordeaux, thinking that the white coat would suit him well and avoid the same financial difficulties.<ref name=\"Teteatete\">[http://www.franceculture.fr/emission-le-tete-a-tete-jean-didier-vincent-2012-01-22 Entretien avec Jean-Didier Vincent] dans ''Le T\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate'' de [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Tadde\u00ef]] sur [[France Culture]] le 22 janvier 2012.</ref> He became a major in [[Physics]], [[Chemistry]], [[Biology]] (a former university degree preparing for the first year of medicine). As an intern in clinical services, he met the neuropsychiatrist Jacques Faure, who encouraged him to do research in this field.<ref name=\"Teteatete\" /><ref>Interview de Jean Didier Vincent par [[Jacques Paugam]] sur Canal Acad\u00e9mie, 27 f\u00e9vrier 2011</ref>\n\nJean-Didier Vincent is a hospital [[biologist]] in physiology and functional explorations at the CHRU of Bordeaux (1966-1977), professor without a chair (1973-1978) and professor of physiology at the Bordeaux Faculty of Medicine (1979-1992). He headed the [[Inserm]] 176/CNRS \"Neurobiology of Behaviours\" unit at the Bordeaux University Hospital (1978-1990) before taking over as Director of the Alfred-Fessart Institute in [[Gif-sur-Yvette]] from 1992 to 2003. He is Professor of Physiology at the Faculty of Medicine of Paris Sud, Hospital Practitioner at the [[Le Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre|Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre]] Hospital (1992-2006) and Professor at the Institut universitaire de France, Chair of Neuro-endocrinology at the Faculty of Medicine of Paris-Sud, Paris XI University (1994-2004).<ref>[http://histoire.inserm.fr/les-femmes-et-les-hommes/jean-didier-vincent/(page)/2 Jean-Didier Vincent], sur histoire.inserm.fr</ref>\n\nIn 1988, he signed the appeal to [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], but has regretted this political commitment since.<ref name=\"autobio gen\" />\n\nHe has carried out research in neurobiology in the United States (postdoctoral fellowship at the Brain Institute of the [[University of California]], Los Angeles) and then in France (CNRS, Inserm).\n\nJean-Didier Vincent has been President of the National Council of Programmes at the Ministry of National Education since 2002, member of the CNRS Ethics of Science Committee (COMETS) and the INRA (Instiut National de Recherche en Agronomie) Ethics and Precaution Committee for Agricultural Research Applications (COMEPRA). A member of the Executive Board of the Foundation for Political Innovation until 23 January 2009, he has been President of the Association pour l'Universit\u00e9 num\u00e9rique francophone mondiale (UNFM) since October 2005.\n\n== Scientific contributions ==\nJean-Didier Vincent has contributed significantly to the development of [[neuroendocrinology]], which includes the study of interactions between [[Hormone|hormones]] and the [[nervous system]], the brain being also considered as an [[endocrine gland]]. He has a much more pessimistic vision than his colleague [[Boris Cyrulnik]] about what predetermines human behaviour and believes in the primacy of the biological over reason, stating in 2013 in the film ''La Possibilit\u00e9 d'\u00eatre humain'' : \"''L'homme est libre, ouis mais, en libert\u00e9 surveill\u00e9e''\".\n\nHe has published numerous books with biologizing thesis, Biologie des passions, La Chair et le diable.<ref>S\u00e9bastien Lemerle, \u00ab Les habits neufs du biologisme en France \u00bb, ''Actes de la recherche en sciences sociale'', <abbr>n<sup>os</sup></abbr> 176-177, 2009, <abbr>p.</abbr> 75</ref> In Biologie des passions, he defends a dynamic above all sexual dynamics of love (Eros). He lists the sexual practices that are omnipresent in nature (even the most \"deviant\"), and suggests that the notion of women's property was born during the sedentarization of the [[Neolithic era]]. It also details the complexity of sexual systems, which are often designed to frame the reproductive rules of each species.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent: \"Baisez et tout ira mieux\"|url=http://www.sinemensuel.com/interview/jean-didier-vincent-baisez-et-tout-ira-mieux/|website=Sinemensuel.com|date=July 2015|access-date=21 January 2016|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''Bienvenue en Transhumanie'', he takes a sceptical look at [[transhumanism]], denouncing a lack of morality that is necessary around this radical transformation of the [[genome]]. He also fears a disconnection between reproduction and sexuality, and that sexuality is virtualized by directly stimulating the affected parts of the brain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent, de l'humain au transhumain|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/grands-entretiens/jean-didier-vincent-de-l-humain-au-transhumain-13-10-2011-1386477_326.php|author=\u00c9lisabeth L\u00e9vy|website=Lepoint.fr|date=13 October 2011|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Other functions ==\n\n* Member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* Member of the [[Academia Europaea]]\n* Member of the [[Royal Academies for Science and the Arts of Belgium|Royal Academy of Belgium]] (science class)\n* Honorary Member of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Belgium\n* Corresponding member of the French Academy of sciences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academie-sciences.fr/fr/Liste-des-membres-de-l-Academie-des-sciences-/-V/jean-didier-vincent.html|title=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Member of the French Academy of Medicine<ref>{{cite web|title=Acad\u00e9mie nationale de M\u00e9decine|url=http://www.academie-medecine.fr/composition/membres/membres-titulaires/|date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* 1981: La Caze Prize from the Academy of Sciences\n* 1991: Blaise-Pascal prize\n* 1996: Medicine and Culture Award from the Institute of Health Sciences\n* 1998: Gold medal at the University of Prague\n* 1999: Doctor honoris causa of the Free University of Brussels\n* 2010: Honorary President of the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 historique et arch\u00e9ologique de Libourne\n* Officier of the [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'Honneur]]\n* Commandeur of the [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques|Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]]\n* Chevalier of the [[Order of Agricultural Merit|Ordre du M\u00e9rite Agricole]]\n\n== Books ==\nJean-Didier Vincent has written several books, the most famous of which is ''La Biologie des passions'' and ''[[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]], g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste'' who received the 2010 Femina essai prize.\n\n* ''La Biologie des passions'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1986 et coll. Opus 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Biologie-des-passions/4477|title=La biologie des Passions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Casanova, la contagion du plaisir'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1990, (prix Blaise-Pascal)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Casanova-la-contagion-du-plaisir/28622|title=Casanova la contagion du plaisir|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Celui qui parlait presque'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livre.fnac.com/a1032645/Jean-Didier-Vincent-Celui-qui-parlait-presque|title=Celui qui parlait presque|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''La Chair et le Diable'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-La-chair-et-le-diable/160971|title=La Chair et le Diable|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''L'Art de parler la bouche pleine'', \u00c9ditions de la Presqu'Ile, 1997<ref>{{Cite book|title=L'Art de parler la bouche pleine|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2879380715|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''La vie est une fable'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-La-vie-est-une-fable/441236|title=La vie est une fable|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Qu'est-ce que l'homme ?'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinterest.fr/pin/737253401477285401/|title=Qu'est ce que l'Homme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Faust : une histoire naturelle'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.decitre.fr/ebooks/faust-une-histoire-naturelle-9782738161772_9782738161772_13.html|title=Faust, une histoire naturelle|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''La Dispute sur le vivant'', \u00e9ditions Descl\u00e9e de Brouwer, 2000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://data.bnf.fr/temp-work/ef8c7c2065d708d14b8e00d9deabff5d/|title=La dispute du vivant|last=|first=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|year=2000}}</ref>\n* ''Pour une nouvelle philosophie du go\u00fbt'', 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Pour-une-nouvelle-physiologie-go%C3%BBt-ebook/dp/B00QR1Q44M|title=Pour une nouvelle philosophie du go\u00fbt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le C\u0153ur des autres - Biologie de la compassion'', \u00e9ditions Plon, 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Le-coeur-des-autres--Biologie-de-la-compassion/265569|title=Le c\u0153ur des autres : biologie de la compassion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Voyage extraordinaire au centre du cerveau'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/neurosciences/voyage-extraordinaire-au-centre-du-cerveau_9782738119353.php|title=Voyage extraordinaire au centre du cerveau|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste'', \u00e9ditions Robert Laffont, 2010 (prix Femina essai)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Elis\u00e9e Rectus, g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2221106482|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''Le Sexe expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 ma fille'', \u00e9ditions du Seuil, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seuil.com/ouvrage/le-sexe-explique-a-ma-fille-jean-didier-vincent/9782021021660|title=Le sexe expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 ma fille|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Bienvenue en Transhumanie'', avec Genevi\u00e8ve Ferone, \u00e9ditions Grasset, 2011<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Rodis-Lewis-Bienvenue-en-transhumanie--Sur-lhomme-de-demain/393222|title=Bienvenue en Transhumanie|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le Cerveau sur mesure'', avec Pierre-Marie Lledo, \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2012<ref>{{Cite book|title=Le cerveau sur mesure|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2738127096|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''Biologie du couple'', \u00e9ditions Robert Laffont, 2015<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.lisez.com/livre-grand-format/biologie-du-couple/9782221117088|title=Biologie du couple|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le cerveau expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 mon petit-fils'', \u00e9ditions du Seuil, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Le-cerveau-explique-a-mon-petit-fils/820743|title=Le cerveau expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 mon Petit-fils|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Privacy policy ==\nJean-Didier Vincent was married to Lucy Vincent. He has five children, from two marriages.\n\n== Polemics ==\n\n=== On Down's syndrome ===\nOn 5 October 2012, during the program La T\u00eate au carr\u00e9, broadcast on [[France Inter]], a new test likely to diagnose [[Trisomy-21|trisomy 21]] in early pregnancy was discussed. Jean-Didier Vincent defended this prenatal diagnosis, claiming that \"[[Down syndrome|Down's syndrome]] is a poison in a family. \"During the program, Jean-Didier Vincent revisited this statement, which was considered \"violent\" by host Mathieu Vidard, and withdrew it, calling it an \"unfortunate term\" but without apologizing. \u00c9l\u00e9onore Laloux, a young woman with Down's syndrome and spokesperson for the collective Les Amis d'\u00c9l\u00e9onore, responded to the biologist in 2013 in a video,<ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x177y8o_journee-de-la-trisomie-21-eleonore-laloux-s-exprime_webcam El\u00e9onore Laloux r\u00e9pond \u00e0 Jean-Didier Vincent]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Non, les trisomiques ne sont pas un \"poison dans une famille\" !|url=http://www.lavie.fr/actualite/billets/non-les-trisomiques-ne-sont-pas-un-poison-dans-une-famille-13-11-2012-33238_288.php|author=Emmanuel Laloux|website=Lavie.fr|date=12 November 2012|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref> then again in March 2014 in an autobiographical book, ''Triso et alors!'' co-written with journalist Yann Barte.\n\n=== On GMOs ===\nEarlier, during the same program, which dealt with [[Genetically modified organism|GMO]] testing in agriculture, Jean-Didier Vincent defended the firm [[Monsanto]] and made the following comments in particular: \"we must use GMOs\", \"it has rendered great services to agriculture\", \"it has increased productivity. \u00bb\n\n=== Conviction ===\nOn February 12, 2008, during the television show ''Ce soir ou jamais'', he said about [[Jean-Marie Le Pen|Jean-Marie Le Pen:]] \"We knew him as the white wolf, he was a bastard\", and added: \"he probably committed crimes, but I can't say it on the air\". On 28 May 2009, the Paris Court of Appeal found him guilty of insult (first sentence) and defamation (second sentence), and sentenced him to a suspended fine of \u20ac1,500 and \u20ac4,000 in damages<ref>''[[Lib\u00e9ration (journal)|Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 28 mai 2009 [http://www.liberation.fr/societe/0101570013-5500-euros-pour-avoir-traite-le-pen-de-salopard \u00ab 5500 euros pour avoir trait\u00e9 Le Pen de salopard \u00bb]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vincent, Jean-Didier}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:People from Libourne]]\n[[Category:French neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:French neurologists]]\n[[Category:French psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:French science writers]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Bordeaux faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Paris-Saclay faculty]]\n[[Category:CNRS research directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Jean-Didier Vincent''' (born on June 7, 1935 in [[Libourne]]).<ref>Cf. Acte de naissance n\u00b0 266 en date du 7 juin 1935 du registre des naissances de l'\u00e9tat-civil de la ville de Libourne pour l'ann\u00e9e 1935 ; ''Who's who in France'', \u00e9d. Jacques Lafitte, 41<sup>e</sup> \u00e9dition, 2010, page 2203, o\u00f9 encore ''Who's who in Sud-Ouest'', \u00e9d. Jacques Lafitte, 1<sup>re</sup> \u00e9dition, 1987, page 225, o\u00f9 les notices r\u00e9dig\u00e9es par l'int\u00e9ress\u00e9 lui-m\u00eame mentionnent bien sa naissance \u00e0 Libourne. Il n'est donc pas n\u00e9 \u00e0 Castillon-la-Bataille ou Sainte-Foy-la-Grande, comme l'indiquent \u00e0 tort divers auteurs de publications le concernant.</ref> in [[Gironde]], is a French [[neurobiologist]] and [[Neuropsychiatry|neuropsychiatrist]]. He was Professor of [[Physiology]] at the Faculty of Medicine of the [[University of Bordeaux]] II and then at the [[Paris-Sud University|University of Paris-Sud]]. From 1991 to 2004, he was also Director of the Alfred-Fessard Institute of [[Neurobiology]] at the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]]. He has been a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences|French Academy of sciences]] since 18 November 2003 and of the [[Acad\u00e9mie Nationale de M\u00e9decine|French Academy of Medicine]].\n\n== Biography ==\nJean-Didier Vincent is the only son of a [[Freemasonry|Freemason]] wine broker.<ref name=\"autobio gen\">{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent, neurobiologiste, publie son autobiographie g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Pour lui, \"La vie est une fable\". L'\u00eatre et le vivant|url=http://www.liberation.fr/portrait/1998/12/26/jean-didier-vincent-neurobiologiste-publie-son-autobiographie-genetique-pour-lui-la-vie-est-une-fabl_253452|author=Pascale Nivelle|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|date=26 December 2016|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe studied in [[Sainte-Foy-la-Grande]] (Gironde) at a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] college whose master intended him to study literature at the [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]], then at the Lyc\u00e9e Michel-Montaigne in [[Bordeaux]].<ref name=\"Autrement\">''Chercher - Jours apr\u00e8s jours, les aventuriers du savoir'', [[\u00e9ditions Autrement]], 2000, {{ISBN|9782746700550}}, {{p.|121-123}}.</ref> His parents, wine brokers and Protestants, and having experienced setbacks, encouraged him to undertake medical studies<ref name=\"Autrement\" /> at the \u00c9cole du service de sant\u00e9 des arm\u00e9es de Bordeaux, thinking that the white coat would suit him well and avoid the same financial difficulties.<ref name=\"Teteatete\">[http://www.franceculture.fr/emission-le-tete-a-tete-jean-didier-vincent-2012-01-22 Entretien avec Jean-Didier Vincent] dans ''Le T\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate'' de [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Tadde\u00ef]] sur [[France Culture]] le 22 janvier 2012.</ref> He became a major in [[Physics]], [[Chemistry]], [[Biology]] (a former university degree preparing for the first year of medicine). As an intern in clinical services, he met the neuropsychiatrist Jacques Faure, who encouraged him to do research in this field.<ref name=\"Teteatete\" /><ref>Interview de Jean Didier Vincent par [[Jacques Paugam]] sur Canal Acad\u00e9mie, 27 f\u00e9vrier 2011</ref>\n\nJean-Didier Vincent is a hospital [[biologist]] in physiology and functional explorations at the CHRU of Bordeaux (1966-1977), professor without a chair (1973-1978) and professor of physiology at the Bordeaux Faculty of Medicine (1979-1992). He headed the [[Inserm]] 176/CNRS \"Neurobiology of Behaviours\" unit at the Bordeaux University Hospital (1978-1990) before taking over as Director of the Alfred-Fessart Institute in [[Gif-sur-Yvette]] from 1992 to 2003. He is Professor of Physiology at the Faculty of Medicine of Paris Sud, Hospital Practitioner at the [[Le Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre|Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre]] Hospital (1992-2006) and Professor at the Institut universitaire de France, Chair of Neuro-endocrinology at the Faculty of Medicine of Paris-Sud, Paris XI University (1994-2004).<ref>[http://histoire.inserm.fr/les-femmes-et-les-hommes/jean-didier-vincent/(page)/2 Jean-Didier Vincent], sur histoire.inserm.fr</ref>\n\nIn 1988, he signed the appeal to [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], but has regretted this political commitment since.<ref name=\"autobio gen\" />\n\nHe has carried out research in neurobiology in the United States (postdoctoral fellowship at the Brain Institute of the [[University of California]], Los Angeles) and then in France (CNRS, Inserm).\n\nJean-Didier Vincent has been President of the National Council of Programmes at the Ministry of National Education since 2002, member of the CNRS Ethics of Science Committee (COMETS) and the INRA (Instiut National de Recherche en Agronomie) Ethics and Precaution Committee for Agricultural Research Applications (COMEPRA). A member of the Executive Board of the Foundation for Political Innovation until 23 January 2009, he has been President of the Association pour l'Universit\u00e9 num\u00e9rique francophone mondiale (UNFM) since October 2005.\n\n== Scientific contributions ==\nJean-Didier Vincent has contributed significantly to the development of [[neuroendocrinology]], which includes the study of interactions between [[Hormone|hormones]] and the [[nervous system]], the brain being also considered as an [[endocrine gland]]. He has a much more pessimistic vision than his colleague [[Boris Cyrulnik]] about what predetermines human behaviour and believes in the primacy of the biological over reason, stating in 2013 in the film ''La Possibilit\u00e9 d'\u00eatre humain'' : \"''L'homme est libre, ouis mais, en libert\u00e9 surveill\u00e9e''\".\n\nHe has published numerous books with biologizing thesis, Biologie des passions, La Chair et le diable.<ref>S\u00e9bastien Lemerle, \u00ab Les habits neufs du biologisme en France \u00bb, ''Actes de la recherche en sciences sociale'', <abbr>n<sup>os</sup></abbr> 176-177, 2009, <abbr>p.</abbr> 75</ref> In Biologie des passions, he defends a dynamic above all sexual dynamics of love (Eros). He lists the sexual practices that are omnipresent in nature (even the most \"deviant\"), and suggests that the notion of women's property was born during the sedentarization of the [[Neolithic era]]. It also details the complexity of sexual systems, which are often designed to frame the reproductive rules of each species.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent: \"Baisez et tout ira mieux\"|url=http://www.sinemensuel.com/interview/jean-didier-vincent-baisez-et-tout-ira-mieux/|website=Sinemensuel.com|date=July 2015|access-date=21 January 2016|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''Bienvenue en Transhumanie'', he takes a sceptical look at [[transhumanism]], denouncing a lack of morality that is necessary around this radical transformation of the [[genome]]. He also fears a disconnection between reproduction and sexuality, and that sexuality is virtualized by directly stimulating the affected parts of the brain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Didier Vincent, de l'humain au transhumain|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/grands-entretiens/jean-didier-vincent-de-l-humain-au-transhumain-13-10-2011-1386477_326.php|author=\u00c9lisabeth L\u00e9vy|website=Lepoint.fr|date=13 October 2011|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Other functions ==\n\n* Member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* Member of the [[Academia Europaea]]\n* Member of the [[Royal Academies for Science and the Arts of Belgium|Royal Academy of Belgium]] (science class)\n* Honorary Member of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Belgium\n* Corresponding member of the French Academy of sciences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academie-sciences.fr/fr/Liste-des-membres-de-l-Academie-des-sciences-/-V/jean-didier-vincent.html|title=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Member of the French Academy of Medicine<ref>{{cite web|title=Acad\u00e9mie nationale de M\u00e9decine|url=http://www.academie-medecine.fr/composition/membres/membres-titulaires/|date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* 1981: La Caze Prize from the Academy of Sciences\n* 1991: Blaise-Pascal prize\n* 1996: Medicine and Culture Award from the Institute of Health Sciences\n* 1998: Gold medal at the University of Prague\n* 1999: Doctor honoris causa of the Free University of Brussels\n* 2010: Honorary President of the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 historique et arch\u00e9ologique de Libourne\n* Officier of the [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'Honneur]]\n* Commandeur of the [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques|Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]]\n* Chevalier of the [[Order of Agricultural Merit|Ordre du M\u00e9rite Agricole]]\n\n== Books ==\nJean-Didier Vincent has written several books, the most famous of which is ''La Biologie des passions'' and ''[[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]], g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste'' who received the 2010 Femina essai prize.\n\n* ''La Biologie des passions'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1986 et coll. Opus 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Biologie-des-passions/4477|title=La biologie des Passions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Casanova, la contagion du plaisir'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1990, (prix Blaise-Pascal)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Casanova-la-contagion-du-plaisir/28622|title=Casanova la contagion du plaisir|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Celui qui parlait presque'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livre.fnac.com/a1032645/Jean-Didier-Vincent-Celui-qui-parlait-presque|title=Celui qui parlait presque|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''La Chair et le Diable'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-La-chair-et-le-diable/160971|title=La Chair et le Diable|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''L'Art de parler la bouche pleine'', \u00c9ditions de la Presqu'Ile, 1997<ref>{{Cite book|title=L'Art de parler la bouche pleine|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2879380715|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''La vie est une fable'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-La-vie-est-une-fable/441236|title=La vie est une fable|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Qu'est-ce que l'homme ?'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinterest.fr/pin/737253401477285401/|title=Qu'est ce que l'Homme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Faust : une histoire naturelle'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.decitre.fr/ebooks/faust-une-histoire-naturelle-9782738161772_9782738161772_13.html|title=Faust, une histoire naturelle|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''La Dispute sur le vivant'', \u00e9ditions Descl\u00e9e de Brouwer, 2000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://data.bnf.fr/temp-work/ef8c7c2065d708d14b8e00d9deabff5d/|title=La dispute du vivant|last=|first=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|year=2000}}</ref>\n* ''Pour une nouvelle philosophie du go\u00fbt'', 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Pour-une-nouvelle-physiologie-go%C3%BBt-ebook/dp/B00QR1Q44M|title=Pour une nouvelle philosophie du go\u00fbt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le C\u0153ur des autres - Biologie de la compassion'', \u00e9ditions Plon, 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Le-coeur-des-autres--Biologie-de-la-compassion/265569|title=Le c\u0153ur des autres : biologie de la compassion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Voyage extraordinaire au centre du cerveau'', \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/neurosciences/voyage-extraordinaire-au-centre-du-cerveau_9782738119353.php|title=Voyage extraordinaire au centre du cerveau|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste'', \u00e9ditions Robert Laffont, 2010 (prix Femina essai)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Elis\u00e9e Rectus, g\u00e9ographe, anarchiste, \u00e9cologiste|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2221106482|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''Le Sexe expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 ma fille'', \u00e9ditions du Seuil, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seuil.com/ouvrage/le-sexe-explique-a-ma-fille-jean-didier-vincent/9782021021660|title=Le sexe expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 ma fille|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Bienvenue en Transhumanie'', avec Genevi\u00e8ve Ferone, \u00e9ditions Grasset, 2011<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Rodis-Lewis-Bienvenue-en-transhumanie--Sur-lhomme-de-demain/393222|title=Bienvenue en Transhumanie|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le Cerveau sur mesure'', avec Pierre-Marie Lledo, \u00e9ditions Odile Jacob, 2012<ref>{{Cite book|title=Le cerveau sur mesure|last=|first=|date=|id={{ASIN|2738127096|country=fr}}}}</ref>\n* ''Biologie du couple'', \u00e9ditions Robert Laffont, 2015<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.lisez.com/livre-grand-format/biologie-du-couple/9782221117088|title=Biologie du couple|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Le cerveau expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 mon petit-fils'', \u00e9ditions du Seuil, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babelio.com/livres/Vincent-Le-cerveau-explique-a-mon-petit-fils/820743|title=Le cerveau expliqu\u00e9 \u00e0 mon Petit-fils|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Privacy policy ==\nJean-Didier Vincent was married to Lucy Vincent. He has five children, from two marriages.\n\n== Polemics ==\n\n=== On Down's syndrome ===\nOn 5 October 2012, during the programme La T\u00eate au carr\u00e9, broadcast on [[France Inter]], a new test likely to diagnose [[Trisomy-21|trisomy 21]] in early pregnancy was discussed. Jean-Didier Vincent defended this prenatal diagnosis, claiming that \"[[Down syndrome|Down's syndrome]] is a poison in a family. \"During the program, Jean-Didier Vincent revisited this statement, which was considered \"violent\" by host Mathieu Vidard, and withdrew it, calling it an \"unfortunate term\" but without apologizing. \u00c9l\u00e9onore Laloux, a young woman with Down's syndrome and spokesperson for the collective Les Amis d'\u00c9l\u00e9onore, responded to the biologist in 2013 in a video,<ref>[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x177y8o_journee-de-la-trisomie-21-eleonore-laloux-s-exprime_webcam El\u00e9onore Laloux r\u00e9pond \u00e0 Jean-Didier Vincent]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Non, les trisomiques ne sont pas un \"poison dans une famille\" !|url=http://www.lavie.fr/actualite/billets/non-les-trisomiques-ne-sont-pas-un-poison-dans-une-famille-13-11-2012-33238_288.php|author=Emmanuel Laloux|website=Lavie.fr|date=12 November 2012|access-date=21 January 2017|publication-date=}}</ref> then again in March 2014 in an autobiographical book, ''Triso et alors!'' co-written with journalist Yann Barte.\n\n=== On GMOs ===\nEarlier, during the same program, which dealt with [[Genetically modified organism|GMO]] testing in agriculture, Jean-Didier Vincent defended the firm [[Monsanto]] and made the following comments in particular: \"we must use GMOs\", \"it has rendered great services to agriculture\", \"it has increased productivity. \u00bb\n\n=== Conviction ===\nOn February 12, 2008, during the television show ''Ce soir ou jamais'', he said about [[Jean-Marie Le Pen|Jean-Marie Le Pen:]] \"We knew him as the white wolf, he was a bastard\", and added: \"he probably committed crimes, but I can't say it on the air\". On 28 May 2009, the Paris Court of Appeal found him guilty of insult (first sentence) and defamation (second sentence), and sentenced him to a suspended fine of \u20ac1,500 and \u20ac4,000 in damages<ref>''[[Lib\u00e9ration (journal)|Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 28 mai 2009 [http://www.liberation.fr/societe/0101570013-5500-euros-pour-avoir-traite-le-pen-de-salopard \u00ab 5500 euros pour avoir trait\u00e9 Le Pen de salopard \u00bb]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vincent, Jean-Didier}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:People from Libourne]]\n[[Category:French neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:French neurologists]]\n[[Category:French psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:French science writers]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Bordeaux faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Paris-Saclay faculty]]\n[[Category:CNRS research directors]]\n", "name_user": "FluentClothingCo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOn Down's syndrome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Didier_Vincent"}
{"title_page": "List of Edinburgh festivals", "text_new": "__NOTOC__\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:EdinburghNYE.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Edinburgh's Hogmanay|Hogmanay]] fireworks over Edinburgh]]\n[[File:The Pleasance Courtyard Festival venue, 2013.JPG|thumb|The [[Pleasance]] venue]]\n[[File:Edinburgh fringe royal mile street performance.jpg|thumb|[[Royal Mile]] street performance]]\n\nThis is a list of [[Arts festival|arts and cultural festivals]] regularly taking place in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].\n\nThe city has become known for its festivals since the establishment in 1947 of the [[Edinburgh International Festival]] and the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] which runs alongside it. The latter is the largest event of its kind in the world.\n\nThe term '''''Edinburgh Festival''''' is commonly used, but there is no single festival; the various festivals are put on by separate, unrelated organisations. However they are widely regarded as part of the same event, particularly the various festivals that take place simultaneously in August each year. The term ''Edinburgh Festival'' is often used to refer more specifically to the Fringe, being the largest of the festivals; or sometimes to the International Festival, being the original \"official\" arts festival. Within the industry, people refer to all the festivals collectively as the '''''Edinburgh Festivals''''' (plural).\n\n== The festivals ==\n[[File:Edinburgh Tattoo 2010 (4946272332).jpg|thumb|[[Royal Edinburgh Military Tattoo]], 2010]]\n[[File:Fringe Macbeth, 2013.JPG|thumb|Cast members publicising a Fringe production of Shakespeare's Macbeth]]\nListed in chronological order by 2018 start date, with year of foundation in brackets\n\n===April===\n* [[Dead by Dawn]] (1993)\n* [[Edinburgh International Science Festival]] (1988)*\n\n===Easter time===\n* [[Ceilidh Culture]] (1951)\n\n===May===\n* Edinburgh International Children's Festival (formerly the Imaginate Festival) (1990)*\n\n===June===\n* [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]] (1947)* <ref>[http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/news/view/1871/moving-times-at-eiff Moving times at EIFF]</ref>\n* [[Edinburgh Annuale]] (2004)\n\n===July===\n* [[Edinburgh International Magic Festival]] (2010)\n* Edinburgh Jazz and Blues Festival (1978)*\n\n===August===\n* [[Edinburgh Art Festival]] (2004)*\n* [[Edinburgh International Festival]] (1947)*\n* [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] (1947)* <ref>[http://www.edfringe.com/area.html?id=48 Fringe Facts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060127010255/http://www.edfringe.com/area.html?id=48 |date=27 January 2006 }}. edfringe: Official site of the Edinburgh Fringe Festival, 2005. Accessed 26 June 2005.</ref>\n* [[Royal Edinburgh Military Tattoo]] (1950)*\n* Just Festival (formerly the Festival of Spirituality and Peace) (2005)\n* [[Edinburgh International Book Festival]] (1983)*\n* [[Edinburgh Mela]] (1995)\n* [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]] (1976)\n\n===October===\n* [[Africa in Motion]] (2006)\n* Scottish International Storytelling Festival (1990)*\n* Festival of Politics (2005)\n*[[Terminal V]] (2017)\n\n===December===\n* [[Edinburgh's Hogmanay]] (1994)*\n\n===Uncertain dates===\n* [[Edinburgh People's Festival]] (2002, but claims heritage from earlier festival of same name 1951\u20131954)\n\n===Defunct festivals===\n* Edinburgh Interactive Festival (2003)\n* Edinburgh International Internet Festival (1999)\n* Edinburgh Swing Festival (2006)\n* [[Ifest|iFest]] (2007) \u2014 the Internet Festival and Conference\n* [[West Port Book Festival]] (2008) &ndash; a free book festival involving secondhand bookshops in the [[West Port, Edinburgh|West Port]] area\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.edinburghfestivalcity.com/ Edinburgh Festival City]\n* [http://www.edinburghfestivalcity.com Edinburgh Festivals] a guide to the festivals that take place in Edinburgh