tablished_date       = 4th Century BC\n|established_title2     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2      =\n|established_title3     =  <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date3      =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref                =Metric <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =\n|area_land_km2            = 58\n|area_water_km2           =\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_land_sq_mi          =\n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_urban_sq_mi         =\n|area_metro_km2           = 108\n|area_metro_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        =\n|area_blank1_km2          =\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2004 census\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 383,786<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.cbssyr.org/new%20web%20site/General_census/census_2004/NH/TAB06-1-2004.htm Latakia city population] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317032446/http://www.cbssyr.org/new%20web%20site/General_census/census_2004/NH/TAB06-1-2004.htm |date=2013-03-17 }}</ref>\n|population_density_km2         =\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n|population_metro               = 424,392 \n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   =\n|population_density_urban_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_blank2_title        =Religions\n|population_blank2              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =\n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n|population_demonym        = {{lang-ar|\u0644\u0627\u0630\u0642\u0627\u0646\u064a|L\u0101dhqani}}\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|35|31|N|35|47|E|region:SY|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 11\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = 41\n|geocode                = C3480\n|blank_name             = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank_info             = [[Mediterranean climate#Hot-summer Mediterranean climate|Csa]]\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = [http://www.esyria.sy/elatakia/ eLatakia]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Latakia''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0630\u0650\u0642\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0629}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|al-L\u0101dhiq\u012byah}}''; <small> [[Syrian Arabic|Syrian]] pronunciation:</small> {{IPA-ar|el.la\u02d0d\u02c8\u0294\u026ajje, -la\u02d0\u00f0\u02c8q\u026ajja|}}) is the principal port city of [[Syria]], as well as the capital of the [[Latakia Governorate]]. Historically, it has also been known as '''[[Laodicea in Syria]]''' or '''Laodicea ad Mare'''.  In addition to serving as a port, the city is a manufacturing center for surrounding agricultural towns and villages. According to the 2004 official census, the population of the city is 383,786,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssyr.org/new%20web%20site/General_census/census_2004/NH/TAB06-1-2004.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317032446/http://www.cbssyr.org/new%20web%20site/General_census/census_2004/NH/TAB06-1-2004.htm |archivedate=2013-03-17 }}</ref><ref name=gazetteer>City population size reported at {{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-202&srt=pnan&col=adhoq&msz=1500&va=&pt=a |title=World-Gazetteer.com |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130210085405/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-202&srt=pnan&col=adhoq&msz=1500&va=&pt=a |archivedate=2013-02-10 |url-status=dead }} and similarly reported by [http://www.citypopulation.de/Syria.html CityPopulation.de].</ref> Its population greatly increased as a result of the ongoing [[Syrian Civil War]] due to the influx of refugees from rebel and terrorist held areas. It is the 4th-largest city in Syria after [[Aleppo]], [[Damascus]] and [[Homs]], and it borders [[Tartus]] to the south, [[Hama]] to the east, and [[Idlib]] to the north while [[Cape Apostolos Andreas]], the most north-eastern tip of [[Cyprus]] is about {{convert|68|mi}} away.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-09/22/content_6774726.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011035834/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-09/22/content_6774726.htm |archive-date=2016-10-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the site has been inhabited since the 2nd millennium BC, the city was founded in the 4th century BC under the rule of the [[Seleucid empire]]. Latakia was subsequently ruled by the [[Roman empire|Romans]], then the [[Ummayad]]s and [[Abbasid]]s in the 8th\u201310th centuries of the Christian era. Under their rule, the [[Byzantine empire|Byzantines]] frequently attacked the city, periodically recapturing it before losing it again to the Arabs, particularly the [[Fatimid]]s. Afterward, Latakia was ruled successively by the [[Seljuk Turks]], [[Crusades|Crusaders]], [[Ayyubid]]s, [[Mamluk]]s, and the [[Ottoman empire|Ottomans]]. Following [[World War I]], Latakia was assigned to the [[French mandate of Syria]], in which it served as the capital of the autonomous territory of the [[Alawite]]s. This autonomous territory became the [[Alawite State]] in 1922, proclaiming its independence a number of times until reintegrating into Syria in 1944.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n==Etymology==\n{{Distinguish|Laodicea ad Lycum}}\nLike many [[Seleucid Empire|Seleucid]] cities, Latakia was named after a member of the ruling dynasty.<ref name=\"le Strange380\"/> First named ''Laodikeia on the Coast'' ({{Lang-el|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u1f21 \u03a0\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2}}) by [[Seleucus I Nicator]] in honor of his mother, [[Laodice of Macedonia|Laodice]]. In [[Latin]], its name became ''Laodicea ad Mare''. The original name survives in its [[Arabic language|Arabic]] form as ''al-Ladhiqiyyah'' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0630\u0642\u064a\u0629}}), from which the [[French language|French]] ''Lattaqui\u00e9'' and [[English language|English]] ''Latakia'' or ''Lattakia'' derive.<ref name=\"le Strange380\">le Strange, 1890, p.380.</ref><ref name=\"Ball\">Ball, 2000, p.157</ref> To the Ottomans, it was known as Lazkiye.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Latakia}}\n\n===Ancient settlement and founding===\nThe location of Latakia, the '''Ras Ziyarah''' [[promontory]],<ref>\"Ras Ziyarah\", literally, \"Cape of Visitation ([[Ziyarah]])\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=National Geospatial-intelligence Agency|title=Prostar Sailing Directions 2005 Eastern Mediterranean Enroute|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elzyK_4aWPUC&pg=PA38&dq=%22Ras+Ziyarah%22#v=onepage|year=2005|publisher=ProStar Publications|page=38|isbn=9781577856573}}</ref> has a long history of occupation. The [[Phoenicia]]n city of Ramitha was located here.<ref>{{cite book |last1=La Boda |first1=Sharon |title=International Dictionary of Historical Places: Middle East and Africa |date=1994 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=9781315073842 |edition=1st |page=451 |doi=10.4324/9781315073842 }}</ref> [[Stephanus of Byzantium]] writes that the city was named Ramitha ({{lang-grc|\u1fec\u03ac\u03bc\u03b9\u03b8\u03b1}}), then ''Leuk\u00ea Akt\u00ea'' (\"white coast\") ({{lang-grc|\u039b\u03b5\u03c5\u03ba\u1f74 \u1f00\u03ba\u03c4\u03ae}}) and later Laodicea ({{lang-grc|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}).<ref>[https://topostext.org/work/241#L411.7 Stephanus of Byzantium, Ethnica, \u00a7L411.7]</ref>\n\nThe city was described in [[Strabo]]'s ''[[Geographica]]'':<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Strabo\n  | authorlink = Strabo\n  | title = The Geography of Strabo\n  | publisher =\n  | url=https://books.google.com/?id=0cZfAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Strabo+geography\n  | year =1857| page= 164\n  | isbn = 978-0-521-85306-4}}</ref>\n{{bquote|\nIt is a city most beautifully built, has a good harbour, and has territory which, besides its other good crops, abounds in wine. Now this city furnishes the most of the wine to the Alexandreians, since the whole of the mountain that lies above the city and is possessed by it is covered with vines almost as far as the summits. And while the summits are at a considerable distance from L\u0101\u014fd\u012dc\u1e17a, sloping up gently and gradually from it, they tower above Apameia, extending up to a perpendicular height.}}\n\n===Roman rule===\n{{Main|Laodicea in Syria}}\n[[File:Arch latakia1.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|[[Latakia Tetraporticus]], built by [[Septimius Severus]] in AD 193.]]\n[[Pompey the Great]] conquered the city along with most of Syria in the 1st century BC, and [[Julius Caesar]] declared the city a \"free polis.\" The Roman emperor Septimius Severus rewarded the city with the title of \"Metropolis\" in the 2nd century AD, exempted it of the empire's taxation, fortified the city, made it for a few years the capital of [[Roman Syria]] and also built the city's famed Tetraporticus around the same time. Some Roman merchants moved to live in the city under [[Augustus]], but the city was always culturally \"Greek\" influenced. Subsequently, a [[Roman road]] was built from southern [[Anatolia]] toward [[Berytus]] and Damascus, that greatly improved the commerce through the port of Laodicea.\n\nThe heretic [[Apollinaris of Laodicea|Apollinarius]] was bishop of L\u0101\u014fd\u012dc\u1e17a in the 4th century. The city minted coins from an early date, but decreasing in importance after the cities of Alexandria and Antioch flourished in coin minting and overshadowed other cities.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe city was also famed for its wine produced around the port's hills which were exported to all the empire.\n\nDuring the split of the [[Roman Empire]], it belonged to the [[Eastern Roman Empire]]. An earthquake damaged the city in 494, but the city was later reconstructed by Justinian I and made the capital of the [[Theodorias (province)|Eastern Roman province of Theodorias]] from 528 AD until Muslim conquest around 637 AD.\n[[File:Bakhos temple latakia.jpg|alt=Temple of Bacchus|thumb|Ruins of the Temple of Bacchus in Latakia]]\n\n===Early Islamic era===\nAll of Syria, including the Roman province of Theodorias and its capital, [[Siege of Latakia (Laodicea) (636)|Laodicea fell]] into Muslim rule after its attacked by a caliphate general, named [['Ubadah ibn al-Samit]] during the [[Muslim conquest of Syria]] in the 7th century. The city was renamed al-L\u0101dhiq\u012byah (\u0627\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0630\u0650\u0642\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0629) and switched rule from the [[Rashidun Caliphate]], to the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] and finally to the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in a span of 9 centuries, attached to the large province of [[Bilad Al-Sham]] (Greater Syria). Arab geographer, [[Al-Muqaddasi]] (d. 991), mentions al-L\u0101dhiq\u012byah as belonging to the district of Hims ([[Homs, Syria|Homs]]).<ref>Al-Muqaddasi, ''The Best Divisions for Knowledge of the Regions'' (Being a translation of \"Ahsan al-Taqasim fi Ma\u02bfrifat al-Aqalim\"), Reading 1994, p. 141 {{ISBN|1-873938-14-4}}</ref>\n\n===Crusader, Ayyubid, and Mamluk rule===\n\n[[File:Lattakia,CatholicChurch.jpg|thumb|upright|The Latin Church of Latakia, also known as the [[Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus (Latakia)|Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus]]]]\nThe [[Mardaites]] controlled the region from to [[Jebel Aqra]] to northern [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], including Latakia in 705. However, they later withdrew from the city after an agreement with the Umayyad caliph [[Al-Walid I]]. Afterwards, the Mardaites sacked it in 719, but it was rebuilt by [[Umar II]]. The city lost its importance due its location on the border between the [[Byzantine Empire]] and the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] from 750 to 968. The Byzantine Empire recaptured the city in 970 by [[John I Tzimiskes]], but it was lost to the [[Fatimids]] in 980. The [[Banu Munqidh]] managed to control the city until they were succeeded by the [[Seljuks]] during the reign of [[Malik-Shah I]], after their wars against the [[Buyid dynasty]] in 1086, despite a brief Byzantine control in 1074. Later on, [[Guynemer of Boulogne]] raided the city on 19 August 1097, with 28 ships coming from [[Cyprus]] during the [[First Crusade]]. In 1098, [[Raymond IV, Count of Toulouse|Raymond of Saint-Gilles]] captured the city, with the Byzantine fleet presence; hence, the city became contested between the crusaders and the Byzantines who controlled Latakia and [[Baniyas]] in the meantime.{{sfn|La Boda|1994|p=453}}\n\nAfter failed efforts by [[Bohemond I of Antioch]] to capture Latakia from the Byzantine Empire in 1099, and a brief control of the [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] fleet in 1101, the city was taken in 1103 by forces under the command of [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred of Hauteville]], a veteran of the First Crusade and acting regent of the [[Principality of Antioch]].<ref>Thomas Asbridge, The Crusades: The War for the Holy Land, (London: Simon & Schuster, 2010), pp.137\u2013138.</ref> Following the defeat of Antiochene forces at the [[Battle of Harran]] in 1104, the city was reoccupied by the Byzantines led by Admiral [[Cantacuzenus]], however they would again lose the city. Despite a treaty in 1108 with Bohemond promising to return Latakia to the Empire by 1110 it was firmly under the control of the Principality of Antioch,<ref>Thomas Asbridge, The Crusades: The War for the Holy Land, (London: Simon & Schuster, 2010), pp.137\u2013144.</ref> as it was called \"La Liche\". In 1126, the cities of Latakia and [[Jabala]] were the dowry of Princess [[Alice of Antioch|Alice]], daughter of King [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem]], who later donated a house in Latakia to the [[Knights Hospitaller]], which became their main base in the region. In April 1136, the city was sacked by Emir Sawar ibn Aytakin, governor of [[Aleppo]], then it was struck by the [[1157 Hama earthquake|1157 Hama earthquake]] and the [[1170 Syria earthquake]].{{sfn|La Boda|1994|p=453}} \n\nThis situation remained the same with the city serving as the primary port for the Principality until after the loss of Antioch itself to the [[Ayyubids]], under the rule of [[Saladin]] on 23 July 1188. By 1260, the crusaders recaptured the city, until they were defeated by the [[Mamluks]] of [[Qalawun]],<ref>Thomas Asbridge, The Crusades: The War for the Holy Land, (London: Simon & Schuster, 2010), p.637.</ref> on 20 April 1287.\n\nIn circa 1300, Arab geographer al-Dimashqi noted that Latakia had no running water and that trees were scarce, but the city's port was \"a wonderful harbor... full of large ships\".<ref>al-Dimashqi quoted in le Strange, 1890, p.491.</ref> In 1332, the Moroccan traveller [[Ibn Battuta]] visited Latakia in his journeys.<ref>The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century By Ross E. Dunn, University of California Press. pp.137.</ref>\n\nDuring the late 14th and 15th century, [[Republic of Venice|Venetians]] had a consul in Latakia, due to the trade of cotton and silk from Persia.{{sfn|Ashtor|2014|p=121}} The city which was in despair was rebuilt after a visit by [[Qaitbay]] in 1477.\n\n===Ottoman rule===\n[[File:Museum of Latakia, Syria.jpg|thumb|left|The [[National Museum of Latakia]], a previous Ottoman era [[Khan (inn)|khan]]]]\nLatakia became under the Ottoman control after the [[Battle of Marj Dabiq]] in 1516.\n\nIn 1888, when [[Wilaya]]t Beirut was established, Latakia became its northernmost town.<ref>Dumper, 2007, p.84</ref>\n\nIn the Ottoman period{{when|date=September 2015}}, the region of Latakia became predominantly [[Alawites|Alawi]]. The [[Syrian Turkmen|Turkmen]] also consisted a significant minority. The city itself, however, contained significant numbers of [[Sunni]] and Christian inhabitants. The landlords in the countryside tended to be Sunni and Orthodox Christians, while the peasants were mostly Alawi. Like the [[Druze]]s, who also had a special status before the end of World War I, the Alawis had a strained relationship with the Ottoman overlords. In fact, they were not even given the status of [[millet (Ottoman Empire)|millet]], although they enjoyed relative autonomy.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\">Rabinovich, 1979, p.694</ref>\n\n===French Mandate period===\n{{Main|Alawite State}}\n[[File:LatakiaJulesJammalSchool.jpg|thumb|One of the oldest schools in Latakia was previous mandatory-era barracks, and later school. It was subsequently named after [[Jules Jammal]] and known ever since as the 'Jules Jammal School']]\nIn 1920, Latakia fell under the French mandate, under which the Alawite State was established. The state was named after the locally-dominant Alawites, and became a French [[mandate territory]] after World War&nbsp;I.<ref name = \"blag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Syria.html#Alawite+Territory|title=Syria|first=Ben|last=Cahoon|date=|website=worldstatesmen.org|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> The [[French Mandate]] from the [[League of Nations]] began in 1920.<ref>Provence, Michael. \"The Great Syrian Revolt and the Rise of Arab Nationalism.\" Austin: [[University of Texas Press]], 2005.</ref> The creation of the Alawite State as well as the other states of Syria under the French Mandate and the division it created was because the French hoped to focus on fragmenting the various groups in the region, so that the local population would not focus on the larger nationalist movement seeking to end colonial rule. Whatsoever, the French justified the creation of the Alawite state by citing the \"backwardness\" of the mountain-dwellers, religiously distinct from the surrounding Sunni population, and claimed that the division intended to protect the Alawi people from more-powerful majorities.<ref name= \"L\">Longrigg, Stephen Hemsley. \"Syria and Lebanon Under French Mandate.\" London: Oxford University Press, 1958.</ref>\n[[File:Stamp Alaouites 1926 10pi air.jpg|thumb|left|A 10-piastre stamp of Syria used in the Alawite State]]\nThe division the French administration created in Syria didn't stop Alawites such as [[Sheikh Saleh al-Ali]], who led the [[Syrian Revolt of 1919]], to continue and protest French rule. Saleh al-Ali coordinated with the leaders of other anti-French revolts in the country, including the revolt of [[Ibrahim Hananu]] in the Aleppo countryside and [[Subhi Barakat]]'s revolt in Antioch, but Saleh al-Ali's revolt was put down in 1921, and a French court-martial in Latakia sentenced Shaykh Saleh to death in absentia, and offered a reward of 100,000 francs for information on his whereabouts. After the French gave up trying to capturing Shaykh Saleh, a pardon was issued by General [[Henri Gouraud (general)|Henri Gouraud]].\n\nThe state became part of the Syrian Federation in 1922, but left the federation again in 1924. In 1930 the Alawite State was renamed as the Government of Latakia, the only concession by the French to Arab nationalists until 1936. On 3 December 1936 (becoming effective in 1937), the Alawite state was re-incorporated into Syria as a concession by the French to the [[National Bloc (Syria)|Nationalist Bloc]] (the ruling party of the semi-autonomous Syrian government).<ref>Shambrook, Peter A. \"French Imperialism in Syria, 1927\u20131936.\" Reading: Ithaca Press, 1998.</ref>\n\nThere was a great deal of Alawite separatist sentiment in the region, but their political views could not be coordinated into a unified voice. There was also a great deal of factionalism amongst the Alawite tribes, and the Alawite State was incorporated into Syria with little organised resistance.\n\nIn 1942, the Latakia and Druze regions were returned to Syrian control, and by 1946, the French completely left Syria and a new independent government was created.\n\n===Modern era===\n[[File:Lattakia 1970.jpg|thumb|Latakia in 1970.]]\nAll but a few classical buildings have been destroyed, often by earthquakes; those remaining include a Roman triumphal arch and [[Corinthian column]]s known as the Colonnade of [[Dionysus|Bacchus]].<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> However, important remains from the city at Roman and Hellenistic periods including full body statues, Roman funerary art, and column capitals that once belonged to the ancient city, are found in its national museum.\n\nAn extensive port project was proposed in 1948, and construction work began on the [[Port of Latakia]] in 1950, aided by a [[United States dollar|US$]]6&nbsp;million loan from [[Saudi Arabia]]. By 1951, the first stage of the construction was completed, and the port handled an increasing amount of Syria's overseas trade.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nIn August 1957, 4,000 Egyptian troops landed in Latakia under orders from [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] after [[Turkish army|Turkish troops]] massed along the border with Syria, accusing it of harboring [[Communist Party of Turkey (historical)|Turkish Communists]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Podeh|1999|pp=43}}</ref>\n\nA major highway linked Latakia with Aleppo and the [[Euphrates]] valley in 1968 and was supplemented by the completion of a railway line to Homs. The port became even more important after 1975, due to the troubled situation in Lebanon and the loss of Beirut and Tripoli as ports.<ref name=\"Ring5\">Ring, 1994, p.455</ref>\n\nIn 1973, during the [[Yom Kippur War|October War]] (Yom Kippur War), the naval [[Battle of Latakia]] between [[Israel]] and Syria was fought just offshore from Latakia. The battle was the first to be fought using [[missile]]s and [[electronic countermeasures|ECM]] (electronic countermeasures).<ref>{{Citation|last=Betts|first=Richard K.|authorlink=Richard K. Betts|title=Cruise Missile: Technology, Strategy and Politics|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|year=1982|page=381|isbn=978-0-8157-0931-2 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the city hosted the [[1987 Mediterranean Games|tenth round]] of the [[Mediterranean Games]], with the opening ceremony hosted by [[Hafez al-Assad]] in the [[Latakia Sports City]], a sports complex designed specifically to host the games, with the [[Latakia Sports City Stadium]] serving as the main venue for the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esyria.sy/elatakia/index.php?p=stories&category=places&filename=200808031135013|title=\u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0630\u0642\u064a\u0629 \u2013 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \"\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u062f\" \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629...\u0645\u062a\u0646\u0641\u0633 \u0648\u0627\u0633\u0639 \u0644\u0623\u0647\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0648\u0632\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647\u0645|author=|date=|website=esyria.sy|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the city's population reached 303,000, with that number significantly rising to 383,786 in 2004.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Although population assessment in recent years have become difficult due to the ongoing civil war, the city's population is estimated to have rose drastically due to the influx of refugees from the cities of Aleppo, Idlib and other cities held by rebels and extremist terrorists which have been affected by the ongoing war.\n\n====Syrian Civil War====\n{{anchor|civilwar}}\nDuring the Syrian Civil War, Latakia had been a site of [[demonstration (people)|protest activity]] since March 2011. The Syrian government claimed 12 were killed there in clashes in late March,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nowlebanon.com/NewsArchiveDetails.aspx?ID=254868|agency=NOW Lebanon|date=27 March 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011|title=Twelve killed in Saturday's Latakia protests, presidential adviser says|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814080339/http://www.nowlebanon.com/NewsArchiveDetails.aspx?ID=254868|archive-date=14 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> leading to the deployment of the military to restrict movement into and out of the city. Hundreds of Syrians were reportedly arrested, and by late July, activists in Latakia were telling foreign media they feared a more violent crackdown was coming. Protests continued despite the increased security presence and arrests. Several civilians were allegedly killed in confrontations with security officers during this early period of the siege.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/babylonbeyond/2011/07/syria-protesters-in-lattakia-brave-security-forces.html|agency=The Los Angeles Times|date=25 July 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011|title=SYRIA: Protesters in Lattakia brave security forces }}</ref> On 13 August 2011, the [[Syrian Army]] and [[Syrian Navy]] [[Siege of Latakia|launched an operation]] where more than 20 tanks and [[armoured personnel carrier|APCs]] rolled into the Alawi stronghold.<ref name=\"enters\">{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/08/2011813103322136544.html|date=13 August 2011|accessdate=13 August 2011|agency=Al Jazeera English|title=Syrian army 'enters western coastal city'}}</ref> The city was also attacked by the Syrian army on the 14 August 2011. Activists claimed that 25 people died during the attack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/08/201181475734965763.html |title=Syrian 'warships shell port city of Latakia' |date=14 August 2011 <!-- 14:32  --> |publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n[[File:Russian military aircraft at Latakia, Syria (1).jpg|thumb|A [[Russia]]n military aircraft in [[Khmeimim Air Base]], one of Russia's main bases of operation in Syria]]\nLatakia is the home of Russia's largest foreign electronic eavesdropping facility.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/dec/23/syria-crisis-russian-military-presence Russian military presence in Syria poses challenge to US-led intervention] The Guardian, 2012-12-23.</ref> [[Khmeimim Air Base]] is an airbase near Latakia converted to use by the [[Russian military]] in 2015. On 24 November 2015, Turkish forces [[2015 Russian Sukhoi Su-24 shootdown|shot down a Russian fighter plane]] over Latakia. One pilot was killed and the other rescued by Syrian military and brought to Khmeimim.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey shoots down Russian warplane on Syria border|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-mid1dle-east-34907983|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=ru:\u0421\u041c\u0418: \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0442 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0421\u0443-24 \u0431\u044b\u043b \u044d\u0432\u0430\u043a\u0443\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0441\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/social/news/2015/11/25/n_7930979.shtml|accessdate=25 November 2015|work=Gazeta.ru|trans-title=Media: Second pilot of downed Su-24 was evacuated by Syrian military|language=ru|date=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe city has been relatively calm and secure during the civil war, with electricity and water returning as of 2017, and Russian air force constantly patrolling the city and surrounding localities.\n\nIn November 2016, al-Manara university, a private university, was founded in the city under the patronage of the Syrian [[Prime Minister]], [[Imad Khamis]] and Syrian [[First Lady]] [[Asma al-Assad]].<ref name=\"manarauniopened\"/> Its faculties as of 2017 include Pharmacy and Health, Engineering and Business.<ref name=\"manarauni\"/>\n\nIn September 2017, following the [[Syrian Arab Army]]'s lift of [[ISIL]]'s 3 year long siege over the city of [[Deir ez-Zor]] and the entire liberation of the city and surrounding villages in a [[Central Syria campaign (2017)|successful offensive]], 125 tons of [[Citrus fruit|citrus]] were sent in convoys from Latakia as a gift to the people of the city to celebrate the breaking of the devastating siege, with many more batches to be sent to the surrounding localities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sana.sy/en/?p=119650 |title= 125 Tons of Citrus sent from Lattakia to the people of Deir ez-Zor \u2013 Syrian Arab News Agency |publisher=Syrian Arab News Agency |date=25 November 2017 |accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nRussian president [[Vladimir Putin]], accompanied by his Syrian counterpart [[Bashar al-Assad]] visited the [[Khmeimim airbase]], Russia's main military base in Syria, located just outside Latakia near [[Jableh]] on 11 December 2017.<ref>{{citation |work=The Guardian |date=11 December 2017 |title=Vladimir Putin makes triumphant visit to Syria airbase |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/11/vladimir-putin-visit-to-syria-airbase-bashir-al-assad}}</ref> Declaring victory over ISIL, and announcing a partial military withdrawal from Syria, but with continuing Russian presence, as the Khmeimim airbase and the [[Russian naval facility in Tartus]] would still be operated by Russian forces.<ref>{{citation|title=On visit to Syria, Putin lauds victory over ISIS and announces withdrawals|date=11 December 2017|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/putin-makes-first-visit-to-syria-lauds-victory-over-isis-and-announces-withdrawals/2017/12/11/f75389de-de61-11e7-8679-a9728984779c_story.html|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn celebration of [[Christmas]] and the New Year, forces from the Khmeimim-based Russian Coordination Center distributed school bags, stationery and milk to the children of fallen soldiers in the Ghassan Zwan School and to the children of the Russian community in Latakia and the surrounding countryside.<ref>{{citation |work=Syrian Arab News Agency |date=29 December 2017 |title= School supplies and milk distributed to martyrs' children and Russian community in Lattakia \u2013 Syrian Arab News Agency|url= https://sana.sy/en/?p=122876}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Slinfah.png|thumb|[[Slinfah]]]]\nLatakia is located {{convert|348|km|mi}} north-west of Damascus, {{convert|186|km|mi}} south-west from Aleppo, {{convert|186|km|mi}} north-west of Homs, and {{convert|90|km|mi}} north of Tartus.<ref name=\"Homsonline\">{{Citation|url=http://www.homsonline.com/EN/Syria/Distance.htm|publisher=HomsOnline|title=Distance Between Main Syrian Cities|accessdate=2009-02-26|date=2008-05-16}}</ref> Nearby towns and villages include [[Kasab, Syria|Kasab]] to the north, [[Al-Haffah]], Slinfah and [[Qardaha]] to the east in the [[Syrian Coastal Mountain Range|Coastal Mountain Range]], and Jableh and [[Baniyas]] to the south.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nLatakia is the capital of the Latakia Governorate, in western Syria, bordering Turkey to the north. The governorate has a reported area of either {{convert|2297|km2|sqmi}}<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Syria.html|title=Syria|publisher=citypopulation.de|year=2008|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref> or {{convert|2437|km2|sqmi}}.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.statoids.com/usy.html|title=Provinces of Syria|publisher=Statoids|year=2005|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref> Latakia is the administrative centre of the [[Latakia District]] that occupies the northern portion of th Latakia Governorate.\n\n[[Nahr al-Kabir al-Shamali]] flows into the [[Mediterranean Sea]] south of Latakia.\n\n===Climate===\nUnder [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen's climate classification]], Latakia has a [[hot-summer Mediterranean climate]] (''Csa'').<ref>http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.pdf</ref> Latakia's wettest months are December and January, where average precipitation is around 160 mm. The city's driest month, July, only has on average about {{convert|1|mm}} of rain, despite being rather humid. Average high temperatures in the city range from around {{convert|16|C}} in January to around {{convert|30|C}} in August. Latakia on average receives around {{convert|760|mm}} of rainfall annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Latakia (1961\u20131990, extremes 1928\u2013present)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 24.4\n|Feb record high C = 26.3\n|Mar record high C = 32.6\n|Apr record high C = 35.6\n|May record high C = 38.8\n|Jun record high C = 38.4\n|Jul record high C = 36.2\n|Aug record high C = 38.4\n|Sep record high C = 38.2\n|Oct record high C = 39.0\n|Nov record high C = 32.6\n|Dec record high C = 28.0\n|year record high C = 39.0\n|Jan high C = 15.4\n|Feb high C = 16.4\n|Mar high C = 18.3\n|Apr high C = 21.5\n|May high C = 24.1\n|Jun high C = 25.8\n|Jul high C = 28.8\n|Aug high C = 29.6\n|Sep high C = 29.0\n|Oct high C = 26.3\n|Nov high C = 21.9\n|Dec high C = 17.6\n|year high C = 22.9\n|Jan mean C = 11.6\n|Feb mean C = 12.6\n|Mar mean C = 14.8\n|Apr mean C = 17.8\n|May mean C = 20.7\n|Jun mean C = 23.8\n|Jul mean C = 26.3\n|Aug mean C = 27.0\n|Sep mean C = 25.6\n|Oct mean C = 22.3\n|Nov mean C = 17.5\n|Dec mean C = 13.3\n|year mean C = 19.4\n|Jan low C = 8.4\n|Feb low C = 9.1\n|Mar low C = 11.0\n|Apr low C = 14.0\n|May low C = 17.0\n|Jun low C = 20.7\n|Jul low C = 23.7\n|Aug low C = 24.3\n|Sep low C = 21.9\n|Oct low C = 18.2\n|Nov low C = 13.8\n|Dec low C = 10.1\n|year low C = 16.0\n|Jan record low C = -1.6\n|Feb record low C = -0.5\n|Mar record low C = -0.6\n|Apr record low C = 3.9\n|May record low C = 10.6\n|Jun recor