rt cities in Asia]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean port cities and towns in Syria]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 2nd millennium BC]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Syria]]\n", "name_user": "119.195.164.105", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCrusader, Ayyubid, and Mamluk rule:uncertainty !)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latakia"}
{"title_page": "Sasuke Uchiha", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Uchiha|other characters named Uchiha|List of Naruto characters}}{{Hatnote|For other uses of the word \u2018Sasuke\u2019, check [[Sasuke (disambiguation)]].}}{{short description|Fictional character from \"Naruto\".}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox animanga character\n| name       = Jordan young is gay\n| series     = [[Naruto]], [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]\n| image      = SasukeKishimoto.jpg\n| caption    = Sasuke Uchiha as seen in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] (right), [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]] (left), and the finale as well as the [[Boruto: Naruto the Movie|''Boruto'' film]] and [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|series]] (middle)\n| alt        = Three forms of a black-haired fictional character showing his teenage self (left), his adult self (middle), and his child self (right)  \n| first      = ''Naruto'' chapter 3: Enter Sasuke! (1999)\n| creator    = [[Masashi Kishimoto]]\n| voiced by  = '''Japanese'''<br> [[Noriaki Sugiyama]]<br />'''English''' <br />[[Yuri Lowenthal]]\n| paux1      = <!-- Fugaku and Mikoto are not notable. Do not add them. --> [[Itachi Uchiha]] (brother, deceased)<br>[[Sakura Haruno|Sakura Uchiha]] (wife)\n[[Sarada Uchiha]] (daughter)\n| paux1 name = Notable relatives\n| paux2      = Genin in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]]<br> Missing-Nin in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part II)|Part II]]\n| paux2 name = Ninja rank\n| paux3      = [[List of Naruto characters#Team 7|Team 7]] ([[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]])<br>[[List of Naruto characters#Taka|Taka]] ([[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]])\n| paux3 name = Ninja team\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Sasuke Uchiha'''|\u3046\u3061\u306f \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1|Uchiha Sasuke|lead=yes}} ({{IPAc-en|'|s|\u0251\u02d0|s|k|e\u026a|}}) is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in the ''[[Naruto]]'' [[manga]] and [[anime]] franchise created by [[Masashi Kishimoto]]. Sasuke belongs to the Uchiha clan, a notorious [[ninja]] family, and one of the most powerful, allied with {{nihongo|Konohagakure|\u6728\u30ce\u8449\u96a0\u308c\u306e\u91cc||English version: \"Hidden Leaf Village\"}}. Most of its members were massacred by Sasuke's older brother, [[Itachi Uchiha]], before the series began, leaving Sasuke one of the few living. Despite becoming empathetic toward his teammates [[Naruto Uzumaki]] and [[Sakura Haruno]], Sasuke's feelings of powerlessness force him to abandon his friends and his home in his quest to become stronger, and to find [[Orochimaru (Naruto)|Orochimaru]]. Sasuke appears in several of the series' [[Naruto#Films|animated feature films]] and related media, including [[List of Naruto video games|video games]], [[Naruto#Original video animations|original video animations]] ([[original video animations|OVAs]]), and ''[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2015) and its manga [[sequel]], ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' (2016), in which he is depicted as a [[vigilante]] supporting his village and a mentor to Naruto's son [[Boruto Uzumaki]].\n\nKishimoto conceived Sasuke as a rival of the series' title character Naruto Uzumaki. Despite Sasuke's dark [[character arc|character development]] later in the story, Kishimoto avoided portraying him as a villain; he found designing the character challenging and had difficulty creating a suitable look for him. Nonetheless, Kishimoto has grown to enjoy drawing him. In the manga's animated adaptations, Sasuke was voiced by [[Noriaki Sugiyama]] in Japanese and [[Yuri Lowenthal]] in English.\n\nSasuke's character has received mixed responses from anime and manga publications. His impressive fighting skills, plot contribution, and rivalry with Naruto Uzumaki received some praise, but he was criticized as a stereotypical rival in the mold of similar characters from other [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] and as exhibiting a cold personality. Nevertheless, Sasuke's characterization in latter parts of the story and more mature personality in the ''Boruto'' sequels earned further positive comments. Sasuke has also placed highly in ''Naruto'' reader popularity polls and has also been the subject of studies by scholars. Character-based merchandise, including [[action figure]]s and [[Keychain|key chains]], has been released.\n\n=={{anchor|Creation and conception}}Creation==\n===Development===\n[[Manga]] artist [[Masashi Kishimoto]] did not include Sasuke Uchiha in his original concept for the ''[[Naruto]]'' series, a story revolving around the character [[Naruto Uzumaki]]. Discussing the series' future, his editor, Kosuke Yahagi, advised him to add a rival character for the [[protagonist]] Naruto and he created Sasuke.<ref>{{cite book|issue=April 2007|year=2007|title=Shonen Jump|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|page=366|issn=1545-7818|title-link=Shonen Jump (magazine)}}</ref> The character's first name came from [[Sanpei Shirato]]'s manga ''Sasuke'' and [[Sarutobi Sasuke]], a fictional [[ninja]] character in Japanese children's stories.<ref name=\"sarutobi\">{{cite journal|date=August 2007|title=Interview: Tracking Down the Source|journal=Shonen Jump Naruto Collector 3|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> To introduce Sasuke, Kishimoto wrote a chapter that was set before the formation of his ninja squad, [[List of Naruto characters#Team 7|Team 7]]. The idea was scrapped; Yahagi told Kishimoto to focus the series' first two chapters on introducing Naruto instead and the focus on Sasuke and the rest of the supporting characters were shown in the next chapters for the first time.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Jump Square]]|title=Naruto: The Beginning|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|issue=12\u201314|date=December 2014|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015[\u79d8\u4f1d\u00b7\u7686\u306e\u66f8]\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret \u00b7 Everyone's Book Official Premium Fan|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|date=December 4, 2009|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|isbn=978-4-08-874834-4|series=[[Naruto]]|page=190|language=Japanese|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> \n\nKishimoto had read a variety of manga to obtain ideas for the creation of an effective rivalry between two characters, which he incorporated into Naruto and Sasuke's relationship. He was also inspired by his relationship with his twin brother, [[Seishi Kishimoto]]; since childhood, Masashi had worried about Seishi when he faced failure and had tried to help him.<ref name=\"finale\">{{cite magazine|magazine=Entermix|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]|issue=November 2014|year=2014|language=Japanese|title=\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8 \u672c\u5f53\u306b\u7d42\u308f\u3063\u3061\u3083\u3046\u306e?|trans-title=Naruto Is it really going to end?|page=70|asin=B01LEPKJ28}}</ref> To contrast Sasuke with Naruto, Kishimoto made him less emotional and depicted him as a \"cool genius\"; he felt he had created an ideal rivalry in the pair,<ref>{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=140|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> and when one character progressed he ensured the other did as well.<ref name=wsja/> Kishimoto wanted Naruto and Sasuke to seem like brothers and rivals, building on a mutual experience of childhood loneliness. Although Sasuke does not regard Naruto as a worthy opponent at first, he is surprised by Naruto's [[character arc|growth]] and becomes fiercely competitive. In the [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] finale, their rivalry leads to a fight and they grow further apart. Kishimoto said he did not want Sasuke to recognize Naruto as an equal until later in [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]].<ref name=\"Kizuna\">{{cite book|title=Naruto\uff0d\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\uff0d\u540d\u8a00\u96c6\u3000\u7d46\uff0dKizuna\uff0d\u3000\u5929\u30ce\u5dfb|trans-title=Naruto Bonds: The Words That React|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|year=2013|isbn=978-4-08-720681-4|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|pages=188\u2013195|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref>\n\nWhen plot developments made Sasuke one of the story's [[antagonist]]s, Kishimoto called him and Naruto [[yin and yang]] because of their differences and complementary natures.<ref name=wsja>{{cite journal|date=February 2012|title=Interview with Masashi Kishimoto (Creator of Naruto)|journal=[[Weekly Shonen Jump Alpha]]|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|issue=2\u201306\u201312|pages=120\u2013123|last=Kido|first=Misaki C.}}</ref> During this period, he was asked whether Sasuke was good or evil; he replied that Sasuke was neither and called him a \"very pure person.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=February 2014|title=Interview with Masashi Kishimoto (Creator of Naruto)|url=http://shonenjump.viz.com/node/1962|journal=[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|issue=2\u201303\u201314|quote='''Masashi Kishimoto:''' Sasuke is basically a very pure person who does not think about whether what he does is good or bad. He just does what he does which causes troubles for others.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222040608/http://shonenjump.viz.com/node/1962|archive-date=February 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said although some of Sasuke's actions such as following his clan's ideas were positive, his self-centeredness tended to cause problems with others. Since the beginning of the story's serialization, Kishimoto planned to conclude the series with a fight between Sasuke and Naruto, but he was uncertain whether the characters would end up as friends or enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/cool_japan/style/AJ201411100007|title=Masashi Kishimoto: Fan letters from overseas made me realize the popularity of 'Naruto'|date=November 10, 2014|website=ajw.asahi.com|publisher=Asashi|access-date=November 10, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110064229/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/cool_japan/style/AJ201411100007|archive-date=November 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although both characters had used ninja techniques throughout the series, Kishimoto wanted the two fighters to rely on hand-to-hand combat for the climax of their final battle.<ref name=\"Koba\"/> He decided to have Naruto forgive Sasuke because he had also forgiven [[List of Naruto characters#Nagato|Nagato]], another former enemy.<ref name=\"comiconinter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94186|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019091230/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94186|archive-date=October 19, 2016|title=Masashi Kishimoto at New York Comic-con The Anime News Network Interview|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Aoki|first=Deb|date=October 14, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe final fight between Sasuke and Naruto was considered one of the biggest challenges ever faced by the staff from [[Pierrot (company)|Pierrot]] as it took an entire month to adapt it from the manga. Director Hiroyuki Yamashita elected himself in charge of the battle which left most of the anime members relieved due to his experience. For the scenario, Pierrot received assistance from [[CyberConnect2]], the video game development studio who had already adapted this battle through the fighting game ''[[Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4]]''. There was a need to make every movement in the fight look realistic, giving Sasuke a scary look as well as hair movement in order to express the idea of both fighters willing to do anything to kill each other, which confused some due to Naruto's wish to avoid this fate. The final clash between Sasuke's Chidori and Naruto's Rasengan moves involved references from other scenes of the series to gave the viewer a bigger emotional impact. The staff noted that following this fight, Sasuke's face became calmer despite his initial look, giving room to explore his redemption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pierrot2.com/naruto/2016/10/03/%E3%83%A9%E3%82%B9%E3%83%88%E3%83%90%E3%83%88%E3%83%AB%E3%81%AE%E8%A3%8F%E8%A9%B1/|title=\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30c8\u30eb\u306e\u88cf\u8a71|publisher=Pierrot|language=Japanese|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKishimoto found Sasuke a difficult character to write, requiring considerable planning. In the series finale, Sasuke leaves on a solo journey; Kishimoto later stated that in addition to atonement, Sasuke wants to discover the origin of the final antagonist, but this was not explained in the story.<ref name=\" finale\"/> He planned Sasuke and [[Sakura Haruno]]'s romance early in ''Naruto''{{'s}} production and decided that despite having a good relationship with his allies, Sasuke would remain a rogue ninja at the end of the series.<ref name=\"cinema\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/page/A0004639|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie|website=CinemaToday.jp|language=Japanese|publisher=Cinema Today|access-date=June 14, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617171917/http://www.cinematoday.jp/page/A0004639|archive-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKishimoto wished to further explore Sasuke's role in the series after ''Naruto''{{'s}} finale. He wanted to explain the connection between Sasuke and Sakura in the [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] manga ''[[Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring]]'' (2015), which focuses on their daughter, [[Sarada Uchiha]]. Despite their separation during Sasuke's mission, which draws him away from his village, the story explains the bond between the three characters. Kishimoto focused on the final scene of the Uchiha family, which he regards as the spin-off's most important facet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ganganonline.com:80/contents/sukedachi_talk/|title=\u5cb8\u672c\u8056\u53f2\u00d7\u5cb8\u672c\u6589\u53f2 \u53cc\u5b50\u6f2b\u753b\u5bb6\u5144\u5f1f\u5bfe\u8ac7|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|trans-title=Seishi Kishimoto \u00d7 Masashi Kishimoto twin brothers manga artist interview|website=GanganOnline.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807021939/http://www.ganganonline.com/contents/sukedachi_talk/|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Because Sasuke had few appearances in the [[Naruto#Films|''Naruto'' films]], Kishimoto decided to give him a bigger role in ''[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2015), in which he teaches Naruto's firstborn child, [[Boruto Uzumaki]]; a reference to [[Piccolo (Dragon Ball)|Piccolo]] and [[Gohan]] in [[Akira Toriyama]]'s ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' manga series and also depicted in the manga ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' (2016). Kishimoto identified Naruto's fights alongside Sasuke against Momoshiki as the highlights of the film and asked that the film's staff pay close attention to those sequences. Two other scenes written by the staff which surprised Kishimoto were Sasuke's use of one of his [[taijutsu]] moves and the combination of his  [[Susanoo]] technique and Naruto's recreation of the [[List of Naruto characters#Kurama|Nine-Tailed Fox]].<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]|year=2015|medium=[[DVD]]}} Studio: [[Pierrot (company)|Pierrot]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u300cBoruto: Naruto the Movie-\u300d\u5267\u573a\u7248\u4e0a\u6620\u524d\u7279\u522b\u8282\u76ee|trans-title=Movie Version Before Screening Special Separation Clause|website=[[AcFun]]|url=http://www.acfun.cn/v/ac2074543|date=August 5, 2015|language=Japanese|access-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107000915/http://www.acfun.cn/v/ac2074543|archive-date=January 7, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = While early designs of Sasuke as seen in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] (left) were similar to the final one,<ref name=\"Design\"/> for [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]] (right) Kishimoto conceived multiple sketches which were scrapped.<ref name=\"sketch\"/>\n| image1 = SasukeUchihasketch.jpg\n| alt1   = Sketches of a male teenage manga character that include his full body, face, and clan symbol \u2014 the Japanese hand-held fan, also known as an ''uchiwa''\n| width1 = 120\n| image2 = SasukeUchihapartIIbeta.jpg\n| alt2   = Sketches of a male teenage character featured in a manga series\n| width2 = 120\n}}\nKishimoto regarded Sasuke as his most memorable character design because he was developed as Naruto's opposite.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bfBook \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u9663\u306e\u66f8|trans-title=Naruto Character Official Data Book Secret \u00b7 Book of Guys|year=2014|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|pages=378\u2013387|isbn=978-4-08-880263-3|language=Japanese}}</ref> He said the design of Sasuke and his {{nihongo|Sharingan|\u5199\u8f2a\u773c||lit. \"Copy Wheel Eye\", English manga: \"Mirror Wheel Eye\"}} ability were influenced by the character [[List of YuYu Hakusho characters#Hiei|Hiei]] in [[Yoshihiro Togashi]]'s manga series, ''[[YuYu Hakusho]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015[\u79d8\u4f1d\u00b7\u7686\u306e\u66f8]\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret \u00b7 Everyone's Book Official Premium Fan|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|date=December 4, 2009|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|isbn=978-4-08-874834-4|series=[[Naruto]]|pages=74\u201381|language=Japanese|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> Sasuke originally had necklaces and ties around his arms and legs because Kishimoto had a habit of giving characters as much ornamentation as possible; realizing he could not draw such a complex character on a weekly basis, Kishimoto simplified the design to a basic contrast with Naruto's costume.<ref name=\"Design\">{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=3|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2004|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|page=26|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> The {{nihongo|Chidori|\u5343\u9ce5||lit. \"One Thousand Birds\"}} \u2014 one of Sasuke and [[Kakashi Hatake]]'s best-known fighting techniques \u2014 originally had a different name that Kishimoto forgot. He found the name \"Chidori\" and its variant, the \"Lightning Blade\", appropriate.<ref name=\"Kizuna\" />\n\nKishimoto considered Sasuke his most challenging character to design and draw. He lacked a clear idea of how his face should look, saying Sasuke seemed older than Naruto, his contemporary,<ref name=\"Face\">{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=124|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> and felt this inconvenience was a result of his inexperience in drawing characters who were mature beyond their years.<ref name=\"Design\" /> Sasuke's hair, which was originally short to save Kishimoto time, slowly grew longer as the series progressed.<ref name=\"Face\" /> Mid-way through Part I, he drew a new costume for Sasuke with belts strapped around his arms and legs, but he returned to the character's original design because it took less time to draw.<ref>{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=130|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> Sasuke is his favorite character to draw despite the time and energy required,<ref name=\"Design\" /> and he compared Sasuke with Sakura in difficulty.<ref name=\"Koba\">{{cite AV media|title=\u6f2b\u9053\u30b3\u30d0\u30e4\u30b7\u7b2c13\u53f7\u300cNaruto\u5b8c\u7d50\uff01\u5cb8\u672c\u6589\u53f2SP\u300d|date=December 13, 2014|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Fuji Television]]|trans-title=Kobayashi No. 13 'Completion of Naruto! Masashi Kishimoto SP'}}</ref> Kishimoto's superiors sometimes asked him to redraw parts of the manga that did not illustrate Sasuke well.<ref name=\"Koba\"/>\n\nKishimoto's design focus for Part II was Sasuke's older appearance. Originally, Kishimoto had wanted to draw him as a more attractive person, but the idea was discarded. An outfit he initially planned combined the younger Sasuke's outfit with new, more modern clothes. Kishimoto tried several other looks, including the use of [[Shimenawa]] to evoke the antagonist [[Orochimaru (Naruto)|Orochimaru]], and a [[Polo neck|turtleneck]] and military uniform to connote cleanliness. He avoided the second option due to similarities with cold weather clothing and eventually chose Japanese clothing and a ''[[chokut\u014d]]'' sword.<ref name=\"sketch\">{{cite book|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u8005\u306e\u66f8 \u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bfBook|trans-title=Naruto Secret: Scroll of People Character Official Databook|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|year=2008|isbn=978-4-08-874247-2|page=343|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nFor ''[[The Last: Naruto the Movie]]'', Kishimoto gave Sasuke a new, young-adult design with sharper facial features.<ref name=\"The Last\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-14/the-last-naruto-the-movie-s-sasuke-kakashi-character-designs-unveiled/.81021|title=The Last -Naruto the Movie-'s Sasuke, Kakashi Character Designs Unveiled|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=June 14, 2017|date=November 14, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501012120/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-14/the-last-naruto-the-movie-s-sasuke-kakashi-character-designs-unveiled/.81021|archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> In contrast with the older Naruto, who cut his hair, Sasuke's hairstyle grew longer to cover part of the character's face. In the original concept, the hair hid Sasuke's mysterious left eye \u2014 the {{nihongo|Rinnegan|\u8f2a\u5efb\u773c||lit. \"[[Sa\u1e43s\u0101ra]] Eye\"}}. According to Kishimoto, he decided to give the character a large hood because Sasuke concealed his identity during the events of the film. Sasuke's design was specifically created to support his actions; the area that showed Sasuke had lost his left arm in the ''Naruto'' finale was also covered by his clothes.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u5217\u306e\u66f8 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30e0\u30fc\u30d3\u30fc\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret: Scroll of Line Official Movie Guidebook|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|pages=63\u201364|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|Voice actors and personality}}Personality and voice actors===\n[[File:Yuri Lowenthal by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|[[Yuri Lowenthal]], voice of Sasuke in the anime's English-language version|alt=A middle-aged, Caucasian man with short, dark hair, wearing a black jacket and speaking into a microphone]]\n\nSasuke is voiced by [[Noriaki Sugiyama]] in Japanese media. At the beginning of [[Naruto#Anime|the anime's first part]], Sugiyama had difficulty voicing Sasuke because he knew little about his personality; he began to understand the character at the point in the story where Sasuke encounters his brother, [[Itachi Uchiha]]. Sugiyama read the manga and became particularly interested in Sasuke's development when the character left Konohagakure; he wanted to revoice some scenes from the [[anime]], including Sasuke's departure from Konohagakure.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[V Jump]]|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|pages=320\u2013321|title=\u30a4\u30bf\u30c1\u306e\u30a8\u30cb\u30b0\u30de|trans-title=The Enigma that is Itachi|issue=March 2016|year=2016|language=Japanese}}</ref> In ''Behind the Scenes of Uchiha'', a feature about Sasuke and Itachi's backstory, Sugiyama said he had become emotional during the recording sessions of the sixth season of [[Naruto#Naruto: Shippuden|the anime's second part]] (''Naruto: Shippuden''), in which Sasuke learns the truth about his brother's role in the massacre of the Uchiha clan.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u75be\u98a8\u4f1d \u5e2b\u306e\u4e88\u8a00\u3068\u5fa9\u8b90|trans-title=Naruto Shippuden Master's Prophecy and Vengeance 6|publisher=[[Aniplex]]|year=2011|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nSugiyama thought Sasuke's line, \"You are annoying,\" summed up the character's feelings toward Sakura and indicated a change in their relationship each time it was said; although she initially annoys him, he smiles when he repeats it before leaving Konohagakure. Naruto's Japanese voice actress, [[Junko Takeuchi]], said  Sasuke's line addressed to Sakura, \"See you next time... Thank you,\" revealed his feelings for her. Sugiyama stated that by the end of the series, Sasuke realized how much he had hurt Sakura's feelings and apologized to her after his final fight against Naruto because of this. While recording for ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', Sugiyama expected to see a bond between Sasuke and his apprentice, Boruto Uzumaki.<ref>{{cite magazine|transcript=http://imgur.com/a/D4DoR|title=\u6f14\u8005\u3082\u30ef\u30af\u30ef\u30af\u3057\u3001\u9a5a\u3044\u305f\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u885d\u6483\u7684\u306a\u5c55\u958b\n|trans-title=Even the actors are excited, the shocking unfolding of the surprising ending|magazine=Da Vinci|year=2015|issue=May|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]|pages=32\u201335}}</ref> According to  Sugiyama, Sasuke's personality had changed for the [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations#Anime plot|''Boruto'' anime series]], and the actor wanted fans to see the character's interaction with his family.<ref name=\"boruto\">{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/naruto-side-story-to-get-an-episode-in-boruto/|title=Naruto Side Story to Get an Episode in Boruto|website=Manga Tokyo|last=Kitahata|first=Yukihiro|access-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017202900/https://manga.tokyo/news/naruto-side-story-to-get-an-episode-in-boruto/|archive-date=October 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Japanese rock band [[Scenarioart]] in charge of performing the ending theme song of this story arc were given directions by Pierrot to make the song show the distant but caring relationship between Sasuke and Sarada. As a result, although the lyrics often mentions the farewells Sasuke and Sarada had, the intention was meant to make it look optimistic as they are destined to meet once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cho-animedia.jp/music/25027/|title=Boruto Ed|publisher=Animedia|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Yuri Lowenthal]], who voices Sasuke in the English [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubs]], said he was honored to receive the role since many actors had auditioned for it, and he added that the job was stressful. Although fans were critical of deviations and mistakes in his recordings,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ds.ign.com/articles/720/720129p1.html|title=Comic-Con 2006: Naruto Party Interview|website=[[IGN]]|last=Bozon|first=Mark|date=July 21, 2006|access-date=December 30, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071204211110/http://ds.ign.com/articles/720/720129p1.html|archive-date=December 4, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he enjoyed voicing the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamingunion.net/interviews/2386/yuri-lowenthal-on-prince-of-persia-amongst-other-things/|title=Yuri Lowenthal On Prince of Persia, Amongst Other Things|last=Alessandra|first=Lauren|website=Gaming Union|date=August 6, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150627165520/http://www.gamingunion.net/interviews/2386/yuri-lowenthal-on-prince-of-persia-amongst-other-things/|access-date=June 13, 2017|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> His first impression of Sasuke was of \"a serious guy dedicated to his training\", but his view changed as he learned about the character's backstory.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Naruto Collector<!--correct name needed-->|journal=Naruto Collector|issue=June 2006|year=2006|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> Lowenthal said in 2010 that Sasuke was one of the first dark characters he voiced, adding, \"He's sort of a hero, but he's not the na\u00efve, young [[Black and white hat symbolism in film|white\u2013hat hero]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticalgamer.co.uk/2010/06/07/yuri-lowenthal-mcm-expo-2010-interview-part-one/|title=Yuri Lowenthal: MCM Expo 2010 interview (part one)|last=K.|first=Luke|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131125234019/http://www.criticalgamer.co.uk/2010/06/07/yuri-lowenthal-mcm-expo-2010-interview-part-one/|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 25, 2013|df=|website=Critical Gamer}}</ref> Lowenthal said that some of Sasuke's lines, such as his use of the word \"kill\", were changed because [[Viz Media]] often censored parts of the series' dialogue for Western viewers. As a result, he found the original Japanese version truer to the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2006/03/01/yuri-lowenthal-speaks-about-sasuke/|title=Yuri Lowenthal Speaks about Sasuke|date=March 1, 2006|website=Siliconera|access-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912234830/http://www.siliconera.com/2006/03/01/yuri-lowenthal-speaks-about-sasuke/|archive-date=September 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Character==\n[[File:Sasuke Uchiha kusanagi 02.JPG|thumb|A replica of Sasuke's [[Kusanagi]] sword|alt=A plain sword in a sheath]]\n\nSasuke is introduced in Part I as a young, spiky-black-haired pre-teen wearing a blue shirt with an image of a fan that represents his clan on its back. He also wears short white pants and a Konohagakure headband.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 3|isbn=978-1-56931-900-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Early in the series, Orochimaru brands Sasuke with a Cursed Seal that, when activated, covers his body with black marks and later gives him gray skin, white hair, and claw-like wings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 232|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> In Part II, he is normally depicted wearing a white [[kimono]] and black pants. Although he is skilled in the use of [[shuriken]], in Part II Sasuke uses a ''chokut\u014d'' sword that he calls [[Kusanagi]]. In addition to using Kusanagi for [[kenjutsu|swordsmanship]], Sasuke combines it with lightning-based techniques to increase the power of his attacks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=34|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 308|isbn=978-1-4215-2002-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=42|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 389|isbn=978-1-4215-2843-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> In ''The Last: Naruto the Movie'', his adult wardrobe consists of gray pants and a light-brown cloak over a black shirt,<ref name=\"The Last\"/> while in  ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', he wears black pants and a black cape over a lilac vest.<ref name=\"cinema\"/>\n\nSasuke is a silent character who tries to gain more power and kill his older brother, Itachi, for betraying and murdering their clan.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 4|isbn=978-1-56931-900-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He cares about his teammates and saves them on numerous occasions,<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2004\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=3|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 27|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=15|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 133|isbn=978-1-4215-1089-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=16|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 138|isbn=978-1-4215-1090-3|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> but he severs all of his bonds later in Part I, believing this will strengthen him. Sasuke is moved when Naruto Uzumaki wants him to make peace with the village; he considers Naruto his only friend.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2015\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=72|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 698|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke becomes more kindhearted by the end of the series, but he decides not to return home, chooses to redeem himself, and searches for an enemy threatening the peace of Konohagakure.<ref name=\"renamed_from_699_on_20170915212700\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n==={{anchor|In ''Naruto''}}In ''Naruto''===\n====In Part I====\nSasuke is introduced in the third chapter of ''Naruto''{{'}}s manga as a young ninja assigned to become a member of Team&nbsp;7 alongside his rival Naruto Uzumaki and Sakura Haruno, the latter of whom is infatuated with him.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 3|isbn=1-56931-900-6|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> The trio are trained under the guidance of Kakashi Hatake.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto|volume=2|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 8|isbn=978-1-59116-178-3|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Although Sasuke is antisocial, cold, and distant, he starts caring about Naruto and Sakura.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=3|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 19|page=40|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> During a mission, Sasuke awakens his Sharingan \u2014 his clan's inherited ability to see through illusions \u2014 which allows him to learn imperceptible movements at a superhuman rate.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2004\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 230|pages=74\u201375|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> It is revealed later that Sasuke is the sole survivor of the once-powerful Uchiha clan of Konohagakure. He, at the age of seven, survived the massacre of his clan perpetrated by his brother, Itachi, who spared Sasuke's life because he did not consider him worth killing.<ref name=\"Resolution\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=25|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 225|isbn=978-1-4215-1861-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke seeks strong fighting opponents to reassure himself his power is growing.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=5|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 38|isbn=978-1-59116-359-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\nDuring a ninja examination meant to improve their ranks, Team&nbsp;7 encounters Orochimaru, an exile from Konohagakure who afflicts Sasuke with a Cursed Seal that contains a fragment of Orochimaru's consciousness, which increases Sasuke's physical abilities, but makes him cruel and sadistic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=7|year=2005|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 56|isbn=978-1-59116-875-1|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=21|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 184|pages=[https://archive.org/details/narutovol21pursu21kish/page/68 68\u201372]|isbn=978-1-4215-1855-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Kakashi teaches Sasuke the lightning-based offensive technique called Chidori in an attempt to appease Sasuke's desire for power.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=15|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 128|pages=[https://archive.org/details/narutovol21pursu21kish/page/35 35\u201336]|isbn=978-1-4215-1855-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> During a siege of Konohagakure, a [[Beserker|beserker ninja]] named [[Gaara]] beats Sasuke, who is rescued by Naruto. Shortly afterward, Itachi returns to the village; Sasuke tries to kill him, but he is beaten and tortured instead. Shaken by the experience he decides to leave Team&nbsp;7 and Konohagakure to become stronger.<ref name=\"Corruption\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=20|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 176|isbn=978-1-4215-1655-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Thinking Orochimaru's training will make him more powerful, Sasuke becomes an outlaw.<ref name=\"Defection\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=20|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 179|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781421516554/page/155 155\u2013157]|isbn=978-1-4215-1655-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Naruto follows him and they fight when Sasuke refuses to return; Sasuke wins, spares Naruto's life, and continues to Orochimaru's hideout.<ref name=\"Decision\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 234|pages=161\u2013163|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\n====In Part II====\nAfter two-and-a-half years of training, Sasuke absorbs Orochimaru before he can possess his younger body.<ref name=\"Betrayal\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=38|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 343|isbn=978-1-4215-2174-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Following this, Sasuke forms [[List of Naruto characters#Taka|Team Hebi]] to find Itachi.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=42|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 380|isbn=978-1-4215-2843-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Itachi and Sasuke fight and Itachi dies at the climax of the battle from an illness.<ref name=\"Brotherly\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=43|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 401|isbn=978-1-4215-2929-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke then meets [[List of Naruto characters#Obito Uchiha|Tobi]], Itachi's superior, who reveals that Itachi killed the Uchiha clan under orders from Konohagakure and spared Sasuke out of love rather than contempt.<ref name=\"Brotherly\"/> Sasuke rejoins Hebi \u2014 which he renames Taka \u2014 and declares his intention to destroy his former village in retribution. Due to his brother's death, Sasuke's Sharingan has evolved into a {{nihongo|Mangekyo Sharingan|\u4e07\u83ef\u93e1\u5199\u8f2a\u773c|Mangeky\u014d Sharingan|lit. \"Kaleidoscope Copy Wheel Eye\"}}, giving him powerful new techniques.<ref name=\"Vengeance\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=43|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 402|isbn=978-1-4215-2929-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> After he agrees to work temporarily for Tobi's terrorist organization, [[List of Naruto characters#Akatsuki|Akatsuki]], Sasuke becomes a criminal.<ref name=\"ch419\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=45|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 419|isbn=978-1-4215-3135-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He kills [[List of Naruto characters#Danzo Shimura|Danzo Shimura]] \u2014 a mastermind of the Uchiha massacre and the acting Hokage, the leader of Konohagakure, at the time.<ref name=\"ch457\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=49|year=2010|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 457|isbn=978-1-4215-3475-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke is confronted by his former Team&nbsp;7 colleagues, and Naruto challenges him to a death match.<ref name=\"ch486\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=52|year=2011|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 486|isbn=978-1-4215-3957-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\nSasuke initially prepares to fight Naruto but instead decides to protect Konohagakure after he encounters the re-animated bodies of Itachi<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=62|year=2012|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 590|isbn=978-4-08-870515-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> and the [[List of Naruto characters#Hashirama Senju|First Hokage]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=62|year=2012|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 593|isbn=978-4-08-870515-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=65|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 627|isbn=978-1-4215-6455-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He rejoins Team&nbsp;7 and fights the Ten-Tails monster that is controlled by the masterminds behind Akatsuki.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=66|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 631|isbn=978-1-4215-6948-2|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=68|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 655|isbn=978-1-4215-7682-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke inherits the Rinnegan \u2014 a legendary eye technique \u2014 from the spirit of the Sage of the Six Paths Hagoromo Otsutsuki, the Founder of Shinobi. Team&nbsp;7 fights and seals an ancient being called [[List of Naruto characters#Kaguya \u014ctsutsuki|Kaguya Otsutsuki]] \u2014 Hagoromo's mother \u2014 who created the Ten-Tails.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=70|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 679|isbn=978-1-4215-7975-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke then fights Naruto alone to settle their village's future;<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=72|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|chapter=Chapter 692|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> when he loses his left arm, Sasuke surrenders and reconciles with Naruto.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2015\"/> Sasuke then destroys Akatsuki's illusion placed on mankind with his Rinnegan. He is pardoned for his crimes by Kakashi \u2014 the current Hokage \u2014 and decides to travel the world in search of redemption. Before leaving, he says farewell to both Sakura and Naruto with gratitude.<ref name=\"renamed_from_699_on_20170915212700\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=72|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 699|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> By the end of the manga, having briefly returned to the village, Sasuke is revealed to have married Sakura who is raising their daughter Sarada.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=72|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|chapter=Chapter 700|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\n===In the ''Boruto'' franchise===\nIn the ''Naruto'' spin-off manga, ''Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring'', and the ''Boruto: Naruto Next Generations'' anime (2017), Sasuke has left Konohagakure sometime after Sarada's birth on a secret mission to investigate a possible threat relating to Kaguya, traveling across the world and Kaguya's dimensions for clues while aiding the other villages in secret. In the ''Boruto'' anime, Sasuke briefly returns to his village before the [[Story arc|arc]] begins and asks Naruto to offer Sakura his apologies.<ref name=\"boruto\"/> He rejoins Naruto to oppose Orochimaru's former test subject [[List of Naruto characters#Shin Uchiha|Shin]], who takes the Uchiha surname for his own while seeking to avenge Itachi and revive the Akatsuki to end the peace. After defeating Shin and his clone children, Sasuke bonds with his daughter for the first time and resumes his mission.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring|year=2016|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|isbn=978-1421584935|title-link=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring}}</ref> A novel by Mirei Miyamoto focuses on Sasuke's work in his village where he replaces [[List of Naruto characters#Konohamaru Sarutobi|Konohamaru Sarutobi]] as the leader of Boruto, Sarada, and [[Mitsuki (Naruto)|Mitsuki]]'s team.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Sasuke Shinden: The Teacher's Star Pupil|isbn=978-4-08-703450-9|year=2018|last1=Miyamoto|first1=Mirei|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1\u65b0\u4f1d \u5e2b\u5f1f\u306e\u661f}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', also covered in both the ''Boruto'' manga and anime, Sasuke returns to Konohagakure to warn Naruto of the threat posed by Kaguya's kinsmen [[List of Naruto characters#Momoshiki \u014ctsutsuki|Momoshiki Otsutsuki]] and [[List of Naruto characters#Kinshiki \u014ctsutsuki|Kinshiki Otsutsuki]], who seek the tailed beast chakra for their end.<ref name=BorutoTheMovie>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-the-movie/.93939|title=Boruto -Naruto the Movie-|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 9, 2015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=April 20, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420100434/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-the-movie/.93939|archive-date=April 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|last1=Kishimoto|first1=Masashi|last2=Ikemoto|first2=Mikio|last3=Kodachi|first3=Ukyo|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2017|isbn=9781421592114|volume=1|chapter=1|author1-link=Masashi Kishimoto|author2-link=Mikio Ikemoto|title-link=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations}}</ref> He meets Naruto's son, Boruto, and becomes the boy's mentor once having him learn to use his father's {{nihongo|Rasengan|\u87ba\u65cb\u4e38||lit. spiral sphere, English manga: \"Spiral Chakra Sphere\"}}. When the Otsutsuki members abduct Naruto during the Chunin Exam, Sasuke is accompanied by Boruto as he and the Kage \u2014 the leaders of the ninja villages \u2014 travel to Momoshiki's planet to save Naruto. Sasuke then aids Naruto and Boruto in defeating Momoshiki, who absorbs Kinshiki to increase his power.<ref name=BorutoTheMovie/> After Momoshiki's defeat, Sasuke notices the enemy has placed a seal on Boruto.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|last1=Kishimoto|first1=Masashi|last2=Ikemoto|first2=Mikio|last3=Kodachi|first3=Ukyo|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2018|isbn=978-1-4215-9822-2|volume=3|chapter=Chapter 11|author1-link=Masashi Kishimoto|author2-link=Mikio Ikemoto|title-link=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations}}</ref> The anime has Sasuke searching Urashiki Otsutsuki alongside Gaara.<ref>{{cite episode|title=With Sasuke As The Goal|series=[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]|airdate=August 18, 2019|publisher=Studio Pierrot}}</ref> In the manga, Sasuke later travels to an Otsutsuki site where he finds records on the Otsutsuki clan which include some of its members that came to his world, learning that Kara's leader Jigen is somehow connected to Kaguya. He aids Naruto against Jigen, but the Konohagakure ninjas are overwhelmed in combat and Sasuke is forced to escape back to Konoha as Naruto is sealed away by the enemy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-37/chapter/19050 |title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations, Chapter 37 |website=[[Viz.com]] |accessdate=20 August 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820163234/https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-37/chapter/19050 |archivedate=20 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-38/chapter/19053 |title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations, Chapter 38 |website=[[Viz.com]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920174122/https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-38/chapter/19053 |archivedate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===In other media===\n\nSasuke appears in the first four [[Naruto#Original video animations|original video animations]] ([[original video animations|OVAs]]) produced for the series. In the first episode, he helps Naruto and Konohamaru find a [[four-leaf clover]];<ref name=\"loststory\">{{cite AV media|date=2007|title=Naruto OVA \u2013 The Lost Story|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=Viz Video|url=http://www.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=8722|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217110548/http://www.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=8722|archive-date=December 17, 2007|df=mdy-all|access-date=August 29, 2013}}</ref> in the second, he joins Naruto's team for a mission;<ref name=\"loststory\"/> he participates in a tournament in the third; and he works with Team 7 in the fourth.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2005|title=\u3064\u3044\u306b\u6fc0\u7a81\uff01\u4e0a\u5fcdVS\u4e0b\u5fcd\uff01\uff01\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u5927\u4e71\u6226\u5927\u4f1a\u958b\u50ac\uff01\uff01|trans-title=Finally a clash! Jonin VS Genin!! Indiscriminate grand melee tournament meeting!!|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[TV Tokyo]]|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000BNPT3E/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-30/naruto-toriko-one-piece-event-anime-shorts-streamed|date=November 30, 2009|title=Naruto, Toriko, One Piece Event Anime Shorts Streamed|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=November 30, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108105635/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-30/naruto-toriko-one-piece-event-anime-shorts-streamed|archive-date=November 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> One OVA presents an alternate fight between Sasuke and Naruto in ''Naruto: Shippuden''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-12-20/naruto-anime-dvd-offered-at-uniqlo-t-shirt-stores|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106114433/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-12-20/naruto-anime-dvd-offered-at-uniqlo-t-shirt-stores|archive-date=November 6, 2016|date=December 20, 2010|title=News: Naruto Anime DVD Offered at Uniqlo T-Shirt Stores|website=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The character is present in the first two ''Naruto'' feature films; he guards a princess in ''[[Naruto the Movie: Ninja Clash in the Land of Snow]]'' (2004) and makes a brief appearance in a flashback in ''[[Naruto the Movie: Legend of the Stone of Gelel]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2007|title=Naruto the Movie: Ninja Clash in the Land of Snow|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=Viz Video|url=http://www.viz.com/anime/dvd/naruto-the-movie-video-volume-1/6828|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323191537/http://www.viz.com/anime/dvd/naruto-the-movie-video-volume-1/6828|archive-date=March 23, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The first Part II film in which he appears is ''[[Naruto Shippuden 2: Bonds]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2011|title=Naruto Shippuden: The Movie \u2013 Bonds|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005DVIPE4/}}</ref> The sixth Part II film, ''[[Road to Ninja: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2012), contains a flirtatious, alternate-reality version of Sasuke.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2012|title=Road to Ninja: Naruto the Movie|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00Q4F7FDK/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212013938/https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00Q4F7FDK/|archive-date=December 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In ''The Last: Naruto the Movie'' (2014), an adult Sasuke returns briefly to Konohagakure to protect it from a meteor.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2015|title=The Last: Naruto the Movie|format=[[Blu-ray]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00ZCHTRKA/}}</ref>\n\nHe is a recurring character in the ''Naruto'' [[light novels]] and the protagonist of the manga ''Naruto Jinraiden: The Day the Wolf Howled'' (2012), which explores Sasuke's reflections after Itachi's death and his decision to destroy Konohagakure.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Naruto Jinraiden: The Day the Wolf Howled|isbn=978-4-08-703279-6|year=2012|last1=Higashiyama|first1=Akira|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u8fc5\u96f7\u4f1d \u72fc\u306e\u54ed\u304f\u65e5}}</ref> In ''Sakura Hiden'' (2015), an adult Sasuke continues his journey of redemption but returns to Konohagakure out of concern for Sakura's safety.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Naruto: Sakura's Story \u2014 Love Riding the Spring Breeze|isbn=978-1-42-158442-3|year=2016|last1=Tomohito|first1=\u014csaki|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|title=\u30b5\u30af\u30e9\u79d8\u4f1d \u601d\u604b\u3001\u6625\u98a8\u306b\u306e\u305b\u3066}}</ref> In ''Akatsuki Hiden'' (2015), Sasuke meets two children who tell him stories about Akatsuki, and they discuss Itachi's legacy.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: \u6681\u79d8\u4f1d \u54b2\u304d\u4e71\u308c\u308b\u60aa\u306e\u83ef|isbn=978-4-08-703367-0|year=2015|last1=Towada|first1=Shin|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|language=Japanese|trans-title=Naruto Akatsuki Hiden: Evil Flowers in Full Bloom|publisher=[[Shueisha]]}}</ref> He is the protagonist of ''Sasuke Shinden'' (2015); he agrees to aid Konohagakure by investigating a series of disappearances, which he solves with the help of Taka and a Konohagakure ninja named [[List of Naruto characters#Sai|Sai]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: Sasuke's Story \u2014 Sunrise|isbn=978-1-42-159129-2|year=2017|last1=Towada|first1=Shin|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> Sasuke is also the protagonist of manga artist Kenji Taira's ''Naruto'' spin-off, ''Sasuke Uchiha's Sharingan Legend'' (2014), in which he and Taka search for Itachi. According to Taira, Sasuke would be characterized as an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: Chibi Sasuke's Sharingan Legend|volume=1|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|page=1|last=Taira|first=Kenji|year=2017|isbn=978-1421597102}}</ref> A new novel focused on Sasuke's life as an adult alongside Sakura, ''Sasuke Retsuden: The Uchiha Descendants and the Heavenly Stardust'' (2019), was written by Jun Esaka.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Sasuke Retsuden: The Uchiha Descendants and the Heavenly Stardust|title=NARUTO -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1\u70c8\u4f1d\u3000\u3046\u3061\u306f\u306e\u672b\u88d4\u3068\u5929\u7403\u306e\u661f\u5c51|publisher=Shueisha|year=2019|isbn=978-4-08-703481-3|last1=Esaka|first1=Jun|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi}}</ref>\n\nSasuke is a [[player character|playable character]] in [[List of Naruto video games|''Naruto'' video games]], including the [[Naruto: Clash of Ninja|''Clash of Ninja'']] and [[Naruto: Ultimate Ninja|''Ultimate Ninja'']] series.<ref name=\"IGNCoN2GuidePage1\">{{cite web|url=http://cube.ign.com/articles/736/736611p1.html|title=Naruto: The Complete Fighter Profile|last=Bozon|first=Mark|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 29, 2006|access-date=January 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516171031/http://cube.ign.com/articles/736/736611p1.html|archive-date=May 16, 2010|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"IGNCoN3HandsOn\">{{cite web|url=http://cube.ign.com/articles/551/551374p1.html|title=TGS 2004: Naruto Gekitou Ninja Taisen! 3 Hands-on|last=Alfonso|first=Andrew|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 26, 2004|access-date=January 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304010910/http://cube.ign.com/articles/551/551374p1.html|archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GUIDE1 26\">{{cite book|title=Naruto: Ultimate Ninja English instruction manual|year=2006|publisher=[[Bandai Namco]]|page=26}}</ref> His Cursed Seal can be unlocked and activated in some games. Due to his absence from early ''Naruto: Shippuden'' episodes, Sasuke has not appeared in any games based on ''Naruto: Shippuden'' until the launch of ''[[Naruto: Clash of Ninja#Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Gekit\u014d Ninja Taisen! EX (Wii series)|Gekitou Ninja Taisen EX 2]]'' and ''[[Naruto Ultimate Ninja#Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Ultimate Ninja 5|Ultimate Ninja 5]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"VJump 54-55\">{{cite book|title=V Jump|year=2007|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|language=Japanese|pages=54\u201355|title-link=V Jump}}</ref> Sasuke is also present in [[Crossovers in video games|crossover]] games, such as ''[[Jump Super Stars]]'' (2005), ''[[Jump Ultimate Stars]]'' (2006), ''[[Battle Stadium D.O.N]]'' (2006), ''[[J-Stars Victory VS]]'' (2014), and ''[[Jump Force]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajsj/char11.html|title=Jump Super Stars -Characters|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|website=nintendo.co.jp|language=Japanese|access-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630171117/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajsj/char11.html|archive-date=June 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajuj/character/chara_24.html|title=Jump Ultimate Stars Characters|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|website=nintendo.co.jp|language=Japanese|access-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630184517/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajuj/character/chara_24.html|archive-date=June 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2013-08-28/naruto/dragon-ball/toriko-rivals-transformations-in-j-stars-victory-vs-game|title=Naruto/Dragon Ball/Toriko Rivals, Transformations in J-Stars Victory Vs. Game|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 28, 2013|access-date=August 29, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828221406/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2013-08-28/naruto/dragon-ball/toriko-rivals-transformations-in-j-stars-victory-vs-game|archive-date=August 28, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2006/07/31/battle-stadium-don/|title=Battle Stadium D.O.N.|website=Siliconera|access-date=December 11, 2017|date=July 31, 2006|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609202559/http://www.siliconera.com/2006/07/31/battle-stadium-don/|archive-date=June 9, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Popularity===\nSasuke has ranked among the top-five ''Naruto'' characters in every ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]'' popularity poll of the series. Initially alternating between third and fourth places, he has finished first twice.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=28|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 245|pages=[https://archive.org/details/naruto00kish_2/page/8 8\u20139]|isbn=978-1-4215-1864-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=33|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 293|isbn=978-1-4215-2001-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> A popularity poll on the Japanese website ''Charapedia'' ranked Sasuke and Naruto's rivalry as the best in anime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/LatestNews/News1/Japanese-Fans-Rank-Animes-Most-Memorable-Rivalries-6620.aspx|title=Japanese Fans Rank Anime's Most Memorable Rivalries|last=Schley|first=Matt|website=[[Otaku USA]]|access-date=October 22, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721132127/http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/LatestNews/News1/Japanese-Fans-Rank-Animes-Most-Memorable-Rivalries-6620.aspx|archive-date=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Similarly, Sasuke was voted as the second best rival in manga and anime in a poll by ''Anime Anime''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otakuusamagazine.com/animes-greatest-rivals/|title=Japanese Fans Rank Anime's Greatest Rivals|website=[[Otaku USA]]|publisher=Sovereign Media|access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref> At New York's 2015 [[New York Comic Con|Comic-Con]], moderator Christopher Butcher and editor Jo Otsuki commented that Sasuke had become the series' most popular character, and Otsuki called him his favorite. Butcher wondered whether readers considered Sasuke a more-relatable character after he had embraced Naruto's positive outlook on life in the series finale. According to Otsuki, fans regarded Sasuke's character and abilities as \"cooler\" than those of his rival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94188|title=Part II \u2013 An Evening with Masashi Kishimoto|date=October 14, 2015|access-date=June 9, 2017|last=Aoki|first=Deb|website=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529004749/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94188|archive-date=May 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jacob Hope of ''[[Anime News Network]]'' (''ANN'') listed Sasuke and Naruto as two of the \"Fiercest Frenemies\" in anime due to their resemblance despite being adversaries and their need to engage in a mortal fight to become friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-06-08/anime-fiercest-frenemies/.102975|title=Anime's Fiercest Frenemies|last=Chapman|first=Jacob Hope|date=June 8, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=July 1, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029002837/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-06-08/anime-fiercest-frenemies/.102975|archive-date=October 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a Tokyo Otaku Mode poll, Sasuke was deemed the sixth best character women would want to have a date with.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://otakumode.com/release/2013-12-02-1|title=Tokyo Otaku Mode Fall 2013 User Poll|date=December 1, 2013|website=Otaku Mode|access-date=May 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Merchandise===\nSasuke merchandise includes [[keychain|key chains]]<ref name=\"SasukeKeyChain\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Keychains-Sasuke-PVC-Keychain/products_id/112321.html|title=Naruto \u2013 Keychains \u2013 Sasuke PVC Keychain|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529152728/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Keychains-Sasuke-PVC-Keychain/products_id/112321.html|archive-date=May 29, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[action figure|figurines]].<ref name=\"VizActionFigures\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttc/action-figures/cPath/10175_10219.html|title=Naruto Toys \u2013 Action Figures at Official Naruto Store|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203090007/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttc/action-figures/cPath/10175_10219.html|archive-date=February 3, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"SasukeActionFigure\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Action-Figure-Sasuke-Premium-Sculpt-8-Figure/products_id/111604.html|title=Naruto \u2013 Toys \u2013 Sasuke Roto 8\" Figure|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212191811/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Action-Figure-Sasuke-Premium-Sculpt-8-Figure/products_id/111604.html|archive-date=February 12, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/10/30/love-and-ninja-included-in-new-naruto-prize-figure-lottery|title=Love and Ninja Included in New \"Naruto\" Prize Figure Lottery|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=October 31, 2012|access-date=May 11, 2018|first=Scott|last=Green|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511124633/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/10/30/love-and-ninja-included-in-new-naruto-prize-figure-lottery|archive-date=May 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Boruto'' film audiences were offered fans bearing images of Sasuke and his daughter, Sarada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-07-28/naruto-creator-on-being-asked-for-sequel-please-let-me-rest-now/.90993|title=Naruto Creator on Being Asked for Sequel: 'Please Let Me Rest Now'|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 28, 2015|access-date=October 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701042712/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-07-28/naruto-creator-on-being-asked-for-sequel-please-let-me-rest-now/.90993|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \nTo promote the video game ''[[Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4]]'', two 1/6-scale statues depicting Sasuke and Naruto during their final clash from the series were developed by Luxembourgian company Tsume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2015-12-09/namco-bandai-europe-teases-naruto-shippuden-ultimate-ninja-storm-4-bonus-figures/.96300|title=Namco Bandai Europe Teases Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4 Bonus Figures|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 9, 2015|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801054224/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2015-12-09/namco-bandai-europe-teases-naruto-shippuden-ultimate-ninja-storm-4-bonus-figures/.96300|archive-date=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nJapanese toy company [[Bandai]] released an action figure of Sasuke performing the Chidori move.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-02-21/figure-build-close-up-2016-s.h-figuarts-naruto-and-sasuke/.112477|title=Figure Build Close-up: 2016 S.H. Figuarts Naruto & Sasuke|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 21, 2017|access-date=February 22, 2018|last=Orsini|first=Lauren|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801151320/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-02-21/figure-build-close-up-2016-s.h-figuarts-naruto-and-sasuke/.112477|archive-date=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2017, Bandai launched a figurine of Sasuke performing his Susanoo eye technique, which represents the god of thunder [[Raijin]]. [[Studio Pierrot]] released artwork that was sold alongside this figure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-05-16/naruto-sasuke-god-figures-make-a-storm-this-september/.116103|title=Naruto, Sasuke God Figures Make a Storm This September|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731132511/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-05-16/naruto-sasuke-god-figures-make-a-storm-this-september/.116103|archive-date=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bandai also produced a limited-edition adult figurine of Sasuke as he appears in the ''Naruto'' finale and the ''Boruto'' franchise, which impressed Scott Green, a writer for [[Ain't It Cool News]] and [[Crunchyroll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/03/14-1/limited-boruto-naruto-the-movie-sasuke-uchiha-gem-figure-planned|title=Limited \"Boruto -Naruto The Movie-\" Sasuke Uchiha G.E.M. Figure Planned|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|publisher=[[Otter Media]]|last=Green|first=Scott|date=March 14, 2016|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711081449/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/03/14-1/limited-boruto-naruto-the-movie-sasuke-uchiha-gem-figure-planned|archive-date=July 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://p-bandai.jp/item/item-1000103229/|title=G.E.M.\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba Boruto -Naruto the Movie- \u3046\u3061\u306f\u30b5\u30b9\u30b1|website=P-Bandai.jp|publisher=[[Bandai]]|language=Japanese|trans-title=G.E.M. Series Boruto -Naruto the Movie- Sasuke Uchiha|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715041536/http://p-bandai.jp/item/item-1000103229/|archive-date=July 15, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:F\u00e4cher04.JPG|thumb|upright|The Eastern fan (''[[uchiwa]]'') is Sasuke's clan symbol.<ref name=\"Plumb\"/>|alt=A white Eastern fan, with pink and purple flowers]]\n\nSasuke's character has received both praise and criticism in online and printed publications.<ref name=\"IGNReadersGuide\">{{cite web|url=http://anime.ign.com/articles/834/834323p1.html|title=IGN: Naruto Reader's Guide|website=[[IGN]]|last=Sparrow|first=A. E.|date=November 9, 2007|access-date=December 22, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216195848/http://anime.ign.com/articles/834/834323p1.html|archive-date=February 16, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Reviewing the series' first part, writers said they enjoyed Sasuke's fights but disapproved of his dark personality, which resembled the stereotypical rival in [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/6181360/index.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=newsfeatures&tag=newsfeatures;title;1|title=Franchise Player: Naruto|website=[[GameSpot]]|last=Dodson|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2007|access-date=December 24, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025053616/http://www.gamespot.com/features/6181360/index.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=newsfeatures&tag=newsfeatures%3Btitle%3B1|archive-date=October 25, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-gn-8-10|title=Naruto G.novel 8\u201310|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Kimlinger|first=Carl|date=November 2, 2006|access-date=April 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204230415/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-gn-8-10|archive-date=February 4, 2010|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=120|title=THEM Anime Reviews 4.0 \u2013 Naruto|website=T.H.E.M. Anime Reviews|last=Christina|first=Ross|access-date=January 24, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608034457/http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=120|archive-date=June 8, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Critics commended the relationship between Sasuke, Naruto, and Sakura; they regarded the characters as complex and mature because of their teamwork and despite their youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/naruto-unleashed-set-11_article_78617.html|title=Naruto Unleashed Set 1.1|website=Mania Entertainment|last=Moure|first=Dani|date=September 1, 2006|access-date=September 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005023611/http://www.mania.com/naruto-unleashed-set-11_article_78617.html|archive-date=October 5, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|year=2009|title=The Rough Guide to Manga|chapter=Naruto|last=Yadao|first=Jason S.|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=978-1858285610|page=159}}</ref> Reviewers considered that the characters' tactics and the emphasis on their rivalry's emotional undercurrents made Sasuke and Naruto's final fight from the story's first part one of the most entertaining in the series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3983/57/|title=Naruto Uncut Box Set 10 Limited Edition (Adnace Review)|date=October 7, 2008|website=Active Anime|access-date=November 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707081528/http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3983/57/|archive-date=July 7, 2011|last=Jones|first=Davey C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/846/846722p1.html|title=Naruto: \"For a Friend\" Review|date=January 22, 2008|website=[[IGN]]|last=White|first=Charles|access-date=November 7, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928211439/http://tv.ign.com/articles/846/846722p1.html|archive-date=September 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and they praised the one-sided romantic relationship between Sasuke and Sakura.<ref>{{cite book|title=New Media Literacies and Participatory Popular Culture Across Borders|page=38|last1=Williams|first1=Bronwyn|last2=Zenger|first2=Amy A.|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0415897686|chapter=My Love}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/23/naruto-an-invitation-from-the-sound-review|title=Naruto: \"An Invitation From The Sound\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=October 23, 2007|last=White|first=Charles|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108141441/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/23/naruto-an-invitation-from-the-sound-review|archive-date=November 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although critics enjoyed Yuri Lowenthal's voicing of Sasuke,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toonzone.net/review-boruto-naruto-movie-kids-mostly-alright/|title=Review: \"Boruto: Naruto the Movie\" \u2013 The Kids Are (Mostly) Alright|website=Toon Zone|access-date=February 24, 2018|date=May 24, 2017}}</ref> Theron Martin of ''ANN'' said the actor had difficulty sounding younger in flashbacks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naruto Season 3 Box Set 1 DVD|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Martin|first=Theron|date=November 7, 2008|access-date=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130902201337/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-season-3-box-set-1/dvd|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-season-3-box-set-1/dvd|archive-date=September 2, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nReviewers were more enthusiastic about Sasuke's character in the second part of the series. Critics stated that his more-emotional demeanor and his conversation with the Nine-Tailed Fox \u2014 a creature sealed within Naruto's body \u2014 made his scenes in ''Naruto: Shippuden'' interesting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/dvd-box-set-4|title=Naruto Shipp\u016bden DVD Box Set 4|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Kimlinger|first=Carl|date=December 12, 2010|access-date=October 8, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119191002/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/dvd-box-set-4|archive-date=November 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/naruto-shippuden-box-set-04-also-wle_article_124771.html|title=Naruto: Shippuden Box Set 04 (also w/LE)|website=Mania Entertainment|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|date=November 17, 2010|access-date=October 8, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119081609/http://www.mania.com/naruto-shippuden-box-set-04-also-wle_article_124771.html|archive-date=November 19, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Jason Thompson (writer)|Jason Thompson]] wrote that Sasuke had not become evil despite siding with the antagonist Orochimaru, lending ambiguity to his character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2014-11-13/naruto-part-ii/.80991|title=House of 1000 Manga Naruto Part II|last=Thompson|first=Jason|date=November 13, 2014|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428143850/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2014-11-13/naruto-part-ii/.80991|archive-date=April 28, 2017|df=|author-link=Jason Thompson (writer)}}</ref> Writers believed Sasuke's fights during the story's first part's climax against Naruto second part had a major impact on the plot and the character,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mangalife.com/features/MangaLifeSpotlightonNaruto.htm|title=MangaLife Spotlight on: Naruto v34-v40!|website=Manga Life|last=Cooper|first=Park|date=March 10, 2009|access-date=September 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326001417/http://www.mangalife.com/features/MangaLifeSpotlightonNaruto.htm|archive-date=March 26, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ANN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-42|title=Naruto GN 42\u201344|last=Brienza|first=Casey|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 25, 2009|access-date=April 25, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426044213/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-42|archive-date=April 26, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.ign.com/naruto-1/86392/feature/los-20-mejores-duelos-de-naruto-y-naruto-shippuden?p=4|title=Los 20 mejores duelos de Naruto y Naruto Shippuden|trans-title=The 20 Best Naruto and Naruto Shippuden Duels|website=es.ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> and they regarded his battles as some of the franchise's best.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Naruto_Shippuden_Box_Set_17.html|title=Anime Review: Naruto Shippuden Box Set 17|website=UK Anime Network|last=Rhodes|first=Dan|date=February 4, 2014|access-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe series finale garnered praise from critics for the intensified rivalry between Naruto and Sasuke because of the characters' similarities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episodes-476-477/.107067|title=Naruto Shippuden Episodes 476\u2013477|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 1, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=October 15, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221112557/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episodes-476-477/.107067|archive-date=December 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/09/30/naruto-shippuden-episode-476-477-anime-review/|title=Naruto: Shippuden Episode #476 \u2013 477 Anime Review|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|date=September 30, 2016|website=The Fandom Post|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007215755/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/09/30/naruto-shippuden-episode-476-477-anime-review/|archive-date=October 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Reviewers also applauded Sasuke's acknowledgement of his crimes, his agreement to go to prison, and his decision to begin a journey of redemption, indicating an acceptance of responsibility for his misdeeds and a response to Sakura's feelings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episode-479/.107635|title=Naruto Shippuden Episode 479|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 14, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=October 15, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016224755/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episode-479/.107635|archive-date=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Writers thought the character's monologue after his final fight with Naruto highlighted his deeper side and that his farewell was a satisfying ending to the final story arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-72/.93358|title=Naruto GN 72|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 4, 2015|last=McNulty|first=Amy|access-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711082141/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-72/.93358|archive-date=July 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/10/14/naruto-shippuden-episode-479-anime-review/|title=Naruto: Shippuden Episode #479 Anime Review|website=The Fandom Post|date=October 14, 2016|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|access-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225001607/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/10/14/naruto-shippuden-episode-479-anime-review/|archive-date=February 25, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSasuke has continued to receive praise following the end of the ''Naruto'' series. Writers considered his fight scenes in ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'' and in particular his teamwork with Naruto to be the best parts of the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/72039/boruto-naruto-the-movie/|title=Boruto \u2013 Naruto the Movie (Blu-ray)|last=Zimmerman|first=Chris|date=March 28, 2017|website=[[DVD Talk]]|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701033907/http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/72039/boruto-naruto-the-movie/|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanator.com/review-boruto-naruto-the-movie-34393.phtml|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie|last=Chiok|first=Christian|date=October 22, 2015|website=Japanator|access-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731004936/http://www.japanator.com/review-boruto-naruto-the-movie-34393.phtml|archive-date=July 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://otakuusamagazine.com/Anime/News1/Boruto-Naruto-the-Movie-Review-6749.aspx|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie Review|last=Hill|first=Alexandria|date=October 8, 2015|website=[[Otaku USA]]|access-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901072314/http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/Anime/News1/Boruto-Naruto-the-Movie-Review-6749.aspx|archive-date=September 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Boruto:_Naruto_the_Movie.html|title=Anime Review: Boruto: Naruto the Movie|website=UK Anime Network|last=Rhodes|first=Dan|date=January 6, 2017|access-date=June 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614133520/http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Boruto%3A_Naruto_the_Movie.html|archive-date=June 14, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with its television series also received critical acclaimed to the point of finding as appealing as the final fight from ''Shippuden'' between Sasuke and Naruto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-next-generations/episode-65/.134480|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 65|website=Anime News Network|access-date=August 18, 2019|date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> A similar assessment was made of Sasuke's characterization as an adult; Chris Beveridge of ''The Fandom Post'' approved of his new personality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/05/10/boruto-chapter-1-manga-review/|title=Boruto Chapter #1 Manga Review|website=The Fandom Post|date=May 10, 2016|access-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701055507/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/05/10/boruto-chapter-1-manga-review/|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Beveridge|first=Chris}}</ref> Critics also commented that Sasuke had become more caring toward his daughter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/08/24/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-21-sasuke-and-sarada-review|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 21: \"Sasuke and Sarada\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=August 24, 2017|access-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831045904/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/08/24/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-21-sasuke-and-sarada-review|archive-date=August 31, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Stewart|first=Sam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/06/230036|title=In Boruto, Sasuke Is a Jerk Who Loves His Daughter|website=Anime Now|date=September 6, 2017|access-date=September 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906182539/http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/06/230036|archive-date=September 6, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Iikura|first=Ken}}</ref> and they said the ''Boruto'' anime had developed Sasuke as a father and a husband and had solidified his relationship with his wife, Sakura,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/the-seventh-hokage-and-the-scarlet-spring/gn/.96890|title=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=December 27, 2015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=May 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/15/230004|title=Sasuke & Sakura's Marriage Has a Balance That's Hard to See|website=Anime Now|date=September 15, 2017|access-date=September 15, 2017|last=Nelkin|first=Sarah|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917141306/http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/15/230004|archive-date=September 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> despite his flawed interaction with his family due to his mission to stop Kaguya's followers in order to atone for his past actions and protect his hometown in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/08/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-23-bonds-come-in-all-shapes-review|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 23: \"Bonds Come In All Shapes\" Review|last=Stewart|first=Sam|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 8, 2017|access-date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908204431/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/08/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-23-bonds-come-in-all-shapes-review|archive-date=September 8, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fandompost.com/2019/09/04/boruto-naruto-next-generations-set-2-blu-ray-anime-review/|title=Boruto Naruto Next Generations Set 2 Blu-ray Anime Review|publisher=Fandom Post|author=Beveridge, Chris|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Sasuke's interaction with Boruto also earned praise by ''Anime News Network'' for how supportive he is on his student when Boruto is depressed about his father's disappearance and he encourages to join his rescue team to find him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-next-generations/episode-63/.133556|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 66|website=Anime News Network|access-date=August 18, 2019|date=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nScholars have also analyzed the character. According to a study of readers' abilities to predict character types based on physical cues, Sasuke was classified as an INTJ ([[Myers\u2013Briggs Type Indicator|Myers-Briggs]]) character type, making him a [[Foil (literature)|foil]] for Naruto.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chen|first1=Ming-Hung|last2=Chen|first2=I-Ping|title=The Relationship Between Personalities and Faces of Manga Characters|journal=The Comics Grid: Journal of Comics Scholarship|date=June 8, 2015|volume=4|issue=1|doi=10.5334/cg.bc|doi-access=free}}</ref> Rik Spanjers regarded Sasuke's dissimilarity to Naruto as tragic but wrote that the contrast between the protagonists' approaches to the world was fundamental to the plot: \"Naruto's strength grows as he gains more loved ones to protect, while Sasuke remains alone and is increasingly absorbed by his quest for revenge\".<ref name=\"Spanjers\">{{cite book|title=Critical Survey of Graphic Novels : Manga|date=2013|publisher=Salem Press|isbn=978-1-58765-955-3|pages=215\u2013221|chapter=Naruto|chapter-url-access=subscription|chapter-url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=88265667&site=ehost-live|via=[[EBSCOhost]]|last1=Spanjers|first1=Rik|editor1-last=Beaty|editor1-first=Bart H.|editor2-last=Weiner|editor2-first=Stephen|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420045729/http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=88265667&site=ehost-live|archive-date=April 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to academic Amy Plumb, Kishimoto's references to [[Japanese mythology]] in ''Naruto'', including the heraldic symbol of Sasuke's clan \u2014 a fan known as an ''[[uchiwa]]'' \u2014 added layers to the story and Sasuke's ability to 'blow away' the Nine-Tailed Fox's influence on Naruto resembled the mythological use of the fan to dispel evil.<ref name=\"Plumb\">{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Japanese Religion, Mythology, and the Supernatural in Anime and Manga|journal=The International Journal of the Humanities|volume=8|issue=5|issn=1447-9508|last=Plumb|first=Amy|pp=237\u2013246}}</ref> Beatriz Pe\u00f1a viewed Sasuke's antagonism in the series as a result of the war theme often shown throughout the story, with the Uchihas having been slaughtered due to a possible civil war against Konohagakure, which expanded the connection between him and Naruto.<ref>{{cite book|title=Popular Culture: A Reader|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iFwxBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&dq=sasuke+uchiha#v=onepage&q=sasuke%20uchiha&f=false|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|page=109|last=Pe\u00f1a|first=Beatriz|work=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n:{{Portal|Anime and manga}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Sasuke Uchiha}}\n\n{{Naruto}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uchina, Sasuke}}\n[[Category:Naruto characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional ninja]]\n[[Category:Fictional illusionists]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional amputees]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with electric or magnetic abilities]]\n[[Category:Child characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Male characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in anime and manga]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Uchiha|other characters named Uchiha|List of Naruto characters}}{{Hatnote|For other uses of the word \u2018Sasuke\u2019, check [[Sasuke (disambiguation)]].}}{{short description|Fictional character from \"Naruto\".}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox animanga character\n| name       = Sasuke Uchiha\n| series     = [[Naruto]], [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]\n| image      = SasukeKishimoto.jpg\n| caption    = Sasuke Uchiha as seen in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] (right), [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]] (left), and the finale as well as the [[Boruto: Naruto the Movie|''Boruto'' film]] and [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|series]] (middle)\n| alt        = Three forms of a black-haired fictional character showing his teenage self (left), his adult self (middle), and his child self (right)  \n| first      = ''Naruto'' chapter 3: Enter Sasuke! (1999)\n| creator    = [[Masashi Kishimoto]]\n| voiced by  = '''Japanese'''<br> [[Noriaki Sugiyama]]<br />'''English''' <br />[[Yuri Lowenthal]]\n| paux1      = <!-- Fugaku and Mikoto are not notable. Do not add them. --> [[Itachi Uchiha]] (brother, deceased)<br>[[Sakura Haruno|Sakura Uchiha]] (wife)\n[[Sarada Uchiha]] (daughter)\n| paux1 name = Notable relatives\n| paux2      = Genin in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]]<br> Missing-Nin in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part II)|Part II]]\n| paux2 name = Ninja rank\n| paux3      = [[List of Naruto characters#Team 7|Team 7]] ([[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]])<br>[[List of Naruto characters#Taka|Taka]] ([[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]])\n| paux3 name = Ninja team\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Sasuke Uchiha'''|\u3046\u3061\u306f \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1|Uchiha Sasuke|lead=yes}} ({{IPAc-en|'|s|\u0251\u02d0|s|k|e\u026a|}}) is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in the ''[[Naruto]]'' [[manga]] and [[anime]] franchise created by [[Masashi Kishimoto]]. Sasuke belongs to the Uchiha clan, a notorious [[ninja]] family, and one of the most powerful, allied with {{nihongo|Konohagakure|\u6728\u30ce\u8449\u96a0\u308c\u306e\u91cc||English version: \"Hidden Leaf Village\"}}. Most of its members were massacred by Sasuke's older brother, [[Itachi Uchiha]], before the series began, leaving Sasuke one of the few living. Despite becoming empathetic toward his teammates [[Naruto Uzumaki]] and [[Sakura Haruno]], Sasuke's feelings of powerlessness force him to abandon his friends and his home in his quest to become stronger, and to find [[Orochimaru (Naruto)|Orochimaru]]. Sasuke appears in several of the series' [[Naruto#Films|animated feature films]] and related media, including [[List of Naruto video games|video games]], [[Naruto#Original video animations|original video animations]] ([[original video animations|OVAs]]), and ''[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2015) and its manga [[sequel]], ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' (2016), in which he is depicted as a [[vigilante]] supporting his village and a mentor to Naruto's son [[Boruto Uzumaki]].\n\nKishimoto conceived Sasuke as a rival of the series' title character Naruto Uzumaki. Despite Sasuke's dark [[character arc|character development]] later in the story, Kishimoto avoided portraying him as a villain; he found designing the character challenging and had difficulty creating a suitable look for him. Nonetheless, Kishimoto has grown to enjoy drawing him. In the manga's animated adaptations, Sasuke was voiced by [[Noriaki Sugiyama]] in Japanese and [[Yuri Lowenthal]] in English.\n\nSasuke's character has received mixed responses from anime and manga publications. His impressive fighting skills, plot contribution, and rivalry with Naruto Uzumaki received some praise, but he was criticized as a stereotypical rival in the mold of similar characters from other [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] and as exhibiting a cold personality. Nevertheless, Sasuke's characterization in latter parts of the story and more mature personality in the ''Boruto'' sequels earned further positive comments. Sasuke has also placed highly in ''Naruto'' reader popularity polls and has also been the subject of studies by scholars. Character-based merchandise, including [[action figure]]s and [[Keychain|key chains]], has been released.\n\n=={{anchor|Creation and conception}}Creation==\n===Development===\n[[Manga]] artist [[Masashi Kishimoto]] did not include Sasuke Uchiha in his original concept for the ''[[Naruto]]'' series, a story revolving around the character [[Naruto Uzumaki]]. Discussing the series' future, his editor, Kosuke Yahagi, advised him to add a rival character for the [[protagonist]] Naruto and he created Sasuke.<ref>{{cite book|issue=April 2007|year=2007|title=Shonen Jump|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|page=366|issn=1545-7818|title-link=Shonen Jump (magazine)}}</ref> The character's first name came from [[Sanpei Shirato]]'s manga ''Sasuke'' and [[Sarutobi Sasuke]], a fictional [[ninja]] character in Japanese children's stories.<ref name=\"sarutobi\">{{cite journal|date=August 2007|title=Interview: Tracking Down the Source|journal=Shonen Jump Naruto Collector 3|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> To introduce Sasuke, Kishimoto wrote a chapter that was set before the formation of his ninja squad, [[List of Naruto characters#Team 7|Team 7]]. The idea was scrapped; Yahagi told Kishimoto to focus the series' first two chapters on introducing Naruto instead and the focus on Sasuke and the rest of the supporting characters were shown in the next chapters for the first time.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Jump Square]]|title=Naruto: The Beginning|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|issue=12\u201314|date=December 2014|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015[\u79d8\u4f1d\u00b7\u7686\u306e\u66f8]\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret \u00b7 Everyone's Book Official Premium Fan|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|date=December 4, 2009|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|isbn=978-4-08-874834-4|series=[[Naruto]]|page=190|language=Japanese|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> \n\nKishimoto had read a variety of manga to obtain ideas for the creation of an effective rivalry between two characters, which he incorporated into Naruto and Sasuke's relationship. He was also inspired by his relationship with his twin brother, [[Seishi Kishimoto]]; since childhood, Masashi had worried about Seishi when he faced failure and had tried to help him.<ref name=\"finale\">{{cite magazine|magazine=Entermix|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]|issue=November 2014|year=2014|language=Japanese|title=\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8 \u672c\u5f53\u306b\u7d42\u308f\u3063\u3061\u3083\u3046\u306e?|trans-title=Naruto Is it really going to end?|page=70|asin=B01LEPKJ28}}</ref> To contrast Sasuke with Naruto, Kishimoto made him less emotional and depicted him as a \"cool genius\"; he felt he had created an ideal rivalry in the pair,<ref>{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=140|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> and when one character progressed he ensured the other did as well.<ref name=wsja/> Kishimoto wanted Naruto and Sasuke to seem like brothers and rivals, building on a mutual experience of childhood loneliness. Although Sasuke does not regard Naruto as a worthy opponent at first, he is surprised by Naruto's [[character arc|growth]] and becomes fiercely competitive. In the [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] finale, their rivalry leads to a fight and they grow further apart. Kishimoto said he did not want Sasuke to recognize Naruto as an equal until later in [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]].<ref name=\"Kizuna\">{{cite book|title=Naruto\uff0d\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\uff0d\u540d\u8a00\u96c6\u3000\u7d46\uff0dKizuna\uff0d\u3000\u5929\u30ce\u5dfb|trans-title=Naruto Bonds: The Words That React|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|year=2013|isbn=978-4-08-720681-4|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|pages=188\u2013195|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref>\n\nWhen plot developments made Sasuke one of the story's [[antagonist]]s, Kishimoto called him and Naruto [[yin and yang]] because of their differences and complementary natures.<ref name=wsja>{{cite journal|date=February 2012|title=Interview with Masashi Kishimoto (Creator of Naruto)|journal=[[Weekly Shonen Jump Alpha]]|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|issue=2\u201306\u201312|pages=120\u2013123|last=Kido|first=Misaki C.}}</ref> During this period, he was asked whether Sasuke was good or evil; he replied that Sasuke was neither and called him a \"very pure person.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=February 2014|title=Interview with Masashi Kishimoto (Creator of Naruto)|url=http://shonenjump.viz.com/node/1962|journal=[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|issue=2\u201303\u201314|quote='''Masashi Kishimoto:''' Sasuke is basically a very pure person who does not think about whether what he does is good or bad. He just does what he does which causes troubles for others.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222040608/http://shonenjump.viz.com/node/1962|archive-date=February 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said although some of Sasuke's actions such as following his clan's ideas were positive, his self-centeredness tended to cause problems with others. Since the beginning of the story's serialization, Kishimoto planned to conclude the series with a fight between Sasuke and Naruto, but he was uncertain whether the characters would end up as friends or enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/cool_japan/style/AJ201411100007|title=Masashi Kishimoto: Fan letters from overseas made me realize the popularity of 'Naruto'|date=November 10, 2014|website=ajw.asahi.com|publisher=Asashi|access-date=November 10, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110064229/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/cool_japan/style/AJ201411100007|archive-date=November 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although both characters had used ninja techniques throughout the series, Kishimoto wanted the two fighters to rely on hand-to-hand combat for the climax of their final battle.<ref name=\"Koba\"/> He decided to have Naruto forgive Sasuke because he had also forgiven [[List of Naruto characters#Nagato|Nagato]], another former enemy.<ref name=\"comiconinter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94186|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019091230/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94186|archive-date=October 19, 2016|title=Masashi Kishimoto at New York Comic-con The Anime News Network Interview|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Aoki|first=Deb|date=October 14, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe final fight between Sasuke and Naruto was considered one of the biggest challenges ever faced by the staff from [[Pierrot (company)|Pierrot]] as it took an entire month to adapt it from the manga. Director Hiroyuki Yamashita elected himself in charge of the battle which left most of the anime members relieved due to his experience. For the scenario, Pierrot received assistance from [[CyberConnect2]], the video game development studio who had already adapted this battle through the fighting game ''[[Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4]]''. There was a need to make every movement in the fight look realistic, giving Sasuke a scary look as well as hair movement in order to express the idea of both fighters willing to do anything to kill each other, which confused some due to Naruto's wish to avoid this fate. The final clash between Sasuke's Chidori and Naruto's Rasengan moves involved references from other scenes of the series to gave the viewer a bigger emotional impact. The staff noted that following this fight, Sasuke's face became calmer despite his initial look, giving room to explore his redemption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pierrot2.com/naruto/2016/10/03/%E3%83%A9%E3%82%B9%E3%83%88%E3%83%90%E3%83%88%E3%83%AB%E3%81%AE%E8%A3%8F%E8%A9%B1/|title=\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u30d0\u30c8\u30eb\u306e\u88cf\u8a71|publisher=Pierrot|language=Japanese|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKishimoto found Sasuke a difficult character to write, requiring considerable planning. In the series finale, Sasuke leaves on a solo journey; Kishimoto later stated that in addition to atonement, Sasuke wants to discover the origin of the final antagonist, but this was not explained in the story.<ref name=\" finale\"/> He planned Sasuke and [[Sakura Haruno]]'s romance early in ''Naruto''{{'s}} production and decided that despite having a good relationship with his allies, Sasuke would remain a rogue ninja at the end of the series.<ref name=\"cinema\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/page/A0004639|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie|website=CinemaToday.jp|language=Japanese|publisher=Cinema Today|access-date=June 14, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617171917/http://www.cinematoday.jp/page/A0004639|archive-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKishimoto wished to further explore Sasuke's role in the series after ''Naruto''{{'s}} finale. He wanted to explain the connection between Sasuke and Sakura in the [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] manga ''[[Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring]]'' (2015), which focuses on their daughter, [[Sarada Uchiha]]. Despite their separation during Sasuke's mission, which draws him away from his village, the story explains the bond between the three characters. Kishimoto focused on the final scene of the Uchiha family, which he regards as the spin-off's most important facet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ganganonline.com:80/contents/sukedachi_talk/|title=\u5cb8\u672c\u8056\u53f2\u00d7\u5cb8\u672c\u6589\u53f2 \u53cc\u5b50\u6f2b\u753b\u5bb6\u5144\u5f1f\u5bfe\u8ac7|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|trans-title=Seishi Kishimoto \u00d7 Masashi Kishimoto twin brothers manga artist interview|website=GanganOnline.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807021939/http://www.ganganonline.com/contents/sukedachi_talk/|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Because Sasuke had few appearances in the [[Naruto#Films|''Naruto'' films]], Kishimoto decided to give him a bigger role in ''[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2015), in which he teaches Naruto's firstborn child, [[Boruto Uzumaki]]; a reference to [[Piccolo (Dragon Ball)|Piccolo]] and [[Gohan]] in [[Akira Toriyama]]'s ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' manga series and also depicted in the manga ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' (2016). Kishimoto identified Naruto's fights alongside Sasuke against Momoshiki as the highlights of the film and asked that the film's staff pay close attention to those sequences. Two other scenes written by the staff which surprised Kishimoto were Sasuke's use of one of his [[taijutsu]] moves and the combination of his  [[Susanoo]] technique and Naruto's recreation of the [[List of Naruto characters#Kurama|Nine-Tailed Fox]].<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Boruto: Naruto the Movie]]|year=2015|medium=[[DVD]]}} Studio: [[Pierrot (company)|Pierrot]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u300cBoruto: Naruto the Movie-\u300d\u5267\u573a\u7248\u4e0a\u6620\u524d\u7279\u522b\u8282\u76ee|trans-title=Movie Version Before Screening Special Separation Clause|website=[[AcFun]]|url=http://www.acfun.cn/v/ac2074543|date=August 5, 2015|language=Japanese|access-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107000915/http://www.acfun.cn/v/ac2074543|archive-date=January 7, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = While early designs of Sasuke as seen in [[List of Naruto chapters (Part I)|Part I]] (left) were similar to the final one,<ref name=\"Design\"/> for [[List of Naruto volumes#Part II|Part II]] (right) Kishimoto conceived multiple sketches which were scrapped.<ref name=\"sketch\"/>\n| image1 = SasukeUchihasketch.jpg\n| alt1   = Sketches of a male teenage manga character that include his full body, face, and clan symbol \u2014 the Japanese hand-held fan, also known as an ''uchiwa''\n| width1 = 120\n| image2 = SasukeUchihapartIIbeta.jpg\n| alt2   = Sketches of a male teenage character featured in a manga series\n| width2 = 120\n}}\nKishimoto regarded Sasuke as his most memorable character design because he was developed as Naruto's opposite.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bfBook \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u9663\u306e\u66f8|trans-title=Naruto Character Official Data Book Secret \u00b7 Book of Guys|year=2014|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|pages=378\u2013387|isbn=978-4-08-880263-3|language=Japanese}}</ref> He said the design of Sasuke and his {{nihongo|Sharingan|\u5199\u8f2a\u773c||lit. \"Copy Wheel Eye\", English manga: \"Mirror Wheel Eye\"}} ability were influenced by the character [[List of YuYu Hakusho characters#Hiei|Hiei]] in [[Yoshihiro Togashi]]'s manga series, ''[[YuYu Hakusho]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto\u2015\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8\u2015[\u79d8\u4f1d\u00b7\u7686\u306e\u66f8]\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret \u00b7 Everyone's Book Official Premium Fan|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|date=December 4, 2009|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|isbn=978-4-08-874834-4|series=[[Naruto]]|pages=74\u201381|language=Japanese|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> Sasuke originally had necklaces and ties around his arms and legs because Kishimoto had a habit of giving characters as much ornamentation as possible; realizing he could not draw such a complex character on a weekly basis, Kishimoto simplified the design to a basic contrast with Naruto's costume.<ref name=\"Design\">{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=3|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2004|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|page=26|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> The {{nihongo|Chidori|\u5343\u9ce5||lit. \"One Thousand Birds\"}} \u2014 one of Sasuke and [[Kakashi Hatake]]'s best-known fighting techniques \u2014 originally had a different name that Kishimoto forgot. He found the name \"Chidori\" and its variant, the \"Lightning Blade\", appropriate.<ref name=\"Kizuna\" />\n\nKishimoto considered Sasuke his most challenging character to design and draw. He lacked a clear idea of how his face should look, saying Sasuke seemed older than Naruto, his contemporary,<ref name=\"Face\">{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=124|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> and felt this inconvenience was a result of his inexperience in drawing characters who were mature beyond their years.<ref name=\"Design\" /> Sasuke's hair, which was originally short to save Kishimoto time, slowly grew longer as the series progressed.<ref name=\"Face\" /> Mid-way through Part I, he drew a new costume for Sasuke with belts strapped around his arms and legs, but he returned to the character's original design because it took less time to draw.<ref>{{cite book|title=Uzumaki: the Art of Naruto|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4215-1407-9|page=130|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto}}</ref> Sasuke is his favorite character to draw despite the time and energy required,<ref name=\"Design\" /> and he compared Sasuke with Sakura in difficulty.<ref name=\"Koba\">{{cite AV media|title=\u6f2b\u9053\u30b3\u30d0\u30e4\u30b7\u7b2c13\u53f7\u300cNaruto\u5b8c\u7d50\uff01\u5cb8\u672c\u6589\u53f2SP\u300d|date=December 13, 2014|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Fuji Television]]|trans-title=Kobayashi No. 13 'Completion of Naruto! Masashi Kishimoto SP'}}</ref> Kishimoto's superiors sometimes asked him to redraw parts of the manga that did not illustrate Sasuke well.<ref name=\"Koba\"/>\n\nKishimoto's design focus for Part II was Sasuke's older appearance. Originally, Kishimoto had wanted to draw him as a more attractive person, but the idea was discarded. An outfit he initially planned combined the younger Sasuke's outfit with new, more modern clothes. Kishimoto tried several other looks, including the use of [[Shimenawa]] to evoke the antagonist [[Orochimaru (Naruto)|Orochimaru]], and a [[Polo neck|turtleneck]] and military uniform to connote cleanliness. He avoided the second option due to similarities with cold weather clothing and eventually chose Japanese clothing and a ''[[chokut\u014d]]'' sword.<ref name=\"sketch\">{{cite book|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u8005\u306e\u66f8 \u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bfBook|trans-title=Naruto Secret: Scroll of People Character Official Databook|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|year=2008|isbn=978-4-08-874247-2|page=343|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nFor ''[[The Last: Naruto the Movie]]'', Kishimoto gave Sasuke a new, young-adult design with sharper facial features.<ref name=\"The Last\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-14/the-last-naruto-the-movie-s-sasuke-kakashi-character-designs-unveiled/.81021|title=The Last -Naruto the Movie-'s Sasuke, Kakashi Character Designs Unveiled|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=June 14, 2017|date=November 14, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501012120/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-14/the-last-naruto-the-movie-s-sasuke-kakashi-character-designs-unveiled/.81021|archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> In contrast with the older Naruto, who cut his hair, Sasuke's hairstyle grew longer to cover part of the character's face. In the original concept, the hair hid Sasuke's mysterious left eye \u2014 the {{nihongo|Rinnegan|\u8f2a\u5efb\u773c||lit. \"[[Sa\u1e43s\u0101ra]] Eye\"}}. According to Kishimoto, he decided to give the character a large hood because Sasuke concealed his identity during the events of the film. Sasuke's design was specifically created to support his actions; the area that showed Sasuke had lost his left arm in the ''Naruto'' finale was also covered by his clothes.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u79d8\u4f1d\u30fb\u5217\u306e\u66f8 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30e0\u30fc\u30d3\u30fc\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9Book|trans-title=Naruto Secret: Scroll of Line Official Movie Guidebook|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|pages=63\u201364|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|Voice actors and personality}}Personality and voice actors===\n[[File:Yuri Lowenthal by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|[[Yuri Lowenthal]], voice of Sasuke in the anime's English-language version|alt=A middle-aged, Caucasian man with short, dark hair, wearing a black jacket and speaking into a microphone]]\n\nSasuke is voiced by [[Noriaki Sugiyama]] in Japanese media. At the beginning of [[Naruto#Anime|the anime's first part]], Sugiyama had difficulty voicing Sasuke because he knew little about his personality; he began to understand the character at the point in the story where Sasuke encounters his brother, [[Itachi Uchiha]]. Sugiyama read the manga and became particularly interested in Sasuke's development when the character left Konohagakure; he wanted to revoice some scenes from the [[anime]], including Sasuke's departure from Konohagakure.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[V Jump]]|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|pages=320\u2013321|title=\u30a4\u30bf\u30c1\u306e\u30a8\u30cb\u30b0\u30de|trans-title=The Enigma that is Itachi|issue=March 2016|year=2016|language=Japanese}}</ref> In ''Behind the Scenes of Uchiha'', a feature about Sasuke and Itachi's backstory, Sugiyama said he had become emotional during the recording sessions of the sixth season of [[Naruto#Naruto: Shippuden|the anime's second part]] (''Naruto: Shippuden''), in which Sasuke learns the truth about his brother's role in the massacre of the Uchiha clan.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u75be\u98a8\u4f1d \u5e2b\u306e\u4e88\u8a00\u3068\u5fa9\u8b90|trans-title=Naruto Shippuden Master's Prophecy and Vengeance 6|publisher=[[Aniplex]]|year=2011|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nSugiyama thought Sasuke's line, \"You are annoying,\" summed up the character's feelings toward Sakura and indicated a change in their relationship each time it was said; although she initially annoys him, he smiles when he repeats it before leaving Konohagakure. Naruto's Japanese voice actress, [[Junko Takeuchi]], said  Sasuke's line addressed to Sakura, \"See you next time... Thank you,\" revealed his feelings for her. Sugiyama stated that by the end of the series, Sasuke realized how much he had hurt Sakura's feelings and apologized to her after his final fight against Naruto because of this. While recording for ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', Sugiyama expected to see a bond between Sasuke and his apprentice, Boruto Uzumaki.<ref>{{cite magazine|transcript=http://imgur.com/a/D4DoR|title=\u6f14\u8005\u3082\u30ef\u30af\u30ef\u30af\u3057\u3001\u9a5a\u3044\u305f\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u885d\u6483\u7684\u306a\u5c55\u958b\n|trans-title=Even the actors are excited, the shocking unfolding of the surprising ending|magazine=Da Vinci|year=2015|issue=May|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]|pages=32\u201335}}</ref> According to  Sugiyama, Sasuke's personality had changed for the [[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations#Anime plot|''Boruto'' anime series]], and the actor wanted fans to see the character's interaction with his family.<ref name=\"boruto\">{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/naruto-side-story-to-get-an-episode-in-boruto/|title=Naruto Side Story to Get an Episode in Boruto|website=Manga Tokyo|last=Kitahata|first=Yukihiro|access-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017202900/https://manga.tokyo/news/naruto-side-story-to-get-an-episode-in-boruto/|archive-date=October 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Japanese rock band [[Scenarioart]] in charge of performing the ending theme song of this story arc were given directions by Pierrot to make the song show the distant but caring relationship between Sasuke and Sarada. As a result, although the lyrics often mentions the farewells Sasuke and Sarada had, the intention was meant to make it look optimistic as they are destined to meet once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cho-animedia.jp/music/25027/|title=Boruto Ed|publisher=Animedia|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Yuri Lowenthal]], who voices Sasuke in the English [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubs]], said he was honored to receive the role since many actors had auditioned for it, and he added that the job was stressful. Although fans were critical of deviations and mistakes in his recordings,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ds.ign.com/articles/720/720129p1.html|title=Comic-Con 2006: Naruto Party Interview|website=[[IGN]]|last=Bozon|first=Mark|date=July 21, 2006|access-date=December 30, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071204211110/http://ds.ign.com/articles/720/720129p1.html|archive-date=December 4, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he enjoyed voicing the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamingunion.net/interviews/2386/yuri-lowenthal-on-prince-of-persia-amongst-other-things/|title=Yuri Lowenthal On Prince of Persia, Amongst Other Things|last=Alessandra|first=Lauren|website=Gaming Union|date=August 6, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150627165520/http://www.gamingunion.net/interviews/2386/yuri-lowenthal-on-prince-of-persia-amongst-other-things/|access-date=June 13, 2017|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> His first impression of Sasuke was of \"a serious guy dedicated to his training\", but his view changed as he learned about the character's backstory.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Naruto Collector<!--correct name needed-->|journal=Naruto Collector|issue=June 2006|year=2006|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> Lowenthal said in 2010 that Sasuke was one of the first dark characters he voiced, adding, \"He's sort of a hero, but he's not the na\u00efve, young [[Black and white hat symbolism in film|white\u2013hat hero]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticalgamer.co.uk/2010/06/07/yuri-lowenthal-mcm-expo-2010-interview-part-one/|title=Yuri Lowenthal: MCM Expo 2010 interview (part one)|last=K.|first=Luke|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131125234019/http://www.criticalgamer.co.uk/2010/06/07/yuri-lowenthal-mcm-expo-2010-interview-part-one/|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 25, 2013|df=|website=Critical Gamer}}</ref> Lowenthal said that some of Sasuke's lines, such as his use of the word \"kill\", were changed because [[Viz Media]] often censored parts of the series' dialogue for Western viewers. As a result, he found the original Japanese version truer to the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2006/03/01/yuri-lowenthal-speaks-about-sasuke/|title=Yuri Lowenthal Speaks about Sasuke|date=March 1, 2006|website=Siliconera|access-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912234830/http://www.siliconera.com/2006/03/01/yuri-lowenthal-speaks-about-sasuke/|archive-date=September 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Character==\n[[File:Sasuke Uchiha kusanagi 02.JPG|thumb|A replica of Sasuke's [[Kusanagi]] sword|alt=A plain sword in a sheath]]\n\nSasuke is introduced in Part I as a young, spiky-black-haired pre-teen wearing a blue shirt with an image of a fan that represents his clan on its back. He also wears short white pants and a Konohagakure headband.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 3|isbn=978-1-56931-900-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Early in the series, Orochimaru brands Sasuke with a Cursed Seal that, when activated, covers his body with black marks and later gives him gray skin, white hair, and claw-like wings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 232|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> In Part II, he is normally depicted wearing a white [[kimono]] and black pants. Although he is skilled in the use of [[shuriken]], in Part II Sasuke uses a ''chokut\u014d'' sword that he calls [[Kusanagi]]. In addition to using Kusanagi for [[kenjutsu|swordsmanship]], Sasuke combines it with lightning-based techniques to increase the power of his attacks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=34|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 308|isbn=978-1-4215-2002-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=42|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 389|isbn=978-1-4215-2843-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> In ''The Last: Naruto the Movie'', his adult wardrobe consists of gray pants and a light-brown cloak over a black shirt,<ref name=\"The Last\"/> while in  ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', he wears black pants and a black cape over a lilac vest.<ref name=\"cinema\"/>\n\nSasuke is a silent character who tries to gain more power and kill his older brother, Itachi, for betraying and murdering their clan.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 4|isbn=978-1-56931-900-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He cares about his teammates and saves them on numerous occasions,<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2004\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=3|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 27|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=15|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 133|isbn=978-1-4215-1089-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=16|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 138|isbn=978-1-4215-1090-3|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> but he severs all of his bonds later in Part I, believing this will strengthen him. Sasuke is moved when Naruto Uzumaki wants him to make peace with the village; he considers Naruto his only friend.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2015\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=72|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 698|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke becomes more kindhearted by the end of the series, but he decides not to return home, chooses to redeem himself, and searches for an enemy threatening the peace of Konohagakure.<ref name=\"renamed_from_699_on_20170915212700\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n==={{anchor|In ''Naruto''}}In ''Naruto''===\n====In Part I====\nSasuke is introduced in the third chapter of ''Naruto''{{'}}s manga as a young ninja assigned to become a member of Team&nbsp;7 alongside his rival Naruto Uzumaki and Sakura Haruno, the latter of whom is infatuated with him.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 3|isbn=1-56931-900-6|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> The trio are trained under the guidance of Kakashi Hatake.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto|volume=2|year=2003|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 8|isbn=978-1-59116-178-3|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Although Sasuke is antisocial, cold, and distant, he starts caring about Naruto and Sakura.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=3|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 19|page=40|isbn=978-1-59116-187-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> During a mission, Sasuke awakens his Sharingan \u2014 his clan's inherited ability to see through illusions \u2014 which allows him to learn imperceptible movements at a superhuman rate.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2004\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 230|pages=74\u201375|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> It is revealed later that Sasuke is the sole survivor of the once-powerful Uchiha clan of Konohagakure. He, at the age of seven, survived the massacre of his clan perpetrated by his brother, Itachi, who spared Sasuke's life because he did not consider him worth killing.<ref name=\"Resolution\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=25|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 225|isbn=978-1-4215-1861-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke seeks strong fighting opponents to reassure himself his power is growing.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=5|year=2004|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 38|isbn=978-1-59116-359-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\nDuring a ninja examination meant to improve their ranks, Team&nbsp;7 encounters Orochimaru, an exile from Konohagakure who afflicts Sasuke with a Cursed Seal that contains a fragment of Orochimaru's consciousness, which increases Sasuke's physical abilities, but makes him cruel and sadistic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=7|year=2005|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 56|isbn=978-1-59116-875-1|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=21|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 184|pages=[https://archive.org/details/narutovol21pursu21kish/page/68 68\u201372]|isbn=978-1-4215-1855-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Kakashi teaches Sasuke the lightning-based offensive technique called Chidori in an attempt to appease Sasuke's desire for power.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=15|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 128|pages=[https://archive.org/details/narutovol21pursu21kish/page/35 35\u201336]|isbn=978-1-4215-1855-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> During a siege of Konohagakure, a [[Beserker|beserker ninja]] named [[Gaara]] beats Sasuke, who is rescued by Naruto. Shortly afterward, Itachi returns to the village; Sasuke tries to kill him, but he is beaten and tortured instead. Shaken by the experience he decides to leave Team&nbsp;7 and Konohagakure to become stronger.<ref name=\"Corruption\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=20|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 176|isbn=978-1-4215-1655-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Thinking Orochimaru's training will make him more powerful, Sasuke becomes an outlaw.<ref name=\"Defection\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=20|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 179|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781421516554/page/155 155\u2013157]|isbn=978-1-4215-1655-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Naruto follows him and they fight when Sasuke refuses to return; Sasuke wins, spares Naruto's life, and continues to Orochimaru's hideout.<ref name=\"Decision\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=26|year=2007|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 234|pages=161\u2013163|isbn=978-1-4215-1862-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\n====In Part II====\nAfter two-and-a-half years of training, Sasuke absorbs Orochimaru before he can possess his younger body.<ref name=\"Betrayal\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=38|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 343|isbn=978-1-4215-2174-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Following this, Sasuke forms [[List of Naruto characters#Taka|Team Hebi]] to find Itachi.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=42|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 380|isbn=978-1-4215-2843-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Itachi and Sasuke fight and Itachi dies at the climax of the battle from an illness.<ref name=\"Brotherly\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=43|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 401|isbn=978-1-4215-2929-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke then meets [[List of Naruto characters#Obito Uchiha|Tobi]], Itachi's superior, who reveals that Itachi killed the Uchiha clan under orders from Konohagakure and spared Sasuke out of love rather than contempt.<ref name=\"Brotherly\"/> Sasuke rejoins Hebi \u2014 which he renames Taka \u2014 and declares his intention to destroy his former village in retribution. Due to his brother's death, Sasuke's Sharingan has evolved into a {{nihongo|Mangekyo Sharingan|\u4e07\u83ef\u93e1\u5199\u8f2a\u773c|Mangeky\u014d Sharingan|lit. \"Kaleidoscope Copy Wheel Eye\"}}, giving him powerful new techniques.<ref name=\"Vengeance\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=43|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 402|isbn=978-1-4215-2929-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> After he agrees to work temporarily for Tobi's terrorist organization, [[List of Naruto characters#Akatsuki|Akatsuki]], Sasuke becomes a criminal.<ref name=\"ch419\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=45|year=2009|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 419|isbn=978-1-4215-3135-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He kills [[List of Naruto characters#Danzo Shimura|Danzo Shimura]] \u2014 a mastermind of the Uchiha massacre and the acting Hokage, the leader of Konohagakure, at the time.<ref name=\"ch457\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=49|year=2010|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 457|isbn=978-1-4215-3475-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke is confronted by his former Team&nbsp;7 colleagues, and Naruto challenges him to a death match.<ref name=\"ch486\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=52|year=2011|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 486|isbn=978-1-4215-3957-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\nSasuke initially prepares to fight Naruto but instead decides to protect Konohagakure after he encounters the re-animated bodies of Itachi<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=62|year=2012|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 590|isbn=978-4-08-870515-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> and the [[List of Naruto characters#Hashirama Senju|First Hokage]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=62|year=2012|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 593|isbn=978-4-08-870515-6|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=65|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 627|isbn=978-1-4215-6455-5|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> He rejoins Team&nbsp;7 and fights the Ten-Tails monster that is controlled by the masterminds behind Akatsuki.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=66|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 631|isbn=978-1-4215-6948-2|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=68|year=2014|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 655|isbn=978-1-4215-7682-4|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke inherits the Rinnegan \u2014 a legendary eye technique \u2014 from the spirit of the Sage of the Six Paths Hagoromo Otsutsuki, the Founder of Shinobi. Team&nbsp;7 fights and seals an ancient being called [[List of Naruto characters#Kaguya \u014ctsutsuki|Kaguya Otsutsuki]] \u2014 Hagoromo's mother \u2014 who created the Ten-Tails.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=70|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 679|isbn=978-1-4215-7975-7|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> Sasuke then fights Naruto alone to settle their village's future;<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=72|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|chapter=Chapter 692|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> when he loses his left arm, Sasuke surrenders and reconciles with Naruto.<ref name=\"Kishimoto 2015\"/> Sasuke then destroys Akatsuki's illusion placed on mankind with his Rinnegan. He is pardoned for his crimes by Kakashi \u2014 the current Hokage \u2014 and decides to travel the world in search of redemption. Before leaving, he says farewell to both Sakura and Naruto with gratitude.<ref name=\"renamed_from_699_on_20170915212700\">{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=72|year=2015|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 699|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> By the end of the manga, having briefly returned to the village, Sasuke is revealed to have married Sakura who is raising their daughter Sarada.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto|volume=72|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4215-8284-9|chapter=Chapter 700|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref>\n\n===In the ''Boruto'' franchise===\nIn the ''Naruto'' spin-off manga, ''Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring'', and the ''Boruto: Naruto Next Generations'' anime (2017), Sasuke has left Konohagakure sometime after Sarada's birth on a secret mission to investigate a possible threat relating to Kaguya, traveling across the world and Kaguya's dimensions for clues while aiding the other villages in secret. In the ''Boruto'' anime, Sasuke briefly returns to his village before the [[Story arc|arc]] begins and asks Naruto to offer Sakura his apologies.<ref name=\"boruto\"/> He rejoins Naruto to oppose Orochimaru's former test subject [[List of Naruto characters#Shin Uchiha|Shin]], who takes the Uchiha surname for his own while seeking to avenge Itachi and revive the Akatsuki to end the peace. After defeating Shin and his clone children, Sasuke bonds with his daughter for the first time and resumes his mission.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring|year=2016|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|isbn=978-1421584935|title-link=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring}}</ref> A novel by Mirei Miyamoto focuses on Sasuke's work in his village where he replaces [[List of Naruto characters#Konohamaru Sarutobi|Konohamaru Sarutobi]] as the leader of Boruto, Sarada, and [[Mitsuki (Naruto)|Mitsuki]]'s team.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Sasuke Shinden: The Teacher's Star Pupil|isbn=978-4-08-703450-9|year=2018|last1=Miyamoto|first1=Mirei|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1\u65b0\u4f1d \u5e2b\u5f1f\u306e\u661f}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'', also covered in both the ''Boruto'' manga and anime, Sasuke returns to Konohagakure to warn Naruto of the threat posed by Kaguya's kinsmen [[List of Naruto characters#Momoshiki \u014ctsutsuki|Momoshiki Otsutsuki]] and [[List of Naruto characters#Kinshiki \u014ctsutsuki|Kinshiki Otsutsuki]], who seek the tailed beast chakra for their end.<ref name=BorutoTheMovie>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-the-movie/.93939|title=Boruto -Naruto the Movie-|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 9, 2015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=April 20, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420100434/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-the-movie/.93939|archive-date=April 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|last1=Kishimoto|first1=Masashi|last2=Ikemoto|first2=Mikio|last3=Kodachi|first3=Ukyo|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2017|isbn=9781421592114|volume=1|chapter=1|author1-link=Masashi Kishimoto|author2-link=Mikio Ikemoto|title-link=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations}}</ref> He meets Naruto's son, Boruto, and becomes the boy's mentor once having him learn to use his father's {{nihongo|Rasengan|\u87ba\u65cb\u4e38||lit. spiral sphere, English manga: \"Spiral Chakra Sphere\"}}. When the Otsutsuki members abduct Naruto during the Chunin Exam, Sasuke is accompanied by Boruto as he and the Kage \u2014 the leaders of the ninja villages \u2014 travel to Momoshiki's planet to save Naruto. Sasuke then aids Naruto and Boruto in defeating Momoshiki, who absorbs Kinshiki to increase his power.<ref name=BorutoTheMovie/> After Momoshiki's defeat, Sasuke notices the enemy has placed a seal on Boruto.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations|last1=Kishimoto|first1=Masashi|last2=Ikemoto|first2=Mikio|last3=Kodachi|first3=Ukyo|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|year=2018|isbn=978-1-4215-9822-2|volume=3|chapter=Chapter 11|author1-link=Masashi Kishimoto|author2-link=Mikio Ikemoto|title-link=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations}}</ref> The anime has Sasuke searching Urashiki Otsutsuki alongside Gaara.<ref>{{cite episode|title=With Sasuke As The Goal|series=[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]|airdate=August 18, 2019|publisher=Studio Pierrot}}</ref> In the manga, Sasuke later travels to an Otsutsuki site where he finds records on the Otsutsuki clan which include some of its members that came to his world, learning that Kara's leader Jigen is somehow connected to Kaguya. He aids Naruto against Jigen, but the Konohagakure ninjas are overwhelmed in combat and Sasuke is forced to escape back to Konoha as Naruto is sealed away by the enemy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-37/chapter/19050 |title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations, Chapter 37 |website=[[Viz.com]] |accessdate=20 August 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820163234/https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-37/chapter/19050 |archivedate=20 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-38/chapter/19053 |title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations, Chapter 38 |website=[[Viz.com]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920174122/https://www.viz.com/shonenjump/boruto-chapter-38/chapter/19053 |archivedate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===In other media===\n\nSasuke appears in the first four [[Naruto#Original video animations|original video animations]] ([[original video animations|OVAs]]) produced for the series. In the first episode, he helps Naruto and Konohamaru find a [[four-leaf clover]];<ref name=\"loststory\">{{cite AV media|date=2007|title=Naruto OVA \u2013 The Lost Story|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=Viz Video|url=http://www.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=8722|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217110548/http://www.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=8722|archive-date=December 17, 2007|df=mdy-all|access-date=August 29, 2013}}</ref> in the second, he joins Naruto's team for a mission;<ref name=\"loststory\"/> he participates in a tournament in the third; and he works with Team 7 in the fourth.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2005|title=\u3064\u3044\u306b\u6fc0\u7a81\uff01\u4e0a\u5fcdVS\u4e0b\u5fcd\uff01\uff01\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u5927\u4e71\u6226\u5927\u4f1a\u958b\u50ac\uff01\uff01|trans-title=Finally a clash! Jonin VS Genin!! Indiscriminate grand melee tournament meeting!!|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[TV Tokyo]]|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000BNPT3E/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-30/naruto-toriko-one-piece-event-anime-shorts-streamed|date=November 30, 2009|title=Naruto, Toriko, One Piece Event Anime Shorts Streamed|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=November 30, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108105635/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-30/naruto-toriko-one-piece-event-anime-shorts-streamed|archive-date=November 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> One OVA presents an alternate fight between Sasuke and Naruto in ''Naruto: Shippuden''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-12-20/naruto-anime-dvd-offered-at-uniqlo-t-shirt-stores|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106114433/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-12-20/naruto-anime-dvd-offered-at-uniqlo-t-shirt-stores|archive-date=November 6, 2016|date=December 20, 2010|title=News: Naruto Anime DVD Offered at Uniqlo T-Shirt Stores|website=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The character is present in the first two ''Naruto'' feature films; he guards a princess in ''[[Naruto the Movie: Ninja Clash in the Land of Snow]]'' (2004) and makes a brief appearance in a flashback in ''[[Naruto the Movie: Legend of the Stone of Gelel]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2007|title=Naruto the Movie: Ninja Clash in the Land of Snow|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=Viz Video|url=http://www.viz.com/anime/dvd/naruto-the-movie-video-volume-1/6828|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323191537/http://www.viz.com/anime/dvd/naruto-the-movie-video-volume-1/6828|archive-date=March 23, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The first Part II film in which he appears is ''[[Naruto Shippuden 2: Bonds]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2011|title=Naruto Shippuden: The Movie \u2013 Bonds|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005DVIPE4/}}</ref> The sixth Part II film, ''[[Road to Ninja: Naruto the Movie]]'' (2012), contains a flirtatious, alternate-reality version of Sasuke.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2012|title=Road to Ninja: Naruto the Movie|format=[[DVD]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00Q4F7FDK/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212013938/https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00Q4F7FDK/|archive-date=December 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In ''The Last: Naruto the Movie'' (2014), an adult Sasuke returns briefly to Konohagakure to protect it from a meteor.<ref>{{cite AV media|date=2015|title=The Last: Naruto the Movie|format=[[Blu-ray]]|publisher=[[Viz Video]]|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00ZCHTRKA/}}</ref>\n\nHe is a recurring character in the ''Naruto'' [[light novels]] and the protagonist of the manga ''Naruto Jinraiden: The Day the Wolf Howled'' (2012), which explores Sasuke's reflections after Itachi's death and his decision to destroy Konohagakure.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Naruto Jinraiden: The Day the Wolf Howled|isbn=978-4-08-703279-6|year=2012|last1=Higashiyama|first1=Akira|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title=Naruto -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u8fc5\u96f7\u4f1d \u72fc\u306e\u54ed\u304f\u65e5}}</ref> In ''Sakura Hiden'' (2015), an adult Sasuke continues his journey of redemption but returns to Konohagakure out of concern for Sakura's safety.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Naruto: Sakura's Story \u2014 Love Riding the Spring Breeze|isbn=978-1-42-158442-3|year=2016|last1=Tomohito|first1=\u014csaki|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|title=\u30b5\u30af\u30e9\u79d8\u4f1d \u601d\u604b\u3001\u6625\u98a8\u306b\u306e\u305b\u3066}}</ref> In ''Akatsuki Hiden'' (2015), Sasuke meets two children who tell him stories about Akatsuki, and they discuss Itachi's legacy.<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: \u6681\u79d8\u4f1d \u54b2\u304d\u4e71\u308c\u308b\u60aa\u306e\u83ef|isbn=978-4-08-703367-0|year=2015|last1=Towada|first1=Shin|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|language=Japanese|trans-title=Naruto Akatsuki Hiden: Evil Flowers in Full Bloom|publisher=[[Shueisha]]}}</ref> He is the protagonist of ''Sasuke Shinden'' (2015); he agrees to aid Konohagakure by investigating a series of disappearances, which he solves with the help of Taka and a Konohagakure ninja named [[List of Naruto characters#Sai|Sai]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: Sasuke's Story \u2014 Sunrise|isbn=978-1-42-159129-2|year=2017|last1=Towada|first1=Shin|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi|author2-link=Masashi Kishimoto|publisher=[[Viz Media]]}}</ref> Sasuke is also the protagonist of manga artist Kenji Taira's ''Naruto'' spin-off, ''Sasuke Uchiha's Sharingan Legend'' (2014), in which he and Taka search for Itachi. According to Taira, Sasuke would be characterized as an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Naruto: Chibi Sasuke's Sharingan Legend|volume=1|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|page=1|last=Taira|first=Kenji|year=2017|isbn=978-1421597102}}</ref> A new novel focused on Sasuke's life as an adult alongside Sakura, ''Sasuke Retsuden: The Uchiha Descendants and the Heavenly Stardust'' (2019), was written by Jun Esaka.<ref>{{cite book|trans-title=Sasuke Retsuden: The Uchiha Descendants and the Heavenly Stardust|title=NARUTO -\u30ca\u30eb\u30c8- \u30b5\u30b9\u30b1\u70c8\u4f1d\u3000\u3046\u3061\u306f\u306e\u672b\u88d4\u3068\u5929\u7403\u306e\u661f\u5c51|publisher=Shueisha|year=2019|isbn=978-4-08-703481-3|last1=Esaka|first1=Jun|last2=Kishimoto|first2=Masashi}}</ref>\n\nSasuke is a [[player character|playable character]] in [[List of Naruto video games|''Naruto'' video games]], including the [[Naruto: Clash of Ninja|''Clash of Ninja'']] and [[Naruto: Ultimate Ninja|''Ultimate Ninja'']] series.<ref name=\"IGNCoN2GuidePage1\">{{cite web|url=http://cube.ign.com/articles/736/736611p1.html|title=Naruto: The Complete Fighter Profile|last=Bozon|first=Mark|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 29, 2006|access-date=January 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516171031/http://cube.ign.com/articles/736/736611p1.html|archive-date=May 16, 2010|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"IGNCoN3HandsOn\">{{cite web|url=http://cube.ign.com/articles/551/551374p1.html|title=TGS 2004: Naruto Gekitou Ninja Taisen! 3 Hands-on|last=Alfonso|first=Andrew|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 26, 2004|access-date=January 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304010910/http://cube.ign.com/articles/551/551374p1.html|archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GUIDE1 26\">{{cite book|title=Naruto: Ultimate Ninja English instruction manual|year=2006|publisher=[[Bandai Namco]]|page=26}}</ref> His Cursed Seal can be unlocked and activated in some games. Due to his absence from early ''Naruto: Shippuden'' episodes, Sasuke has not appeared in any games based on ''Naruto: Shippuden'' until the launch of ''[[Naruto: Clash of Ninja#Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Gekit\u014d Ninja Taisen! EX (Wii series)|Gekitou Ninja Taisen EX 2]]'' and ''[[Naruto Ultimate Ninja#Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Ultimate Ninja 5|Ultimate Ninja 5]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"VJump 54-55\">{{cite book|title=V Jump|year=2007|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|language=Japanese|pages=54\u201355|title-link=V Jump}}</ref> Sasuke is also present in [[Crossovers in video games|crossover]] games, such as ''[[Jump Super Stars]]'' (2005), ''[[Jump Ultimate Stars]]'' (2006), ''[[Battle Stadium D.O.N]]'' (2006), ''[[J-Stars Victory VS]]'' (2014), and ''[[Jump Force]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajsj/char11.html|title=Jump Super Stars -Characters|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|website=nintendo.co.jp|language=Japanese|access-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630171117/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajsj/char11.html|archive-date=June 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajuj/character/chara_24.html|title=Jump Ultimate Stars Characters|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|website=nintendo.co.jp|language=Japanese|access-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630184517/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/ajuj/character/chara_24.html|archive-date=June 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2013-08-28/naruto/dragon-ball/toriko-rivals-transformations-in-j-stars-victory-vs-game|title=Naruto/Dragon Ball/Toriko Rivals, Transformations in J-Stars Victory Vs. Game|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 28, 2013|access-date=August 29, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828221406/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2013-08-28/naruto/dragon-ball/toriko-rivals-transformations-in-j-stars-victory-vs-game|archive-date=August 28, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2006/07/31/battle-stadium-don/|title=Battle Stadium D.O.N.|website=Siliconera|access-date=December 11, 2017|date=July 31, 2006|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609202559/http://www.siliconera.com/2006/07/31/battle-stadium-don/|archive-date=June 9, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Popularity===\nSasuke has ranked among the top-five ''Naruto'' characters in every ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]'' popularity poll of the series. Initially alternating between third and fourth places, he has finished first twice.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=28|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 245|pages=[https://archive.org/details/naruto00kish_2/page/8 8\u20139]|isbn=978-1-4215-1864-0|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kishimoto|first=Masashi|title=Naruto|volume=33|year=2008|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|chapter=Chapter 293|isbn=978-1-4215-2001-8|author-link=Masashi Kishimoto|title-link=Naruto}}</ref> A popularity poll on the Japanese website ''Charapedia'' ranked Sasuke and Naruto's rivalry as the best in anime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/LatestNews/News1/Japanese-Fans-Rank-Animes-Most-Memorable-Rivalries-6620.aspx|title=Japanese Fans Rank Anime's Most Memorable Rivalries|last=Schley|first=Matt|website=[[Otaku USA]]|access-date=October 22, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721132127/http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/LatestNews/News1/Japanese-Fans-Rank-Animes-Most-Memorable-Rivalries-6620.aspx|archive-date=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Similarly, Sasuke was voted as the second best rival in manga and anime in a poll by ''Anime Anime''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otakuusamagazine.com/animes-greatest-rivals/|title=Japanese Fans Rank Anime's Greatest Rivals|website=[[Otaku USA]]|publisher=Sovereign Media|access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref> At New York's 2015 [[New York Comic Con|Comic-Con]], moderator Christopher Butcher and editor Jo Otsuki commented that Sasuke had become the series' most popular character, and Otsuki called him his favorite. Butcher wondered whether readers considered Sasuke a more-relatable character after he had embraced Naruto's positive outlook on life in the series finale. According to Otsuki, fans regarded Sasuke's character and abilities as \"cooler\" than those of his rival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94188|title=Part II \u2013 An Evening with Masashi Kishimoto|date=October 14, 2015|access-date=June 9, 2017|last=Aoki|first=Deb|website=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529004749/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2015-10-14/masashi-kishimoto-at-new-york-comic-con/.94188|archive-date=May 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jacob Hope of ''[[Anime News Network]]'' (''ANN'') listed Sasuke and Naruto as two of the \"Fiercest Frenemies\" in anime due to their resemblance despite being adversaries and their need to engage in a mortal fight to become friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-06-08/anime-fiercest-frenemies/.102975|title=Anime's Fiercest Frenemies|last=Chapman|first=Jacob Hope|date=June 8, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=July 1, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029002837/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-06-08/anime-fiercest-frenemies/.102975|archive-date=October 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a Tokyo Otaku Mode poll, Sasuke was deemed the sixth best character women would want to have a date with.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://otakumode.com/release/2013-12-02-1|title=Tokyo Otaku Mode Fall 2013 User Poll|date=December 1, 2013|website=Otaku Mode|access-date=May 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Merchandise===\nSasuke merchandise includes [[keychain|key chains]]<ref name=\"SasukeKeyChain\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Keychains-Sasuke-PVC-Keychain/products_id/112321.html|title=Naruto \u2013 Keychains \u2013 Sasuke PVC Keychain|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529152728/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Keychains-Sasuke-PVC-Keychain/products_id/112321.html|archive-date=May 29, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[action figure|figurines]].<ref name=\"VizActionFigures\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttc/action-figures/cPath/10175_10219.html|title=Naruto Toys \u2013 Action Figures at Official Naruto Store|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203090007/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttc/action-figures/cPath/10175_10219.html|archive-date=February 3, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"SasukeActionFigure\">{{cite web|url=http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Action-Figure-Sasuke-Premium-Sculpt-8-Figure/products_id/111604.html|title=Naruto \u2013 Toys \u2013 Sasuke Roto 8\" Figure|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|website=NarutoStore.Viz.com|access-date=January 24, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212191811/http://narutostore.viz.com/ttp/Naruto-Action-Figure-Sasuke-Premium-Sculpt-8-Figure/products_id/111604.html|archive-date=February 12, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/10/30/love-and-ninja-included-in-new-naruto-prize-figure-lottery|title=Love and Ninja Included in New \"Naruto\" Prize Figure Lottery|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=October 31, 2012|access-date=May 11, 2018|first=Scott|last=Green|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511124633/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/10/30/love-and-ninja-included-in-new-naruto-prize-figure-lottery|archive-date=May 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Boruto'' film audiences were offered fans bearing images of Sasuke and his daughter, Sarada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-07-28/naruto-creator-on-being-asked-for-sequel-please-let-me-rest-now/.90993|title=Naruto Creator on Being Asked for Sequel: 'Please Let Me Rest Now'|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 28, 2015|access-date=October 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701042712/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-07-28/naruto-creator-on-being-asked-for-sequel-please-let-me-rest-now/.90993|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \nTo promote the video game ''[[Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4]]'', two 1/6-scale statues depicting Sasuke and Naruto during their final clash from the series were developed by Luxembourgian company Tsume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2015-12-09/namco-bandai-europe-teases-naruto-shippuden-ultimate-ninja-storm-4-bonus-figures/.96300|title=Namco Bandai Europe Teases Naruto Shipp\u016bden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 4 Bonus Figures|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 9, 2015|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801054224/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2015-12-09/namco-bandai-europe-teases-naruto-shippuden-ultimate-ninja-storm-4-bonus-figures/.96300|archive-date=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nJapanese toy company [[Bandai]] released an action figure of Sasuke performing the Chidori move.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-02-21/figure-build-close-up-2016-s.h-figuarts-naruto-and-sasuke/.112477|title=Figure Build Close-up: 2016 S.H. Figuarts Naruto & Sasuke|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 21, 2017|access-date=February 22, 2018|last=Orsini|first=Lauren|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801151320/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-02-21/figure-build-close-up-2016-s.h-figuarts-naruto-and-sasuke/.112477|archive-date=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2017, Bandai launched a figurine of Sasuke performing his Susanoo eye technique, which represents the god of thunder [[Raijin]]. [[Studio Pierrot]] released artwork that was sold alongside this figure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-05-16/naruto-sasuke-god-figures-make-a-storm-this-september/.116103|title=Naruto, Sasuke God Figures Make a Storm This September|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731132511/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2017-05-16/naruto-sasuke-god-figures-make-a-storm-this-september/.116103|archive-date=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bandai also produced a limited-edition adult figurine of Sasuke as he appears in the ''Naruto'' finale and the ''Boruto'' franchise, which impressed Scott Green, a writer for [[Ain't It Cool News]] and [[Crunchyroll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/03/14-1/limited-boruto-naruto-the-movie-sasuke-uchiha-gem-figure-planned|title=Limited \"Boruto -Naruto The Movie-\" Sasuke Uchiha G.E.M. Figure Planned|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|publisher=[[Otter Media]]|last=Green|first=Scott|date=March 14, 2016|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711081449/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/03/14-1/limited-boruto-naruto-the-movie-sasuke-uchiha-gem-figure-planned|archive-date=July 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://p-bandai.jp/item/item-1000103229/|title=G.E.M.\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba Boruto -Naruto the Movie- \u3046\u3061\u306f\u30b5\u30b9\u30b1|website=P-Bandai.jp|publisher=[[Bandai]]|language=Japanese|trans-title=G.E.M. Series Boruto -Naruto the Movie- Sasuke Uchiha|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715041536/http://p-bandai.jp/item/item-1000103229/|archive-date=July 15, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:F\u00e4cher04.JPG|thumb|upright|The Eastern fan (''[[uchiwa]]'') is Sasuke's clan symbol.<ref name=\"Plumb\"/>|alt=A white Eastern fan, with pink and purple flowers]]\n\nSasuke's character has received both praise and criticism in online and printed publications.<ref name=\"IGNReadersGuide\">{{cite web|url=http://anime.ign.com/articles/834/834323p1.html|title=IGN: Naruto Reader's Guide|website=[[IGN]]|last=Sparrow|first=A. E.|date=November 9, 2007|access-date=December 22, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216195848/http://anime.ign.com/articles/834/834323p1.html|archive-date=February 16, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Reviewing the series' first part, writers said they enjoyed Sasuke's fights but disapproved of his dark personality, which resembled the stereotypical rival in [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/6181360/index.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=newsfeatures&tag=newsfeatures;title;1|title=Franchise Player: Naruto|website=[[GameSpot]]|last=Dodson|first=Joe|date=October 13, 2007|access-date=December 24, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025053616/http://www.gamespot.com/features/6181360/index.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=newsfeatures&tag=newsfeatures%3Btitle%3B1|archive-date=October 25, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-gn-8-10|title=Naruto G.novel 8\u201310|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Kimlinger|first=Carl|date=November 2, 2006|access-date=April 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204230415/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-gn-8-10|archive-date=February 4, 2010|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=120|title=THEM Anime Reviews 4.0 \u2013 Naruto|website=T.H.E.M. Anime Reviews|last=Christina|first=Ross|access-date=January 24, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608034457/http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=120|archive-date=June 8, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Critics commended the relationship between Sasuke, Naruto, and Sakura; they regarded the characters as complex and mature because of their teamwork and despite their youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/naruto-unleashed-set-11_article_78617.html|title=Naruto Unleashed Set 1.1|website=Mania Entertainment|last=Moure|first=Dani|date=September 1, 2006|access-date=September 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005023611/http://www.mania.com/naruto-unleashed-set-11_article_78617.html|archive-date=October 5, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|year=2009|title=The Rough Guide to Manga|chapter=Naruto|last=Yadao|first=Jason S.|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=978-1858285610|page=159}}</ref> Reviewers considered that the characters' tactics and the emphasis on their rivalry's emotional undercurrents made Sasuke and Naruto's final fight from the story's first part one of the most entertaining in the series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3983/57/|title=Naruto Uncut Box Set 10 Limited Edition (Adnace Review)|date=October 7, 2008|website=Active Anime|access-date=November 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707081528/http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3983/57/|archive-date=July 7, 2011|last=Jones|first=Davey C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/846/846722p1.html|title=Naruto: \"For a Friend\" Review|date=January 22, 2008|website=[[IGN]]|last=White|first=Charles|access-date=November 7, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928211439/http://tv.ign.com/articles/846/846722p1.html|archive-date=September 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and they praised the one-sided romantic relationship between Sasuke and Sakura.<ref>{{cite book|title=New Media Literacies and Participatory Popular Culture Across Borders|page=38|last1=Williams|first1=Bronwyn|last2=Zenger|first2=Amy A.|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0415897686|chapter=My Love}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/23/naruto-an-invitation-from-the-sound-review|title=Naruto: \"An Invitation From The Sound\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=October 23, 2007|last=White|first=Charles|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108141441/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/23/naruto-an-invitation-from-the-sound-review|archive-date=November 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although critics enjoyed Yuri Lowenthal's voicing of Sasuke,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toonzone.net/review-boruto-naruto-movie-kids-mostly-alright/|title=Review: \"Boruto: Naruto the Movie\" \u2013 The Kids Are (Mostly) Alright|website=Toon Zone|access-date=February 24, 2018|date=May 24, 2017}}</ref> Theron Martin of ''ANN'' said the actor had difficulty sounding younger in flashbacks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naruto Season 3 Box Set 1 DVD|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Martin|first=Theron|date=November 7, 2008|access-date=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130902201337/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-season-3-box-set-1/dvd|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-season-3-box-set-1/dvd|archive-date=September 2, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nReviewers were more enthusiastic about Sasuke's character in the second part of the series. Critics stated that his more-emotional demeanor and his conversation with the Nine-Tailed Fox \u2014 a creature sealed within Naruto's body \u2014 made his scenes in ''Naruto: Shippuden'' interesting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/dvd-box-set-4|title=Naruto Shipp\u016bden DVD Box Set 4|website=[[Anime News Network]]|last=Kimlinger|first=Carl|date=December 12, 2010|access-date=October 8, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119191002/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/dvd-box-set-4|archive-date=November 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/naruto-shippuden-box-set-04-also-wle_article_124771.html|title=Naruto: Shippuden Box Set 04 (also w/LE)|website=Mania Entertainment|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|date=November 17, 2010|access-date=October 8, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119081609/http://www.mania.com/naruto-shippuden-box-set-04-also-wle_article_124771.html|archive-date=November 19, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Jason Thompson (writer)|Jason Thompson]] wrote that Sasuke had not become evil despite siding with the antagonist Orochimaru, lending ambiguity to his character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2014-11-13/naruto-part-ii/.80991|title=House of 1000 Manga Naruto Part II|last=Thompson|first=Jason|date=November 13, 2014|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428143850/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2014-11-13/naruto-part-ii/.80991|archive-date=April 28, 2017|df=|author-link=Jason Thompson (writer)}}</ref> Writers believed Sasuke's fights during the story's first part's climax against Naruto second part had a major impact on the plot and the character,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mangalife.com/features/MangaLifeSpotlightonNaruto.htm|title=MangaLife Spotlight on: Naruto v34-v40!|website=Manga Life|last=Cooper|first=Park|date=March 10, 2009|access-date=September 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326001417/http://www.mangalife.com/features/MangaLifeSpotlightonNaruto.htm|archive-date=March 26, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ANN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-42|title=Naruto GN 42\u201344|last=Brienza|first=Casey|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 25, 2009|access-date=April 25, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426044213/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-42|archive-date=April 26, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.ign.com/naruto-1/86392/feature/los-20-mejores-duelos-de-naruto-y-naruto-shippuden?p=4|title=Los 20 mejores duelos de Naruto y Naruto Shippuden|trans-title=The 20 Best Naruto and Naruto Shippuden Duels|website=es.ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> and they regarded his battles as some of the franchise's best.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Naruto_Shippuden_Box_Set_17.html|title=Anime Review: Naruto Shippuden Box Set 17|website=UK Anime Network|last=Rhodes|first=Dan|date=February 4, 2014|access-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe series finale garnered praise from critics for the intensified rivalry between Naruto and Sasuke because of the characters' similarities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episodes-476-477/.107067|title=Naruto Shippuden Episodes 476\u2013477|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 1, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=October 15, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221112557/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episodes-476-477/.107067|archive-date=December 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/09/30/naruto-shippuden-episode-476-477-anime-review/|title=Naruto: Shippuden Episode #476 \u2013 477 Anime Review|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|date=September 30, 2016|website=The Fandom Post|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007215755/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/09/30/naruto-shippuden-episode-476-477-anime-review/|archive-date=October 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Reviewers also applauded Sasuke's acknowledgement of his crimes, his agreement to go to prison, and his decision to begin a journey of redemption, indicating an acceptance of responsibility for his misdeeds and a response to Sakura's feelings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episode-479/.107635|title=Naruto Shippuden Episode 479|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=October 14, 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=October 15, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016224755/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto-shippuden/episode-479/.107635|archive-date=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Writers thought the character's monologue after his final fight with Naruto highlighted his deeper side and that his farewell was a satisfying ending to the final story arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-72/.93358|title=Naruto GN 72|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 4, 2015|last=McNulty|first=Amy|access-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711082141/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/gn-72/.93358|archive-date=July 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/10/14/naruto-shippuden-episode-479-anime-review/|title=Naruto: Shippuden Episode #479 Anime Review|website=The Fandom Post|date=October 14, 2016|last=Beveridge|first=Chris|access-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225001607/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/10/14/naruto-shippuden-episode-479-anime-review/|archive-date=February 25, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSasuke has continued to receive praise following the end of the ''Naruto'' series. Writers considered his fight scenes in ''Boruto: Naruto the Movie'' and in particular his teamwork with Naruto to be the best parts of the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/72039/boruto-naruto-the-movie/|title=Boruto \u2013 Naruto the Movie (Blu-ray)|last=Zimmerman|first=Chris|date=March 28, 2017|website=[[DVD Talk]]|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701033907/http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/72039/boruto-naruto-the-movie/|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanator.com/review-boruto-naruto-the-movie-34393.phtml|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie|last=Chiok|first=Christian|date=October 22, 2015|website=Japanator|access-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731004936/http://www.japanator.com/review-boruto-naruto-the-movie-34393.phtml|archive-date=July 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://otakuusamagazine.com/Anime/News1/Boruto-Naruto-the-Movie-Review-6749.aspx|title=Boruto: Naruto the Movie Review|last=Hill|first=Alexandria|date=October 8, 2015|website=[[Otaku USA]]|access-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901072314/http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/Anime/News1/Boruto-Naruto-the-Movie-Review-6749.aspx|archive-date=September 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Boruto:_Naruto_the_Movie.html|title=Anime Review: Boruto: Naruto the Movie|website=UK Anime Network|last=Rhodes|first=Dan|date=January 6, 2017|access-date=June 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614133520/http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Boruto%3A_Naruto_the_Movie.html|archive-date=June 14, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with its television series also received critical acclaimed to the point of finding as appealing as the final fight from ''Shippuden'' between Sasuke and Naruto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-next-generations/episode-65/.134480|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 65|website=Anime News Network|access-date=August 18, 2019|date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> A similar assessment was made of Sasuke's characterization as an adult; Chris Beveridge of ''The Fandom Post'' approved of his new personality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandompost.com/2016/05/10/boruto-chapter-1-manga-review/|title=Boruto Chapter #1 Manga Review|website=The Fandom Post|date=May 10, 2016|access-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170701055507/http://www.fandompost.com/2016/05/10/boruto-chapter-1-manga-review/|archive-date=July 1, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Beveridge|first=Chris}}</ref> Critics also commented that Sasuke had become more caring toward his daughter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/08/24/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-21-sasuke-and-sarada-review|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 21: \"Sasuke and Sarada\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|date=August 24, 2017|access-date=August 30, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831045904/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/08/24/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-21-sasuke-and-sarada-review|archive-date=August 31, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Stewart|first=Sam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/06/230036|title=In Boruto, Sasuke Is a Jerk Who Loves His Daughter|website=Anime Now|date=September 6, 2017|access-date=September 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906182539/http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/06/230036|archive-date=September 6, 2017|df=mdy-all|last=Iikura|first=Ken}}</ref> and they said the ''Boruto'' anime had developed Sasuke as a father and a husband and had solidified his relationship with his wife, Sakura,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/naruto/the-seventh-hokage-and-the-scarlet-spring/gn/.96890|title=Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring|last=McNulty|first=Amy|date=December 27, 2015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=May 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/15/230004|title=Sasuke & Sakura's Marriage Has a Balance That's Hard to See|website=Anime Now|date=September 15, 2017|access-date=September 15, 2017|last=Nelkin|first=Sarah|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917141306/http://www.anime-now.com/entry/2017/09/15/230004|archive-date=September 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> despite his flawed interaction with his family due to his mission to stop Kaguya's followers in order to atone for his past actions and protect his hometown in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/08/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-23-bonds-come-in-all-shapes-review|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 23: \"Bonds Come In All Shapes\" Review|last=Stewart|first=Sam|website=[[IGN]]|date=September 8, 2017|access-date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908204431/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/08/boruto-naruto-next-generations-episode-23-bonds-come-in-all-shapes-review|archive-date=September 8, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fandompost.com/2019/09/04/boruto-naruto-next-generations-set-2-blu-ray-anime-review/|title=Boruto Naruto Next Generations Set 2 Blu-ray Anime Review|publisher=Fandom Post|author=Beveridge, Chris|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Sasuke's interaction with Boruto also earned praise by ''Anime News Network'' for how supportive he is on his student when Boruto is depressed about his father's disappearance and he encourages to join his rescue team to find him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/boruto-naruto-next-generations/episode-63/.133556|title=Boruto: Naruto Next Generations Episode 66|website=Anime News Network|access-date=August 18, 2019|date=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nScholars have also analyzed the character. According to a study of readers' abilities to predict character types based on physical cues, Sasuke was classified as an INTJ ([[Myers\u2013Briggs Type Indicator|Myers-Briggs]]) character type, making him a [[Foil (literature)|foil]] for Naruto.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chen|first1=Ming-Hung|last2=Chen|first2=I-Ping|title=The Relationship Between Personalities and Faces of Manga Characters|journal=The Comics Grid: Journal of Comics Scholarship|date=June 8, 2015|volume=4|issue=1|doi=10.5334/cg.bc|doi-access=free}}</ref> Rik Spanjers regarded Sasuke's dissimilarity to Naruto as tragic but wrote that the contrast between the protagonists' approaches to the world was fundamental to the plot: \"Naruto's strength grows as he gains more loved ones to protect, while Sasuke remains alone and is increasingly absorbed by his quest for revenge\".<ref name=\"Spanjers\">{{cite book|title=Critical Survey of Graphic Novels : Manga|date=2013|publisher=Salem Press|isbn=978-1-58765-955-3|pages=215\u2013221|chapter=Naruto|chapter-url-access=subscription|chapter-url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=88265667&site=ehost-live|via=[[EBSCOhost]]|last1=Spanjers|first1=Rik|editor1-last=Beaty|editor1-first=Bart H.|editor2-last=Weiner|editor2-first=Stephen|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420045729/http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=88265667&site=ehost-live|archive-date=April 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to academic Amy Plumb, Kishimoto's references to [[Japanese mythology]] in ''Naruto'', including the heraldic symbol of Sasuke's clan \u2014 a fan known as an ''[[uchiwa]]'' \u2014 added layers to the story and Sasuke's ability to 'blow away' the Nine-Tailed Fox's influence on Naruto resembled the mythological use of the fan to dispel evil.<ref name=\"Plumb\">{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Japanese Religion, Mythology, and the Supernatural in Anime and Manga|journal=The International Journal of the Humanities|volume=8|issue=5|issn=1447-9508|last=Plumb|first=Amy|pp=237\u2013246}}</ref> Beatriz Pe\u00f1a viewed Sasuke's antagonism in the series as a result of the war theme often shown throughout the story, with the Uchihas having been slaughtered due to a possible civil war against Konohagakure, which expanded the connection between him and Naruto.<ref>{{cite book|title=Popular Culture: A Reader|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iFwxBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&dq=sasuke+uchiha#v=onepage&q=sasuke%20uchiha&f=false|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|page=109|last=Pe\u00f1a|first=Beatriz|work=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n:{{Portal|Anime and manga}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Sasuke Uchiha}}\n\n{{Naruto}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uchina, Sasuke}}\n[[Category:Naruto characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional ninja]]\n[[Category:Fictional illusionists]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional amputees]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with electric or magnetic abilities]]\n[[Category:Child characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Male characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in anime and manga]]\n", "name_user": "2601:410:280:1f70:952:56cc:338d:59e6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sasuke_Uchiha"}
{"title_page": "Man in the Iron Mask", "text_new": "{{about|an aspect of French history}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = \n| image = Man in the Iron Masque crop.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = ''L'Homme au Masque de Fer'' (''The Man in the Iron Mask''). Anonymous print ([[etching]] and [[mezzotint]], hand-colored) from 1789.\n| birth_name = Birth name unknown\n| birth_date = ''c.'' 1640\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = 19 November 1703\n| death_place = Bastille, Paris\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = Saint-Paul Cemetery, Paris\n| residence = \n| nationality = French\n| other_names = Marchioly, Eustache Dauger\n| occupation = \n| known_for = Mystery regarding his identity\n| height = \n| weight = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| criminal_charge = Unknown\n| conviction_status = Died in prison\n| spouse = <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children = <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = <!-- (as above) -->\n| allegiance = <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive = \n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = \n| date = \n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| country = \n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| endyear = \n| apprehended = 1669/70\n| imprisoned = \n| footnotes = \n| penalty = Life imprisonment\n}}\nThe '''Man in the Iron Mask''' (French: ''L'Homme au Masque de Fer''; c. 1640 \u2013 19 November 1703) was an unidentified prisoner who was arrested in 1669 or 1670 and subsequently held in a number of [[Kingdom of France|French]] prisons, including the [[Bastille]] and the Fortress of Pignerol (modern Pinerolo, Italy). He was held in the custody of the same jailer, [[B\u00e9nigne Dauvergne de Saint-Mars]], for a period of 34 years. He died on 19 November 1703 under the name Marchioly, during the reign of King [[Louis XIV of France]] (1643\u20131715). \n\nBecause no one ever saw his face because it was hidden by a mask of black velvet cloth, the true identity of the prisoner remains a mystery; it has been extensively debated by historians, and various theories have been expounded in numerous books and films.\n\nAmong the leading theories are those proposed by writer and philosopher [[Voltaire]]: He claimed in the second edition of his ''Questions sur l'Encyclop\u00e9die'' (1771) that the prisoner wore a mask made of iron rather than of cloth, and that he was the older, illegitimate brother of Louis XIV. What little is known about the historical Man in the Iron Mask is based mainly on correspondence between Saint-Mars and his superiors in Paris. Recent research suggests that his name might have been Eustache Dauger, a man who was involved in several political scandals of the late 17th century, but this assertion has not been proven.\n\nThe [[National Archives of France]] has made available online the original data relating to the inventories of the goods and papers of Saint-Mars (one inventory, of 64 pages, was drawn up at the [[Bastille]] in 1708; the other, of 68 pages, at the [[citadel of Sainte-Marguerite]] in 1691). These documents had been sought in vain for more than a century and were thought to have been lost. They were discovered in 2015, among the 100 million documents of the {{ill|Minutier central des notaires de Paris|fr}}.<ref>Archives nationales de France: salle des inventaires, Archives nationales (accessed 23 January 2017).</ref><ref>Analyse et photographies des documents d\u00e9couverts, https://sergearoles-documents-archives.com/ [archive] (accessed 23 January 2017).</ref> They show that some of the 800 documents in the possession of the jailer Saint-Mars were analysed after his death. These documents confirm the reputed avarice of Saint-Mars, who appears to have diverted the funds paid by the king for the prisoner. They also give a description of a cell occupied by the masked prisoner, which contained only a sleeping mat, but no luxuries, as was previously thought. \n\nWith the scientific support of the [[National Library of France]] collections of ancient textiles, the accuracy of these notary documents discovered in 2015 has allowed the creation of the first virtual reconstruction of the prison of the man in the iron mask.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2010/11/26/bastille-prison-had-5-star-comforts-research-shows/ |title=Bastille prison had 5-star comforts, research shows|publisher=Twin Cities Pioneer Press |date= 2010-11-06|accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Man in the Iron Mask has also appeared in many works of fiction, most prominently in the late 1840s by [[Alexandre Dumas]]. A section of his novel ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]'', the final installment of his [[D'Artagnan Romances|D'Artagnan saga]], features the Man in the Iron Mask. Here the prisoner is forced to wear an iron mask and is portrayed as Louis XIV's identical twin.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" /> Dumas also presented a review of the popular theories about the prisoner extant in his time in the chapter \"L'homme au masque de fer\" in the sixth volume of his non-fiction ''Crimes C\u00e9l\u00e8bres''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/crimesclbres02dumagoog |title=Crimes c\u00e9l\u00e8bres : Alexandre Dumas : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref>\n\n==Prisoner==\n===Arrest and imprisonment===\nThe earliest surviving records of the masked prisoner are from late July 1669, when [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]'s minister, the [[Fran\u00e7ois-Michel le Tellier, Marquis de Louvois|Marquis de Louvois]], sent a letter to [[B\u00e9nigne Dauvergne de Saint-Mars]], governor of the prison of Pignerol, which at the time was part of France. In his letter, Louvois informed Saint-Mars that a prisoner named \"Eustache Dauger\" was due to arrive in the next month or so.\n[[File:Pinerolo 001.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The town of [[Pinerolo]], previously Pignerol, in Piedmont, Italy.]]\n\nLouis XIV instructed Saint-Mars to prepare a cell with multiple doors, one closing upon the other, which were to prevent anyone from the outside listening in. Saint-Mars was to see Dauger only once a day to provide food and whatever else he needed. Dauger was to be told that if he, Dauger, spoke of anything other than his immediate needs he would be killed, but, according to Louvois, the prisoner should not require much since he was \"only a valet\".\n\nHistorians have noted that the name Eustache Dauger was written in a handwriting different from that used in the rest of the letter's text, suggesting that a clerk wrote the letter under Louvois' dictation, while someone else, very likely Louvois, added the name afterward.\n\nDauger was arrested by Captain Alexandre de Vauroy, garrison commander of [[Dunkirk]], and taken to Pignerol, where he arrived in late August. Evidence has been produced to suggest that the arrest was actually made in [[Calais]] and that not even the local governor was informed of the event \u2013 Vauroy's absence being explained away by his hunting for Spanish soldiers who had strayed into France via the [[Spanish Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nThe first rumours of the prisoner's identity (specifically as a [[Marshal of France]]) began to circulate at this point.\n\n===Masked man serves as a valet===\n[[File:La masque de fer.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Illustration, c. 1872]]\n[[File:Masque de fer selon Warin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''L'Homme au masque de fer'', by [[Jean-Joseph Regnault-Warin]]]]\nThe prison at Pignerol, like the others at which Dauger was later held, was used for men who were considered an embarrassment to the state and usually held only a handful of prisoners at a time.\n\nSaint-Mars' other prisoners at Pignerol included Count [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]], an Italian diplomat who had been kidnapped and jailed for double-crossing the French over the purchase of the important fortress town of [[Casale Monferrato|Casale]] on the Italian border. There was [[Nicolas Fouquet]], Marquis of Belle-\u00cele, a former superintendent of finances who had been jailed by Louis XIV on the charge of embezzlement, and the [[Antoine Nompar de Caumont|Marquis de Lauzun]], who had become engaged to the [[Anne, Duchess of Montpensier|Duchess of Montpensier]], a cousin of the king, without the king's consent. Fouquet's cell was above that of Lauzun.\n\nIn his letters to Louvois, Saint-Mars describes Dauger as a quiet man, giving no trouble, \"disposed to the will of God and to the king\", compared to his other prisoners, who were always complaining, constantly trying to escape, or simply mad.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nDauger was not always isolated from the other prisoners. Wealthy and important ones usually had manservants; Fouquet for instance was served by a man called La Rivi\u00e8re. These servants, however, would become as much prisoners as their masters and it was thus difficult to find people willing to volunteer for such an occupation. Because La Rivi\u00e8re was often ill, Saint-Mars applied for permission for Dauger to act as servant for Fouquet. In 1675, Louvois gave permission for such an arrangement on condition that he was to serve Fouquet only while La Rivi\u00e8re was unavailable and that he was not to meet anyone else; for instance, if Fouquet and Lauzun were to meet, Dauger was not to be present.\n\nIt is an important point that the man in the mask served as a valet. Fouquet was never expected to be released; thus, meeting Dauger was no great matter, but Lauzun was expected to be set free eventually, and it would have been important not to have him spread rumours of Dauger's existence. Historians have also argued that 17th-century protocol made it unthinkable that a man of royal blood would serve as a manservant, casting some doubt on speculation that Dauger was in some way related to the king.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\">''The Man in the Iron Mask'', [[Timewatch]] TV documentary presented by [[Henry Lincoln]], [[BBC]], 1988</ref>\n\nAfter Fouquet's death in 1680, Saint-Mars discovered a secret hole between Fouquet and Lauzun's cells. He was sure that they had communicated through this hole without detection by him or his guards and thus that Lauzun must have been made aware of Dauger's existence. Louvois instructed Saint-Mars to move Lauzun to Fouquet's cell and to tell him that Dauger and La Rivi\u00e8re had been released.\n\n===Other prisons===\n[[File:Exilles02.JPG|thumb|200px|right|[[Fortress of Exilles]]]]\n[[File:Lerins-iron mask prison.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[\u00cele Sainte-Marguerite]]]]\nLauzun was freed in 1681. Later that same year, Saint-Mars was appointed governor of the prison of the [[Exilles Fort|Exiles Fort]] (now [[Exilles]] in Italy). He went there, taking Dauger and La Rivi\u00e8re with him. La Rivi\u00e8re's death was reported in January 1687; in May, Saint-Mars and Dauger moved to [[\u00cele Sainte-Marguerite|Sainte-Marguerite]], one of the [[L\u00e9rins Islands]], half a mile offshore from Cannes.\n\nIt was during the journey to Sainte-Marguerite that rumors spread that the prisoner was wearing an iron mask. Again, he was placed in a cell with multiple doors.\n\nOn 18 September 1698, Saint-Mars took up his new post as governor of the [[Bastille]] prison in Paris, bringing Dauger with him. He was placed in a solitary cell in the prefurnished third chamber of the Bertaudi\u00e8re tower. The prison's second-in-command, de Rosarges, was to feed him. Lieutenant du Junca, another officer of the Bastille, noted that the prisoner wore \"a mask of black velvet\".\n\nThe masked prisoner died on 19 November 1703 and was buried the next day under the name of Marchioly.\n\nIn 1711, King Louis's sister-in-law, [[Elizabeth Charlotte, Princess Palatine]], sent a letter to her aunt, [[Sophia of Hanover|Sophia, Electress of Hanover]], stating that the prisoner had \"two [[musketeers]] at his side to kill him if he removed his mask\". She described him as very devout, and stated that he was well treated and received everything he desired. However, the prisoner had already been dead for eight years by that point and the Princess had not necessarily seen him for herself; rather, she was quite likely reporting rumours she had heard at court.\n\n==Popular interest==\nThe fate of the mysterious prisoner \u2013 and the extent of the apparent precautions his jailers took \u2013 created significant interest in his story and gave birth to many legends. Many theories exist and several books have been written about the case. Some were presented after the existence of the letters was widely known. Still later commentators have presented their own theories, possibly based on embellished versions of the original tale.\n\nTheories about his identity popular during his time included that he was a Marshal of France; the English [[Henry Cromwell]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Dumas|first= Alexandre|title= Celebrated Crimes|volume= 6|page=[https://archive.org/details/celebratedcrimes06duma/page/2008 2008] |date=1910|url= https://archive.org/details/celebratedcrimes06duma}}</ref> son of [[Oliver Cromwell]]; or [[Fran\u00e7ois, Duke of Beaufort]]. Later, many people such as [[Voltaire]] and [[Alexandre Dumas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/2751 |title=Gutenberg.org |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=2004-09-22 |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref> suggested other theories about the man in the mask.\n\n==Candidates==\n\n===King's relative===\n[[Voltaire]] claimed that the prisoner was a son of [[Anne of Austria]] and [[Cardinal Mazarin]], and therefore an illegitimate half-brother of [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]]. However, the sincerity of this claim is uncertain.\n\n==== King's twin brother ====\nIn his history essay ''Le Masque de fer'',<ref name=\"Marcel Pagnol\">{{cite book |title=Le Masque de fer |last=Pagnol |first=Marcel |publisher=\u00c9ditions de Provence |year=1965 |pages=chapters 11 & 12}}</ref> French novelist [[Marcel Pagnol]], supporting his theory in particular on the circumstances of King Louis XIV's birth, claims that the Man in the Iron mask was indeed a twin but born second, and hence the younger, and would have been hidden in order to avoid any dispute over the throne holder.<ref name=\"Marcel Pagnol\"/> {{efn|To make the context clearer, note that at the time there was a controversy over which one of twins was the elder: The one born first, or the one born second, who was then thought to have been conceived first.}}\n\nThe historians who reject this theory (including [[:fr:Jean-Christian Petitfils|Jean-Christian Petitfils]]), highlight the conditions of childbirth for the queen: It usually took place in the presence of multiple witnesses \u2013 the main court's figures. But according to Marcel Pagnol, right after the birth of the future Louis XIV, King Louis XIII took his whole court to the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain-en-Laye|''Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain'']]'s chapel to celebrate a ''[[Te Deum]]'' in great pomp, contrary to the common practice of celebrating it several days before childbirth.<ref>{{cite book |title=Suppl\u00e9ment au Corps Universel Diplomatique |volume=IV |page=176 |editor=Dumont, Jean |editor-link=Jean Dumont (publicist)}}</ref>\n\nAlso supporting the theory of King Louis XIV's twin, a thorough examination of the French Kings' genealogy shows many twin births, in the [[Capetian dynasty]], as well as in the [[House of Valois]], [[House of Bourbon|Bourbon]], and the [[House of Orl\u00e9ans]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Yann |last=Kermabon |article=Courrier des lecteurs |title-link=:fr:Historia (revue) |title=Revue Historia |date=October 1998}}</ref>\n\n[[Alexandre Dumas]] explored a similar theory in his book ''[[The Vicomte de Bragelonne]]'', where the prisoner was instead an identical twin of Louis XIV. This book has served as the basis \u2013 even if loosely adapted \u2013 for many [[The Man in the Iron Mask (film)|film versions]] of the story.\n\nAccording to Marcel Pagnol\u2019s theory, this twin was then born in 1638 and grew up on the Island of [[Jersey]] under the name [[James de la Cloche]]. He would later conspire with [[Roux de Marcilly]] against King Louis XIV, and hypothetically was arrested in Calais in 1669.\n\n==== King's father ====\nHugh Ross Williamson<ref name=\"Williamson2002\">{{cite book|title=Who Was The Man In the Iron Mask? and Other Historical Mysteries|first=Hugh Ross|last=Williamson|publisher=Penguin|year=2002|isbn=0-14-139097-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whowasmaninironm00ross}}</ref> argues that the man in the iron mask was the natural father of Louis XIV. According to this theory, the \"miraculous\" birth of Louis XIV in 1638 would have come after [[Louis XIII]] had been estranged from his wife [[Anne of Austria]] for 14 years.\n\nThe theory then suggests that [[Cardinal Richelieu]], the king's minister, had arranged for a substitute, probably an illegitimate son or grandson of [[Henry IV of France|Henry IV]], to become intimate with the queen and father an heir in the king's stead. At the time, the [[heir presumptive]] was Louis XIII's brother [[Gaston, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]], who was Richelieu's enemy. If Gaston became king, Richelieu would quite likely have lost both his job as minister and his life, and so it was in his best interests to thwart Gaston's ambitions.\n\nSupposedly the substitute father then left for the [[New France|Americas]] but in the 1660s returned to France with the aim of extorting money for keeping his secret, and was promptly imprisoned. This theory would explain the secrecy surrounding the prisoner, whose true identity would have destroyed the legitimacy of Louis XIV's claim to the throne had it been revealed.\n\nThis theory was first disputed by British politician [[Hugh Cecil, 1st Baron Quickswood]]. He said the idea has no historical basis and is hypothetical. Williamson held that to say it is a guess with no solid historical basis is merely to say that it is like every other theory on the matter, although it makes more sense than any of the other theories. There is no known evidence that is incompatible with it, even the age of the prisoner, which Cecil had considered a weak point; and it explains every aspect of the mystery.<ref name=\"Williamson2002\" />\n\n===French general===\n{{See also|Great Cipher#The Man in the Iron Mask}}\n\nIn 1890, Louis Gendron, a French military historian, came across some coded letters and passed them on to [[\u00c9tienne Bazeries]] in the French Army's cryptographic department. After three years Bazeries managed to read some messages in the [[Great Cipher]] of Louis XIV. One of them referred to a prisoner and identified him as General {{ill|Vivien de Bulonde|fr|Vivien l'Abb\u00e9 de Bulonde}}. One of the letters written by Louvois made specific reference to de Bulonde's crime.\n\nAt the [[Siege of Cuneo (1691)|Siege of Cuneo]] in 1691, Bulonde was concerned about enemy troops arriving from Austria and ordered a hasty withdrawal, leaving behind his munitions and wounded men. Louis XIV was furious and in another of the letters specifically ordered him \"to be conducted to the fortress at Pignerol where he will be locked in a cell and under guard at night, and permitted to walk the battlements during the day with a 330 309.\" It has been suggested that the 330 stood for ''masque'' and the 309 for full stop. However, in 17th-century French ''avec un masque'' would mean \"in a mask\".\n\nSome believe that the evidence of the letters means that there is now little need of an alternative explanation for the man in the mask. Other sources, however, claim that Bulonde's arrest was no secret and was actually published in a newspaper at the time and that he was released after just a few months. His death is also recorded as happening in 1709, six years after that of the man in the mask.<ref name=\"Noone\">''The Man Behind the Iron Mask'' by John Noone, 1988 {{ISBN|0750906790}}</ref>\n\n===Valet===\nIn 1801, revolutionary legislator Pierre Roux-Fazillac stated that the tale of the masked prisoner was an amalgamation of the fates of two separate prisoners, [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]] (see below) and an imprisoned valet named \"Eustache d'Auger\".\n\n[[Andrew Lang|Lang]] (1903)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Valet's Tragedy and Other Stories |year=1903 |author-link=Andrew Lang |first=Andrew |last=Lang}}</ref> presented a theory that \"Eustache d'Auger\" was a prison pseudonym of a man called \"Martin\", valet of the [[Huguenot]] [[Roux de Marcilly]]. After his master's execution in 1669 the valet was taken to France, possibly by abduction. A letter from the French Foreign minister has been found rejecting an offer to arrest Martin: He was simply not important.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Man in the Iron Mask |first=Harry |last=Thompson |page=77}}</ref>\n\nNoone (1988)<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Noone |title=The Man behind the Mask |page=272 |year=1988}}</ref> pointed out that the minister was concerned Dauger should not communicate, rather than that his face should be concealed. Later, St. Mars elaborated upon instructions that the prisoner should not be seen during transportation. The idea of keeping d'Auger in a velvet mask was St. Mars' own, to increase his self importance. What d'Auger had seen or done is still a mystery.\n\n===Son of Charles II===\nBarnes (1908)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Man of the Mask |year=1908 |first=Arthur |last=Barnes}}</ref> presents [[James de la Cloche]], the alleged illegitimate son of the reluctant Protestant [[Charles II of England]], who would have been his father's secret intermediary with the Catholic court of France.\n\nOne of Charles's confirmed illegitimate sons, the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], has also been proposed as the man in the mask. A Protestant, he led [[Monmouth Rebellion|a rebellion]] against his uncle, the Catholic [[James II of England|King James II]]. The rebellion failed and Monmouth was executed in 1685. But in 1768, a writer named Saint-Foix claimed that another man was executed in his place and that Monmouth became the masked prisoner, it being in Louis XIV's interests to assist a fellow Catholic like James who would not necessarily want to kill his own nephew. Saint-Foix's case was based on unsubstantiated rumors and allegations that Monmouth's execution was faked.<ref name=\"Noone\"/>\n\n===Italian diplomat===\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2019}}\nAnother candidate, much favored in the 1800s, was Fouquet's fellow prisoner Count [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]] (or Matthioli). He was an Italian diplomat who acted on behalf of debt-ridden [[Charles IV, Duke of Mantua]] in 1678, in selling [[Casale Monferrato|Casale]], a strategic fortified town near the border with France. A French occupation would be unpopular, so discretion was essential, but Mattioli leaked the details to France's Spanish enemies, after pocketing his commission once the sale had been concluded, and they made a bid of their own before the French forces could occupy the town. Mattioli was kidnapped by the French and thrown into nearby Pignerol in April 1679. The French took possession of Casale two years later.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n[[George Agar Ellis]] reached the conclusion that Mattioli was the state prisoner commonly called The Iron Mask when he reviewed documents extracted from French archives in the 1820s. His book,<ref>George Agar Ellis, The true history of the State Prisoner commonly called the Iron Mask, here identified with Count E.A. Mattioli, extracted from documents in the French archives (London, J. Murray, 1826)</ref> published in English in 1826, was translated into French and published in 1830. German historian Wilhelm Broecking came to the same conclusion independently seventy years later.  [[Robert Chambers (journalist)|Robert Chambers]]' ''[[Chambers Book of Days|Book of Days]]'' supports the claim and places Matthioli in the Bastille for the last 13 years of his life.\n\nSince that time, letters sent by Saint-Mars, which earlier historians missed, indicate that Mattioli was only held at Pignerol and Sainte-Marguerite and was not at Exilles or the Bastille and, therefore, it is argued that he can be discounted.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" />\n\n===Eustache Dauger de Cavoye===\nIn his letter to Saint-Mars announcing the imminent arrival of the prisoner who would become the \"man in the iron mask,\" Louvois gave his name as \"Eustache Dauger\" and historians have found evidence that a \"Eustache Dauger\" was living in France at the time and was involved in scandalous and embarrassing events involving people in high places known as [[Affair of the Poisons|l'Affaire des Poisons]]. His full name was Eustache Dauger de Cavoye.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n====Early life====\nRecords indicate that he was born on 30 August 1637, the son of Fran\u00e7ois Dauger, a captain in [[Cardinal Richelieu]]'s guards. Fran\u00e7ois was married to Marie de S\u00e9rignan and they had 11 children, nine of whom survived into adulthood. When Fran\u00e7ois and his two eldest sons were killed in battle, Eustache became the nominal head of the family.\n\n====Disgrace====\nIn April 1659, Eustache and Guiche were invited to an Easter weekend party at the castle of Roissy-en-Brie. By all accounts it was a debauched affair of merry-making, with the men involved in all sorts of sordid activities, including attacking a man who claimed to be [[Cardinal Mazarin]]'s attorney. It was also claimed,{{By whom|date=July 2010}} among other things, that a [[black mass]] was enacted and that a pig was baptized as carp in order to allow them to eat pork on Good Friday.\n\nWhen news of these events became public, an inquiry was held and the various perpetrators jailed or exiled. There is no record as to what happened to Dauger, but in 1665, near the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], he allegedly killed a young [[Page (occupation)|page boy]] in a drunken brawl involving the Duc de Foix. The two men claimed that they had been provoked by the boy, who was drunk, but the fact that the killing took place near a castle where the king was staying meant that this was not a good enough explanation, and as a result, Dauger was forced to resign his [[Commissioned officers|commission]].\n\nDauger's mother died shortly afterwards. In her will, written a year previously, she passed over her eldest surviving sons Eustache and Armand, leaving the bulk of the estate to their younger brother Louis. Eustache was restricted in the amount of money to which he had access, having built up considerable debts, and left with barely enough for \"food and upkeep\".{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n====Affair of the Poisons====\n{{main|Affair of the Poisons}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\nIn the 1930s, historian Maurice Duvivier linked Eustache Dauger de Cavoye to the [[Poison affair|Affair of the Poisons]], a notorious scandal of 1677\u20131682 in which people in high places were accused of being involved in [[black mass]] and poisonings. An investigation had been launched, but Louis XIV had instigated a cover-up when it appeared that his mistress [[Fran\u00e7oise-Ath\u00e9na\u00efs, marquise de Montespan|Madame de Montespan]] was involved.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nThe records show that during the inquiry the investigators were told about a supplier of poisons, a surgeon named Auger, and Duvivier became convinced that Dauger de Cavoye, disinherited and short of money, had become Auger, the supplier of poisons, and subsequently Dauger, the man in the mask.\n\nIn a letter sent by Louvois to Saint-Mars shortly after Fouquet's death while in prison (with Dauger acting as his valet), the minister adds a note in his own handwriting, asking how Dauger performed certain acts that Saint-Mars had mentioned in a previous correspondence (now lost) and \"how he got the drugs necessary to do so\". Duvivier suggested that Dauger may have poisoned Fouquet as part of a complex power struggle between Louvois and his rival [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert|Colbert]].\n\n====Dauger in prison====\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\nHowever, evidence has emerged that Dauger de Cavoye actually died in the [[Prison Saint-Lazare]], an asylum run by monks which many families used in order to imprison their \"[[black sheep]]\". Documents have survived indicating that Dauger de Cavoye was held at Saint-Lazare in Paris at about the same time that Dauger, the man in the mask, was taken into custody in Pignerol, hundreds of miles away in the south.\n\nThese include a letter sent to Dauger de Cavoye's sister, the Marquise de Fabr\u00e8gues, dated 20 June 1678, which is filled with self-pity as Eustache complains about his treatment in prison, where he has been held for 10 years, and how he was deceived by their brother Louis and Cl\u00e9rac, their brother-in-law and the manager of Louis' estate. A year later, he wrote a letter to the king, outlining the same complaints and making a similar request for freedom. The best the king would do, however, was to send a letter to the head of Saint-Lazare telling him that \"M. de Cavoye should have communication with no one at all, not even with his sister, unless in your presence or in the presence of one of the priests of the mission\". The letter was signed by the king and Colbert.\n\nA poem written by Louis-Henri de Lom\u00e9nie de Brienne, an inmate at the time, indicates that Eustache Dauger de Cavoye died as a result of heavy drinking in the late 1680s. Historians consider all this proof enough that he was not involved in any way with the man in the mask.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" /><ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Literature===\n* [[Alfred de Vigny]], \"The Prison\" (1821),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/La_Prison_(Vigny) |title=La Prison (Vigny) |via=Wikisource |language=fr|publisher=Fr.wikisource.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref> a long poem describing the final events in the life of the Man in the Iron Mask. An aged priest is called to offer the last rites of the Catholic Church to a mysterious prisoner. After an involved process to ensure the prisoner's anonymity, the priest is introduced to the dying prisoner, who is addressed as \"my prince\" by the jailer. The priest realizes in the dim light that the prisoner wears an iron mask, and recalls the tales he heard in his youth. The prisoner rejects the priest's efforts, even after the priest promises that his lifelong incarceration has already opened Heaven to him if he would only embrace God. The prisoner dies without repenting. The priest continues to pray for the man for several hours, and is horrified to see that the corpse continues to wear the mask underneath the shroud, denied release even in death.\n* [[Alexandre Dumas]], ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later#Part Three: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' (Chapters 181\u2013269)|The Vicomte de Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]'' (1847\u20131850), the final section of which is titled ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' (French: {{lang|fr|L'homme au masque de fer}})\n* [[Henry Vizetelly]], ''The Man With the Iron Mask'' (1870)\n* [[Juliette Benzoni]], ''Secret d'etat''\n* Louis-C\u00e9sar, ''Cassandra Palmer'' series\n* [[Algis Budrys]]'s 1958 science-fiction novel ''[[Who? (novel)|Who? / The Man in the Steel Mask]]'', and the 1973 film based on it, are loosely inspired by the historical affair, placing a similar mystery in a contemporary [[Cold War]] setting. \n* Karleen Koen, ''Before Versailles'', in which the boy in the iron mask is a central issue among the characters.\n* [[Fortun\u00e9 du Boisgobey]], ''Le Vrai Masque de fer'' (1873). The serialized translations of this work in Japan and Korea in the early twentieth century made this the most popular \u201cMan in the Iron Mask\u201d in these countries, more so than the Dumas novel.\n\n===Films and television===\n\n*1909: ''[[La maschera di ferro]]'' \u2013 Italian silent film\n*1923: ''[[Der Mann mit der eisernen Maske]]'' \u2013 German silent film\n*1929: ''[[The Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 An American silent film starring [[Douglas Fairbanks]]\n*1938: ''The Face Behind the Mask'' \u2013 An American short film directed by [[Jacques Tourneur]] \n*1939: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1939 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 American black and white film directed by [[James Whale]], starring [[Louis Hayward]], [[Joan Bennett]], [[Warren William]] and [[Alan Hale Sr.]] (as \"Porthos\")\n*1952: ''[[Lady in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 American color film starring [[Louis Hayward]], [[Patricia Medina]] and [[Alan Hale Jr.]] (as \"Porthos\")\n*1962: ''[[Le Masque de fer]]'' \u2013 Italian/French film, starring [[Jean Marais]]\n*1968: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British TV series (9 episodes)\n*1968: ''[[The Three Musketeers|The Three Musketeers (Animated Series)]]'' from [[The Banana Splits Adventure Hour]] \u2013 \"The True King\"\n*1970: ''[[Start the Revolution Without Me]]''\n*1977: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1977 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British TV movie with [[Richard Chamberlain (actor)|Richard Chamberlain]], [[Patrick McGoohan]], [[Louis Jourdan]], [[Jenny Agutter]], [[Ian Holm]], [[Ralph Richardson]] and [[Vivien Merchant]]\n*1979: ''[[The Fifth Musketeer]]'' also known as ''Behind the Iron Mask'' \u2013 Austrian/West German film directed by [[Ken Annakin]], with [[Sylvia Kristel]], [[Ursula Andress]], [[Beau Bridges]], [[Cornel Wilde]], [[Lloyd Bridges]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]], [[Olivia de Havilland]], [[Ian McShane]], [[Rex Harrison]] and [[Alan Hale Jr.]] (as \"Porthos\"); remake of the 1939 film\n*1985: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' \u2013 Australian animated TV film\n*1987: ''[[The Three Musketeers (1987 TV series)|Three Musketeers]]'' \u2013 Japanese anime television series, included the character of The Man in the Iron Mask depicted as a [[Doctor Doom]]-like villain.\n*1987: ''[[DuckTales (1987 TV series)|DuckTales]]'' \u2013 American animated TV series, Season 1, Episode 10 \"The Duck in the Iron Mask.\"\n*1993: ''[[The Secret of Queen Anne or Musketeers Thirty Years After]]'' \u2013 Russian [[musical film]] directed by [[Georgi Yungvald-Khilkevich]] based on [[Alexandre Dumas, p\u00e8re|Alexandre Dumas]]' novel ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later|The Vicomte de Bragelonne]]'', with [[Mikhail Boyarsky]], [[Veniamin Smekhov]], [[Valentin Smirnitsky]], [[Igor Starygin]], [[Alisa Freindlich]] and [[Dmitry Kharatyan]]\n*1998: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1998 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British/American film directed by [[Randall Wallace]], with [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Jeremy Irons]], [[John Malkovich]], [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] and [[Gabriel Byrne]]\n*1998: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' also known as ''The Mask of Dumas'' \u2013 American film, directed by [[William Richert]], with [[Edward Albert]], [[Dana Barron]], Rex Ryon and [[Timothy Bottoms]]\n*2007: ''[[Revenge Is a Dish Best Served Three Times]]'' \u2013 18th season of The Simpsons animated television  program.\n*2009: ''[[G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra]]'' \u2013 James McCullen's family background is retconned as his ancestor James McCullen IX was only punished by the French monarchy after being caught selling weapons to both them and England, condemned to have a red-hot iron mask welded onto his face and serve as an example to others who attempted to overthrow the crown.\n*2014: ''[[The Musketeers]]'' (BBC 2014 adaptation) \u2013 series 1, episode 6\n*2016: ''[[The Flash (season 2)]]'', The CW TV Series \u2013 Season 2, Episode 14, The real Jay Garrick is imprisoned and locked in an iron mask by Hunter Zolomon while he impersonates him. This seems to be an homage to the fictional telling in ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1998 film)]]'' \n*2018: In ''[[Versailles (TV series)|Versailles]]'', the Franco-Canadian TV series, the 3rd series commences with the Man in the Iron Mask imprisoned and under consideration for dispatch to the Americas.\n\n===Comic books===\n*1956: \"The Three Super-Musketeers\" (''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' 82), written by [[Edmond Hamilton]], illustrated by [[Dick Sprang]]. [[Superman]], [[Batman]] and Robin are the title characters, tasked to conceal the prisoner's identity.\n*1965: \"The Phantom of Notre Duck\" (''[[Uncle Scrooge]]'' 60) by [[Carl Barks]]. [[Scrooge McDuck]] has a silly adventure in Duckburg, mashing up elements of ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]], [[The Phantom of the Opera]]'' and (briefly) Dumas' version of the Iron Mask legend.\n\n===Music===\n*1983: \"The Man in the Iron Mask\" \u2013 a track on ''[[Life's a Riot with Spy vs Spy]]'' by [[Billy Bragg]].\n*1992: \"The Iron Mask\" \u2013 a CD by gothic rock band Christian Death.\n*1999: \"These Are the times,\" a music video by the R&B group Dru Hill.\n*2006: \"Tilting the Hourglass\" \u2013 a song released by rock band [[Alesana]] on their debut album ''[[On Frail Wings of Vanity and Wax]]'', in which the imprisonment and feelings of the prisoner are portrayed in song.\n*2019: \u201cThe Man in The Iron Mask\u201d - a song released by [[Magneto Dayo]]\n\n===Gaming===\n*2014: \u201cAssassin\u2019s Creed Unity\u201d - a DLC that players can acquire in game within the Estore called \u201cDead Kings\u201d.\nWithin the contents of \u201cDead Kings\u201d you receive new story content and a cosmetic outfit of \u201cThe Man in The Iron Mask\u201d to apply to your player.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]''\n* [[Ivan VI of Russia]], a prisoner with a similar story\n* [[Look-alike]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AmCyc Poster|Iron Mask, Man in the|{{PAGENAME}}}}\n*[http://www.cadytech.com/dumas/related/the_mystery_of_the_iron_mask.php ''The Mystery of the Iron Mask'']\n{{Gutenberg|no=2759|name=The Man in the Iron Mask}}\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/mailbag/mmaninmask.html Who was the \"Man in the Iron Mask\"?] at the [[Straight Dope]]\n\n{{The Man in the Iron Mask|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Man In The Iron Mask, The}}\n[[Category:17th-century births]]\n[[Category:1703 deaths]]\n[[Category:Man in the Iron Mask| ]]\n[[Category:17th-century French people]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:People of the Ancien R\u00e9gime]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of France]]\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:French folklore]]\n[[Category:Mysteries]]\n[[Category:Masked people by occupation]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|an aspect of French history}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = \n| image = Man in the Iron Masque crop.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = ''L'Homme au Masque de Fer'' (''The Man in the Iron Mask''). Anonymous print ([[etching]] and [[mezzotint]], hand-colored) from 1789.\n| birth_name = Birth name unknown\n| birth_date = ''c.'' 1640\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = 19 November 1703\n| death_place = Bastille, Paris\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = Saint-Paul Cemetery, Paris\n| residence = \n| nationality = French\n| other_names = Marchioly, Eustache Dauger\n| occupation = \n| known_for = Mystery regarding his identity\n| height = \n| weight = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| criminal_charge = Unknown\n| conviction_status = Died in prison\n| spouse = <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children = <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = <!-- (as above) -->\n| allegiance = <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive = \n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = \n| date = \n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| country = \n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| endyear = \n| apprehended = 1669/70\n| imprisoned = \n| footnotes = \n| penalty = Life imprisonment\n}}\nThe '''Man in the Iron Mask''' (French: ''L'Homme au Masque de Fer''; c. 1640 \u2013 19 November 1703) was an unidentified prisoner who was arrested in 1669 or 1670 and subsequently held in a number of [[Kingdom of France|French]] prisons, including the [[Bastille]] and the Fortress of Pignerol (modern Pinerolo, Italy). He was held in the custody of the same jailer, [[B\u00e9nigne Dauvergne de Saint-Mars]], for a period of 34 years. He died on 19 November 1703 under the name Marchioly, during the reign of King [[Louis XIV of France]] (1643\u20131715). \n\nBecause no one ever saw his face because it was hidden by a mask of black velvet cloth, the true identity of the prisoner remains a mystery; it has been extensively debated by historians, and various theories have been expounded in numerous books and films.\n\nAmong the leading theories are those proposed by writer and philosopher [[Voltaire]]: He claimed in the second edition of his ''Questions sur l'Encyclop\u00e9die'' (1771) that the prisoner wore a mask made of iron rather than of cloth, and that he was the older, illegitimate brother of Louis XIV. What little is known about the historical Man in the Iron Mask is based mainly on correspondence between Saint-Mars and his superiors in Paris. Recent research suggests that his name might have been Eustache Dauger, a man who was involved in several political scandals of the late 17th century, but this assertion has not been proven.\n\nThe [[National Archives of France]] has made available online the original data relating to the inventories of the goods and papers of Saint-Mars (one inventory, of 64 pages, was drawn up at the [[Bastille]] in 1708; the other, of 68 pages, at the [[citadel of Sainte-Marguerite]] in 1691). These documents had been sought in vain for more than a century and were thought to have been lost. They were discovered in 2015, among the 100 million documents of the {{ill|Minutier central des notaires de Paris|fr}}.<ref>Archives nationales de France: salle des inventaires, Archives nationales (accessed 23 January 2017).</ref><ref>Analyse et photographies des documents d\u00e9couverts, https://sergearoles-documents-archives.com/ [archive] (accessed 23 January 2017).</ref> They show that some of the 800 documents in the possession of the jailer Saint-Mars were analysed after his death. These documents confirm the reputed avarice of Saint-Mars, who appears to have diverted the funds paid by the king for the prisoner. They also give a description of a cell occupied by the masked prisoner, which contained only a sleeping mat, but no luxuries, as was previously thought. \n\nWith the scientific support of the [[National Library of France]] collections of ancient textiles, the accuracy of these notary documents discovered in 2015 has allowed the creation of the first virtual reconstruction of the prison of the man in the iron mask.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2010/11/26/bastille-prison-had-5-star-comforts-research-shows/ |title=Bastille prison had 5-star comforts, research shows|publisher=Twin Cities Pioneer Press |date= 2010-11-06|accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Man in the Iron Mask has also appeared in many works of fiction, most prominently in the late 1840s by [[Alexandre Dumas]]. A section of his novel ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]'', the final installment of his [[D'Artagnan Romances|D'Artagnan saga]], features the Man in the Iron Mask. Here the prisoner is forced to wear an iron mask and is portrayed as Louis XIV's identical twin.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" /> Dumas also presented a review of the popular theories about the prisoner extant in his time in the chapter \"L'homme au masque de fer\" in the sixth volume of his non-fiction ''Crimes C\u00e9l\u00e8bres''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/crimesclbres02dumagoog |title=Crimes c\u00e9l\u00e8bres : Alexandre Dumas : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref>\n\n==Prisoner==\n===Arrest and imprisonment===\nThe earliest surviving records of the masked prisoner are from late July 1669, when [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]'s minister, the [[Fran\u00e7ois-Michel le Tellier, Marquis de Louvois|Marquis de Louvois]], sent a letter to [[B\u00e9nigne Dauvergne de Saint-Mars]], governor of the prison of Pignerol, which at the time was part of France. In his letter, Louvois informed Saint-Mars that a prisoner named \"Eustache Dauger\" was due to arrive in the next month or so.\n[[File:Pinerolo 001.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The town of [[Pinerolo]], previously Pignerol, in Piedmont, Italy.]]\n\nLouis XIV instructed Saint-Mars to prepare a cell with multiple doors, one closing upon the other, which were to prevent anyone from the outside listening in. Saint-Mars was to see Dauger only once a day to provide food and whatever else he needed. Dauger was to be told that if he, Dauger, spoke of anything other than his immediate needs he would be killed, but, according to Louvois, the prisoner should not require much since he was \"only a valet\".\n\nHistorians have noted that the name Eustache Dauger was written in a handwriting different from that used in the rest of the letter's text, suggesting that a clerk wrote the letter under Louvois' dictation, while someone else, very likely Louvois, added the name afterward.\n\nDauger was arrested by Captain Alexandre de Vauroy, garrison commander of [[Dunkirk]], and taken to Pignerol, where he arrived in late August. Evidence has been produced to suggest that the arrest was actually made in [[Calais]] and that not even the local governor was informed of the event \u2013 Vauroy's absence being explained away by his hunting for Spanish soldiers who had strayed into France via the [[Spanish Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nThe first rumours of the prisoner's identity (specifically as a [[Marshal of France]]) began to circulate at this point.\n\n===Masked man serves as a valet===\n[[File:La masque de fer.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Illustration, c. 1872]]\n[[File:Masque de fer selon Warin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''L'Homme au masque de fer'', by [[Jean-Joseph Regnault-Warin]]]]\nThe prison at Pignerol, like the others at which Dauger was later held, was used for men who were considered an embarrassment to the state and usually held only a handful of prisoners at a time.\n\nSaint-Mars' other prisoners at Pignerol included Count [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]], an Italian diplomat who had been kidnapped and jailed for double-crossing the French over the purchase of the important fortress town of [[Casale Monferrato|Casale]] on the Italian border. There was [[Nicolas Fouquet]], Marquis of Belle-\u00cele, a former superintendent of finances who had been jailed by Louis XIV on the charge of embezzlement, and the [[Antoine Nompar de Caumont|Marquis de Lauzun]], who had become engaged to the [[Anne, Duchess of Montpensier|Duchess of Montpensier]], a cousin of the king, without the king's consent. Fouquet's cell was above that of Lauzun.\n\nIn his letters to Louvois, Saint-Mars describes Dauger as a quiet man, giving no trouble, \"disposed to the will of God and to the king\", compared to his other prisoners, who were always complaining, constantly trying to escape, or simply mad.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nDauger was not always isolated from the other prisoners. Wealthy and important ones usually had manservants; Fouquet for instance was served by a man called La Rivi\u00e8re. These servants, however, would become as much prisoners as their masters and it was thus difficult to find people willing to volunteer for such an occupation. Because La Rivi\u00e8re was often ill, Saint-Mars applied for permission for Dauger to act as servant for Fouquet. In 1675, Louvois gave permission for such an arrangement on condition that he was to serve Fouquet only while La Rivi\u00e8re was unavailable and that he was not to meet anyone else; for instance, if Fouquet and Lauzun were to meet, Dauger was not to be present.\n\nIt is an important point that the man in the mask served as a valet. Fouquet was never expected to be released; thus, meeting Dauger was no great matter, but Lauzun was expected to be set free eventually, and it would have been important not to have him spread rumours of Dauger's existence. Historians have also argued that 17th-century protocol made it unthinkable that a man of royal blood would serve as a manservant, casting some doubt on speculation that Dauger was in some way related to the king.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\">''The Man in the Iron Mask'', [[Timewatch]] TV documentary presented by [[Henry Lincoln]], [[BBC]], 1988</ref>\n\nAfter Fouquet's death in 1680, Saint-Mars discovered a secret hole between Fouquet and Lauzun's cells. He was sure that they had communicated through this hole without detection by him or his guards and thus that Lauzun must have been made aware of Dauger's existence. Louvois instructed Saint-Mars to move Lauzun to Fouquet's cell and to tell him that Dauger and La Rivi\u00e8re had been released.\n\n===Other prisons===\n[[File:Exilles02.JPG|thumb|200px|right|[[Fortress of Exilles]]]]\n[[File:Lerins-iron mask prison.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[\u00cele Sainte-Marguerite]]]]\nLauzun was freed in 1681. Later that same year, Saint-Mars was appointed governor of the prison of the [[Exilles Fort|Exiles Fort]] (now [[Exilles]] in Italy). He went there, taking Dauger and La Rivi\u00e8re with him. La Rivi\u00e8re's death was reported in January 1687; in May, Saint-Mars and Dauger moved to [[\u00cele Sainte-Marguerite|Sainte-Marguerite]], one of the [[L\u00e9rins Islands]], half a mile offshore from Cannes.\n\nIt was during the journey to Sainte-Marguerite that rumors spread that the prisoner was wearing an iron mask. Again, he was placed in a cell with multiple doors.\n\nOn 18 September 1698, Saint-Mars took up his new post as governor of the [[Bastille]] prison in Paris, bringing Dauger with him. He was placed in a solitary cell in the prefurnished third chamber of the Bertaudi\u00e8re tower. The prison's second-in-command, de Rosarges, was to feed him. Lieutenant du Junca, another officer of the Bastille, noted that the prisoner wore \"a mask of black velvet\".\n\nThe masked prisoner died on 19 November 1703 and was buried the next day under the name of Marchioly.\n\nIn 1711, King Louis's sister-in-law, [[Elizabeth Charlotte, Princess Palatine]], sent a letter to her aunt, [[Sophia of Hanover|Sophia, Electress of Hanover]], stating that the prisoner had \"two [[musketeers]] at his side to kill him if he removed his mask\". She described him as very devout, and stated that he was well treated and received everything he desired. However, the prisoner had already been dead for eight years by that point and the Princess had not necessarily seen him for herself; rather, she was quite likely reporting rumours she had heard at court.\n\n==Popular interest==\nThe fate of the mysterious prisoner \u2013 and the extent of the apparent precautions his jailers took \u2013 created significant interest in his story and gave birth to many legends. Many theories exist and several books have been written about the case. Some were presented after the existence of the letters was widely known. Still later commentators have presented their own theories, possibly based on embellished versions of the original tale.\n\nTheories about his identity popular during his time included that he was a Marshal of France; the English [[Henry Cromwell]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Dumas|first= Alexandre|title= Celebrated Crimes|volume= 6|page=[https://archive.org/details/celebratedcrimes06duma/page/2008 2008] |date=1910|url= https://archive.org/details/celebratedcrimes06duma}}</ref> son of [[Oliver Cromwell]]; or [[Fran\u00e7ois, Duke of Beaufort]]. Later, many people such as [[Voltaire]] and [[Alexandre Dumas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/2751 |title=Gutenberg.org |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=2004-09-22 |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref> suggested other theories about the man in the mask.\n\n==Candidates==\n\n===King's relative===\n[[Voltaire]] claimed that the prisoner was a son of [[Anne of Austria]] and [[Cardinal Mazarin]], and therefore an illegitimate half-brother of [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]]. However, the sincerity of this claim is uncertain.\n\n==== King's twin brother ====\nIn his history essay ''Le Masque de fer'',<ref name=\"Marcel Pagnol\">{{cite book |title=Le Masque de fer |last=Pagnol |first=Marcel |publisher=\u00c9ditions de Provence |year=1965 |pages=chapters 11 & 12}}</ref> French novelist [[Marcel Pagnol]], supporting his theory in particular on the circumstances of King Louis XIV's birth, claims that the Man in the Iron mask was indeed a twin but born second, and hence the younger, and would have been hidden in order to avoid any dispute over the throne holder.<ref name=\"Marcel Pagnol\"/> {{efn|To make the context clearer, note that at the time there was a controversy over which one of twins was the elder: The one born first, or the one born second, who was then thought to have been conceived first.}}\n\nThe historians who reject this theory (including [[:fr:Jean-Christian Petitfils|Jean-Christian Petitfils]]), highlight the conditions of childbirth for the queen: It usually took place in the presence of multiple witnesses \u2013 the main court's figures. But according to Marcel Pagnol, right after the birth of the future Louis XIV, King Louis XIII took his whole court to the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain-en-Laye|''Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain'']]'s chapel to celebrate a ''[[Te Deum]]'' in great pomp, contrary to the common practice of celebrating it several days before childbirth.<ref>{{cite book |title=Suppl\u00e9ment au Corps Universel Diplomatique |volume=IV |page=176 |editor=Dumont, Jean |editor-link=Jean Dumont (publicist)}}</ref>\n\nAlso supporting the theory of King Louis XIV's twin, a thorough examination of the French Kings' genealogy shows many twin births, in the [[Capetian dynasty]], as well as in the [[House of Valois]], [[House of Bourbon|Bourbon]], and the [[House of Orl\u00e9ans]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Yann |last=Kermabon |article=Courrier des lecteurs |title-link=:fr:Historia (revue) |title=Revue Historia |date=October 1998}}</ref>\n\n[[Alexandre Dumas]] explored a similar theory in his book ''[[The Vicomte de Bragelonne]]'', where the prisoner was instead an identical twin of Louis XIV. This book has served as the basis \u2013 even if loosely adapted \u2013 for many [[The Man in the Iron Mask (film)|film versions]] of the story.\n\nAccording to Marcel Pagnol\u2019s theory, this twin was then born in 1638 and grew up on the Island of [[Jersey]] under the name [[James de la Cloche]]. He would later conspire with [[Roux de Marcilly]] against King Louis XIV, and hypothetically was arrested in Calais in 1669.\n\n==== King's father ====\nHugh Ross Williamson<ref name=\"Williamson2002\">{{cite book|title=Who Was The Man In the Iron Mask? and Other Historical Mysteries|first=Hugh Ross|last=Williamson|publisher=Penguin|year=2002|isbn=0-14-139097-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whowasmaninironm00ross}}</ref> argues that the man in the iron mask was the natural father of Louis XIV. According to this theory, the \"miraculous\" birth of Louis XIV in 1638 would have come after [[Louis XIII]] had been estranged from his wife [[Anne of Austria]] for 14 years.\n\nThe theory then suggests that [[Cardinal Richelieu]], the king's minister, had arranged for a substitute, probably an illegitimate son or grandson of [[Henry IV of France|Henry IV]], to become intimate with the queen and father an heir in the king's stead. At the time, the [[heir presumptive]] was Louis XIII's brother [[Gaston, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]], who was Richelieu's enemy. If Gaston became king, Richelieu would quite likely have lost both his job as minister and his life, and so it was in his best interests to thwart Gaston's ambitions.\n\nSupposedly the substitute father then left for the [[New France|Americas]] but in the 1660s returned to France with the aim of extorting money for keeping his secret, and was promptly imprisoned. This theory would explain the secrecy surrounding the prisoner, whose true identity would have destroyed the legitimacy of Louis XIV's claim to the throne had it been revealed.\n\nThis theory was first disputed by British politician [[Hugh Cecil, 1st Baron Quickswood]]. He said the idea has no historical basis and is hypothetical. Williamson held that to say it is a guess with no solid historical basis is merely to say that it is like every other theory on the matter, although it makes more sense than any of the other theories. There is no known evidence that is incompatible with it, even the age of the prisoner, which Cecil had considered a weak point; and it explains every aspect of the mystery.<ref name=\"Williamson2002\" />\n\n===French general===\n{{See also|Great Cipher#The Man in the Iron Mask}}\n\nIn 1890, Louis Gendron, a French military historian, came across some coded letters and passed them on to [[\u00c9tienne Bazeries]] in the French Army's cryptographic department. After three years Bazeries managed to read some messages in the [[Great Cipher]] of Louis XIV. One of them referred to a prisoner and identified him as General {{ill|Vivien de Bulonde|fr|Vivien l'Abb\u00e9 de Bulonde}}. One of the letters written by Louvois made specific reference to de Bulonde's crime.\n\nAt the [[Siege of Cuneo (1691)|Siege of Cuneo]] in 1691, Bulonde was concerned about enemy troops arriving from Austria and ordered a hasty withdrawal, leaving behind his munitions and wounded men. Louis XIV was furious and in another of the letters specifically ordered him \"to be conducted to the fortress at Pignerol where he will be locked in a cell and under guard at night, and permitted to walk the battlements during the day with a 330 309.\" It has been suggested that the 330 stood for ''masque'' and the 309 for full stop. However, in 17th-century French ''avec un masque'' would mean \"in a mask\".\n\nSome believe that the evidence of the letters means that there is now little need of an alternative explanation for the man in the mask. Other sources, however, claim that Bulonde's arrest was no secret and was actually published in a newspaper at the time and that he was released after just a few months. His death is also recorded as happening in 1709, six years after that of the man in the mask.<ref name=\"Noone\">''The Man Behind the Iron Mask'' by John Noone, 1988 {{ISBN|0750906790}}</ref>\n\n===Valet===\nIn 1801, revolutionary legislator Pierre Roux-Fazillac stated that the tale of the masked prisoner was an amalgamation of the fates of two separate prisoners, [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]] (see below) and an imprisoned valet named \"Eustache d'Auger\".\n\n[[Andrew Lang|Lang]] (1903)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Valet's Tragedy and Other Stories |year=1903 |author-link=Andrew Lang |first=Andrew |last=Lang}}</ref> presented a theory that \"Eustache d'Auger\" was a prison pseudonym of a man called \"Martin\", valet of the [[Huguenot]] [[Roux de Marcilly]]. After his master's execution in 1669 the valet was taken to France, possibly by abduction. A letter from the French Foreign minister has been found rejecting an offer to arrest Martin: He was simply not important.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Man in the Iron Mask |first=Harry |last=Thompson |page=77}}</ref>\n\nNoone (1988)<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Noone |title=The Man behind the Mask |page=272 |year=1988}}</ref> pointed out that the minister was concerned Dauger should not communicate, rather than that his face should be concealed. Later, St. Mars elaborated upon instructions that the prisoner should not be seen during transportation. The idea of keeping d'Auger in a velvet mask was St. Mars' own, to increase his self importance. What d'Auger had seen or done is still a mystery.\n\n===Son of Charles II===\nBarnes (1908)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Man of the Mask |year=1908 |first=Arthur |last=Barnes}}</ref> presents [[James de la Cloche]], the alleged illegitimate son of the reluctant Protestant [[Charles II of England]], who would have been his father's secret intermediary with the Catholic court of France.\n\nOne of Charles's confirmed illegitimate sons, the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], has also been proposed as the man in the mask. A Protestant, he led [[Monmouth Rebellion|a rebellion]] against his uncle, the Catholic [[James II of England|King James II]]. The rebellion failed and Monmouth was executed in 1685. But in 1768, a writer named Saint-Foix claimed that another man was executed in his place and that Monmouth became the masked prisoner, it being in Louis XIV's interests to assist a fellow Catholic like James who would not necessarily want to kill his own nephew. Saint-Foix's case was based on unsubstantiated rumors and allegations that Monmouth's execution was faked.<ref name=\"Noone\"/>\n\n===Italian diplomat===\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2019}}\nAnother candidate, much favored in the 1800s, was Fouquet's fellow prisoner Count [[Ercole Antonio Mattioli]] (or Matthioli). He was an Italian diplomat who acted on behalf of debt-ridden [[Charles IV, Duke of Mantua]] in 1678, in selling [[Casale Monferrato|Casale]], a strategic fortified town near the border with France. A French occupation would be unpopular, so discretion was essential, but Mattioli leaked the details to France's Spanish enemies, after pocketing his commission once the sale had been concluded, and they made a bid of their own before the French forces could occupy the town. Mattioli was kidnapped by the French and thrown into nearby Pignerol in April 1679. The French took possession of Casale two years later.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n[[George Agar Ellis]] reached the conclusion that Mattioli was the state prisoner commonly called The Iron Mask when he reviewed documents extracted from French archives in the 1820s. His book,<ref>George Agar Ellis, The true history of the State Prisoner commonly called the Iron Mask, here identified with Count E.A. Mattioli, extracted from documents in the French archives (London, J. Murray, 1826)</ref> published in English in 1826, was translated into French and published in 1830. German historian Wilhelm Broecking came to the same conclusion independently seventy years later.  [[Robert Chambers (journalist)|Robert Chambers]]' ''[[Chambers Book of Days|Book of Days]]'' supports the claim and places Matthioli in the Bastille for the last 13 years of his life.\n\nSince that time, letters sent by Saint-Mars, which earlier historians missed, indicate that Mattioli was only held at Pignerol and Sainte-Marguerite and was not at Exilles or the Bastille and, therefore, it is argued that he can be discounted.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" />\n\n===Eustache Dauger de Cavoye===\nIn his letter to Saint-Mars announcing the imminent arrival of the prisoner who would become the \"man in the iron mask,\" Louvois gave his name as \"Eustache Dauger\" and historians have found evidence that a \"Eustache Dauger\" was living in France at the time and was involved in scandalous and embarrassing events involving people in high places known as [[Affair of the Poisons|l'Affaire des Poisons]]. His full name was Eustache Dauger de Cavoye.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n====Early life====\nRecords indicate that he was born on 30 August 1637, the son of Fran\u00e7ois Dauger, a captain in [[Cardinal Richelieu]]'s guards. Fran\u00e7ois was married to Marie de S\u00e9rignan and they had 11 children, nine of whom survived into adulthood. When Fran\u00e7ois and his two eldest sons were killed in battle, Eustache became the nominal head of the family.\n\n====Disgrace====\nIn April 1659, Eustache and Guiche were invited to an Easter weekend party at the castle of Roissy-en-Brie. By all accounts it was a debauched affair of merry-making, with the men involved in all sorts of sordid activities, including attacking a man who claimed to be [[Cardinal Mazarin]]'s attorney. It was also claimed,{{By whom|date=July 2010}} among other things, that a [[black mass]] was enacted and that a pig was baptized as carp in order to allow them to eat pork on Good Friday.\n\nWhen news of these events became public, an inquiry was held and the various perpetrators jailed or exiled. There is no record as to what happened to Dauger, but in 1665, near the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], he allegedly killed a young [[Page (occupation)|page boy]] in a drunken brawl involving the Duc de Foix. The two men claimed that they had been provoked by the boy, who was drunk, but the fact that the killing took place near a castle where the king was staying meant that this was not a good enough explanation, and as a result, Dauger was forced to resign his [[Commissioned officers|commission]].\n\nDauger's mother died shortly afterwards. In her will, written a year previously, she passed over her eldest surviving sons Eustache and Armand, leaving the bulk of the estate to their younger brother Louis. Eustache was restricted in the amount of money to which he had access, having built up considerable debts, and left with barely enough for \"food and upkeep\".{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n====Affair of the Poisons====\n{{main|Affair of the Poisons}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\nIn the 1930s, historian Maurice Duvivier linked Eustache Dauger de Cavoye to the [[Poison affair|Affair of the Poisons]], a notorious scandal of 1677\u20131682 in which people in high places were accused of being involved in [[black mass]] and poisonings. An investigation had been launched, but Louis XIV had instigated a cover-up when it appeared that his mistress [[Fran\u00e7oise-Ath\u00e9na\u00efs, marquise de Montespan|Madame de Montespan]] was involved.<ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\nThe records show that during the inquiry the investigators were told about a supplier of poisons, a surgeon named Auger, and Duvivier became convinced that Dauger de Cavoye, disinherited and short of money, had become Auger, the supplier of poisons, and subsequently Dauger, the man in the mask.\n\nIn a letter sent by Louvois to Saint-Mars shortly after Fouquet's death while in prison (with Dauger acting as his valet), the minister adds a note in his own handwriting, asking how Dauger performed certain acts that Saint-Mars had mentioned in a previous correspondence (now lost) and \"how he got the drugs necessary to do so\". Duvivier suggested that Dauger may have poisoned Fouquet as part of a complex power struggle between Louvois and his rival [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert|Colbert]].\n\n====Dauger in prison====\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\nHowever, evidence has emerged that Dauger de Cavoye actually died in the [[Prison Saint-Lazare]], an asylum run by monks which many families used in order to imprison their \"[[black sheep]]\". Documents have survived indicating that Dauger de Cavoye was held at Saint-Lazare in Paris at about the same time that Dauger, the man in the mask, was taken into custody in Pignerol, hundreds of miles away in the south.\n\nThese include a letter sent to Dauger de Cavoye's sister, the Marquise de Fabr\u00e8gues, dated 20 June 1678, which is filled with self-pity as Eustache complains about his treatment in prison, where he has been held for 10 years, and how he was deceived by their brother Louis and Cl\u00e9rac, their brother-in-law and the manager of Louis' estate. A year later, he wrote a letter to the king, outlining the same complaints and making a similar request for freedom. The best the king would do, however, was to send a letter to the head of Saint-Lazare telling him that \"M. de Cavoye should have communication with no one at all, not even with his sister, unless in your presence or in the presence of one of the priests of the mission\". The letter was signed by the king and Colbert.\n\nA poem written by Louis-Henri de Lom\u00e9nie de Brienne, an inmate at the time, indicates that Eustache Dauger de Cavoye died as a result of heavy drinking in the late 1680s. Historians consider all this proof enough that he was not involved in any way with the man in the mask.<ref name=\"BBCdocu\" /><ref name=\"Noone\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Literature===\n* [[Alfred de Vigny]], \"The Prison\" (1821),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/La_Prison_(Vigny) |title=La Prison (Vigny) |via=Wikisource |language=fr|publisher=Fr.wikisource.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-31}}</ref> a long poem describing the final events in the life of the Man in the Iron Mask. An aged priest is called to offer the last rites of the Catholic Church to a mysterious prisoner. After an involved process to ensure the prisoner's anonymity, the priest is introduced to the dying prisoner, who is addressed as \"my prince\" by the jailer. The priest realizes in the dim light that the prisoner wears an iron mask, and recalls the tales he heard in his youth. The prisoner rejects the priest's efforts, even after the priest promises that his lifelong incarceration has already opened Heaven to him if he would only embrace God. The prisoner dies without repenting. The priest continues to pray for the man for several hours, and is horrified to see that the corpse continues to wear the mask underneath the shroud, denied release even in death.\n* [[Alexandre Dumas]], ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later#Part Three: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' (Chapters 181\u2013269)|The Vicomte de Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]'' (1847\u20131850), the final section of which is titled ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' (French: {{lang|fr|L'homme au masque de fer}})\n* [[Henry Vizetelly]], ''The Man With the Iron Mask'' (1870)\n* [[Juliette Benzoni]], ''Secret d'etat''\n* Louis-C\u00e9sar, ''Cassandra Palmer'' series\n* [[Algis Budrys]]'s 1958 science-fiction novel ''[[Who? (novel)|Who? / The Man in the Steel Mask]]'', and the 1973 film based on it, are loosely inspired by the historical affair, placing a similar mystery in a contemporary [[Cold War]] setting. \n* Karleen Koen, ''Before Versailles'', in which the boy in the iron mask is a central issue among the characters.\n* [[Fortun\u00e9 du Boisgobey]], ''Le Vrai Masque de fer'' (1873). The serialized translations of this work in Japan and Korea in the early twentieth century made this the most popular \u201cMan in the Iron Mask\u201d in these countries, more so than the Dumas novel.\n\n===Films and television===\n\n*1909: ''[[La maschera di ferro]]'' \u2013 Italian silent film\n*1923: ''[[Der Mann mit der eisernen Maske]]'' \u2013 German silent film\n*1929: ''[[The Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 An American silent film starring [[Douglas Fairbanks]]\n*1938: ''The Face Behind the Mask'' \u2013 An American short film directed by [[Jacques Tourneur]] \n*1939: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1939 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 American black and white film directed by [[James Whale]], starring [[Louis Hayward]], [[Joan Bennett]], [[Warren William]] and [[Alan Hale Sr.]] (as \"Porthos\")\n*1952: ''[[Lady in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 American color film starring [[Louis Hayward]], [[Patricia Medina]] and [[Alan Hale Jr.]] (as \"Porthos\")\n*1962: ''[[Le Masque de fer]]'' \u2013 Italian/French film, starring [[Jean Marais]]\n*1968: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British TV series (9 episodes)\n*1968: ''[[The Three Musketeers|The Three Musketeers (Animated Series)]]'' from [[The Banana Splits Adventure Hour]] \u2013 \"The True King\"\n*1970: ''[[Start the Revolution Without Me]]''\n*1977: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1977 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British TV movie with [[Richard Chamberlain (actor)|Richard Chamberlain]], [[Patrick McGoohan]], [[Louis Jourdan]], [[Jenny Agutter]], [[Ian Holm]], [[Ralph Richardson]] and [[Vivien Merchant]]\n*1979: ''[[The Fifth Musketeer]]'' also known as ''Behind the Iron Mask'' \u2013 Austrian/West German film directed by [[Ken Annakin]], with [[Sylvia Kristel]], [[Ursula Andress]], [[Beau Bridges]], [[Cornel Wilde]], [[Lloyd Bridges]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]], [[Olivia de Havilland]], [[Ian McShane]], [[Rex Harrison]] and [[Alan Hale Jr.]] (as \"Porthos\"); remake of the 1939 film\n*1985: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' \u2013 Australian animated TV film\n*1987: ''[[The Three Musketeers (1987 TV series)|Three Musketeers]]'' \u2013 Japanese anime television series, included the character of The Man in the Iron Mask depicted as a [[Doctor Doom]]-like villain.\n*1987: ''[[DuckTales (1987 TV series)|DuckTales]]'' \u2013 American animated TV series, Season 1, Episode 10 \"The Duck in the Iron Mask.\"\n*1993: ''[[The Secret of Queen Anne or Musketeers Thirty Years After]]'' \u2013 Russian [[musical film]] directed by [[Georgi Yungvald-Khilkevich]] based on [[Alexandre Dumas, p\u00e8re|Alexandre Dumas]]' novel ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later|The Vicomte de Bragelonne]]'', with [[Mikhail Boyarsky]], [[Veniamin Smekhov]], [[Valentin Smirnitsky]], [[Igor Starygin]], [[Alisa Freindlich]] and [[Dmitry Kharatyan]]\n*1998: ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1998 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]'' \u2013 British/American film directed by [[Randall Wallace]], with [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Jeremy Irons]], [[John Malkovich]], [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] and [[Gabriel Byrne]]\n*1998: ''The Man in the Iron Mask'' also known as ''The Mask of Dumas'' \u2013 American film, directed by [[William Richert]], with [[Edward Albert]], [[Dana Barron]], Rex Ryon and [[Timothy Bottoms]]\n*2007: ''[[Revenge Is a Dish Best Served Three Times]]'' \u2013 18th season of The Simpsons animated television  program.\n*2009: ''[[G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra]]'' \u2013 James McCullen's family background is retconned as his ancestor James McCullen IX was only punished by the French monarchy after being caught selling weapons to both them and England, condemned to have a red-hot iron mask welded onto his face and serve as an example to others who attempted to overthrow the crown.\n*2014: ''[[The Musketeers]]'' (BBC 2014 adaptation) \u2013 series 1, episode 6\n*2016: ''[[The Flash (season 2)]]'', The CW TV Series \u2013 Season 2, Episode 14, The real Jay Garrick is imprisoned and locked in an iron mask by Hunter Zolomon while he impersonates him. This seems to be an homage to the fictional telling in ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1998 film)]]'' \n*2018; In ''[[Versailles (TV series)|Versailles]]'', the Franco-Canadian TV series, the 3rd series commences with the Man in the Iron Mask imprisoned and under consideration for dispatch to the Americas.\n\n===Comic books===\n*1956: \"The Three Super-Musketeers\" (''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' 82), written by [[Edmond Hamilton]], illustrated by [[Dick Sprang]]. [[Superman]], [[Batman]] and Robin are the title characters, tasked to conceal the prisoner's identity.\n*1965: \"The Phantom of Notre Duck\" (''[[Uncle Scrooge]]'' 60) by [[Carl Barks]]. [[Scrooge McDuck]] has a silly adventure in Duckburg, mashing up elements of ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]], [[The Phantom of the Opera]]'' and (briefly) Dumas' version of the Iron Mask legend.\n\n===Music===\n*1983: \"The Man in the Iron Mask\" \u2013 a track on ''[[Life's a Riot with Spy vs Spy]]'' by [[Billy Bragg]].\n*1992: \"The Iron Mask\" \u2013 a CD by gothic rock band Christian Death.\n*1999: \"These Are the times,\" a music video by the R&B group Dru Hill.\n*2006: \"Tilting the Hourglass\" \u2013 a song released by rock band [[Alesana]] on their debut album ''[[On Frail Wings of Vanity and Wax]]'', in which the imprisonment and feelings of the prisoner are portrayed in song.\n*2019: \u201cThe Man in The Iron Mask\u201d - a song released by [[Magneto Dayo]]\n\n===Gaming===\n*2014: \u201cAssassin\u2019s Creed Unity\u201d - a DLC that players can acquire in game within the Estore called \u201cDead Kings\u201d.\nWithin the contents of \u201cDead Kings\u201d you receive new story content and a cosmetic outfit of \u201cThe Man in The Iron Mask\u201d to apply to your player.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later]]''\n* [[Ivan VI of Russia]], a prisoner with a similar story\n* [[Look-alike]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AmCyc Poster|Iron Mask, Man in the|{{PAGENAME}}}}\n*[http://www.cadytech.com/dumas/related/the_mystery_of_the_iron_mask.php ''The Mystery of the Iron Mask'']\n{{Gutenberg|no=2759|name=The Man in the Iron Mask}}\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/mailbag/mmaninmask.html Who was the \"Man in the Iron Mask\"?] at the [[Straight Dope]]\n\n{{The Man in the Iron Mask|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Man In The Iron Mask, The}}\n[[Category:17th-century births]]\n[[Category:1703 deaths]]\n[[Category:Man in the Iron Mask| ]]\n[[Category:17th-century French people]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:People of the Ancien R\u00e9gime]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of France]]\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:French folklore]]\n[[Category:Mysteries]]\n[[Category:Masked people by occupation]]\n", "name_user": "119.195.164.105", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFilms and television)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_in_the_Iron_Mask"}
{"title_page": "Abla Kamel", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| imagesize = \n| caption =  \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|9|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_name = Abla Kamel Mohamed Afifi\n| birth_place = [[Cairo, Egypt]]\n| spouse = \n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1985\u2013present\n}}\n'''Abla Kamel Mohamed Afifi''' ({{lang-arz|\u0639\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0643\u0627\u0645\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0641\u064a\u0641\u064a}}&nbsp; {{IPA-arz|\u02c8\u0295\u00e6bl\u00e6 \u02c8k\u00e6\u02d0mel m\u00e6\u02c8\u0127\u00e6mm\u00e6d \u0295\u00e6\u02c8fi\u02d0fi|pron}}; born 17 September 1960)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sharkiatoday.com/%D8%B9%D8%AF%D8%AF-%D8%B2%D9%8A%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B9%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%84-%D9%88%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7/|title=\u062a\u0639\u0631\u0641 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0639\u062f\u062f \u0632\u064a\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0639\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0643\u0627\u0645\u0644 \u0648\u0639\u0645\u0631\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642\u064a\u0642\u064a|website=sharkiatoday.com|language=Arabic|date=17 September 2019}}</ref> is an [[Egypt]]ian actress, who in 2011 announced that she would retire from acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/abla-kamel-resigns-394510|title=Abla Kamel Resigns|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=June 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nOriginally from Nikla Al Inab in [[Beheira Governorate]], Abla Kamel graduated from the Faculty of Arts Department of Libraries in 1984 and started her career in theater Vanguard. She first participated in mono drama, heart health centers, then with Mohamed Sobhi. She married actor Ahmad Kamal, with whom she had two daughters. She later married actor Mahmoud El Gendy.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\" | Year\n! width=\"30%\" | Title\n! width=\"20%\" | Role\n|-\n|1982\n|''Iftah ya simsim''\n|Khoka\n|-\n|1988\n|''Yom mor... yom helw''\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''Iskanderija, kaman oue kaman''\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''Sawwaq el hanem''\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''Sarek al-farah''\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''Hysteria''\n|-\n|1996\n|''Lan a3isha fi jilbabi abi''\n|-\n|1998\n|''Arak el-balah''\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''El Medina''\n|Bannoura\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2002\n|''[[El-Limby]]''\n|Faransa\n|-\n|''Ayna qalbi''\n|Wesal\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2003\n|''Elly baly balak''\n|Doctor\n|-\n|''Kallem mama''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|''[[Khalty Faransa]]''\n|Faranca\n|-\n|''Eish ayamak''\n|Nahed\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n|''[[Sayed El Atefy]]''\n|Hanifa\n|-\n|''Raya wa Sekina''\n|Raya\n|-\n|2006\n|''Al-andaleeb hikayt shaab''\n|Aliya Shabana\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamel, Abla}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Cairo]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Egyptian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Egyptian actresses]]\n[[Category:Egyptian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| imagesize = \n| caption =  \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|6|16}} <ref>[http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/selsal-aldam/articles/%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%87%D9%88-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B2%D9%88%D8%AC-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84-%D9%84%D9%84%D9%81%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%A9--%D8%B9%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%84--%D9%88%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF-%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%9F.html selsal-aldam]</ref>\n| birth_name = Abla Kamel Mohamed Afifi\n| birth_place = [[Cairo, Egypt]]\n| spouse = \n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1985\u2013present\n}}\n'''Abla Kamel Mohamed Afifi''' ({{lang-arz|\u0639\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0643\u0627\u0645\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0641\u064a\u0641\u064a}}&nbsp; {{IPA-arz|\u02c8\u0295\u00e6bl\u00e6 \u02c8k\u00e6\u02d0mel m\u00e6\u02c8\u0127\u00e6mm\u00e6d \u0295\u00e6\u02c8fi\u02d0fi|pron}}) is an [[Egypt]]ian actress, who in 2011 announced that she would retire from acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/abla-kamel-resigns-394510|title=Abla Kamel Resigns|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=June 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAbla Kamel graduated from the Faculty of Arts Department of Libraries in 1990 and started her career in theater Vanguard. She first participated in mono drama, heart health centers, then with Mohamed Sobhi. She married actor Ahmad Kamal, with whom she had two daughters. She later married actor Mahmoud El Gendy.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\" | Year\n! width=\"30%\" | Title\n! width=\"20%\" | Role\n|-\n|1982\n|''Iftah ya simsim''\n|Khoka\n|-\n|1988\n|''Yom mor... yom helw''\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''Iskanderija, kaman oue kaman''\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''Sawwaq el hanem''\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''Sarek al-farah''\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''Hysteria''\n|-\n|1996\n|''Lan a3isha fi jilbabi abi''\n|-\n|1998\n|''Arak el-balah''\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''El Medina''\n|Bannoura\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2002\n|''[[El-Limby]]''\n|Faransa\n|-\n|''Ayna qalbi''\n|Wesal\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2003\n|''Elly baly balak''\n|Doctor\n|-\n|''Kallem mama''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|''[[Khalty Faransa]]''\n|Faranca\n|-\n|''Eish ayamak''\n|Nahed\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n|''[[Sayed El Atefy]]''\n|Hanifa\n|-\n|''Raya wa Sekina''\n|Raya\n|-\n|2006\n|''Al-andaleeb hikayt shaab''\n|Aliya Shabana\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamel, Abla}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Cairo]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Egyptian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Egyptian actresses]]\n[[Category:Egyptian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "119.195.164.105", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abla_Kamel"}
{"title_page": "Raya Meddine", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Raya Meddine\n| image =\n| caption = \n| birthname = Rana Alamuddin\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| yearsactive = 2003\u2013present\n| othername = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Elie Karam|2004}} \n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Rana Alamuddin''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}}), known professionally as '''Raya Meddine''', is a Lebanese American actress. She is known for her role as [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]] on ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[New York City]], Meddine is a [[Lebanese Druze]] who has lived in several countries due to her father's work in diplomatic missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hakawati.fm/episodes/view/23453?_branch_match_id=772109758862189678|title=Rana Alamuddin|website=Hakawati|language=Arabic|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> Her father was originally from Maimes, and her mother from [[Kfeir]], both in [[Hasbaya District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MMsLoxyzI1U#t=40m29s|title=Adventures of the Soul: a conversation with Rana Alamuddin : \u0645\u063a\u0627\u0645\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u062d: \u062d\u062f\u064a\u062b \u0645\u0639 \u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646|website=Bayneh W Baynek \u2013 YouTube|language=Arabic|date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe speaks five languages: French, Italian, Arabic, Spanish and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archive/interview-victor-s-new-love/article_137c6c1a-06fa-50b8-a873-757a37b27666.html|title=Interview: Victor\u2019s new love|website=tulsaworld.com|date=22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRaya Meddine studied Media at the [[Lebanese American University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlUx_OImSu4#t=13m49s|title=\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d - \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u062b\u0644\u0629 \u0648\u0645\u0642\u062f\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0645\u062c \u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 |website=FutureTV News|language=Arabic|date=19 September 2018}}</ref> She initially worked at [[Orbit TV]] as a host and reporter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107233348/http://www.dohafilminstitute.com/blog/people-in-film-raya-meddine-aka-rana-alamuddin|title=People in Film: Raya Meddine aka Rana Alamuddin|website=dohafilminstitute.com|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> She has later worked in Paris, [[Beirut]] and Los Angeles. In February 2008, Meddine joined the cast of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' in the contract role of [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]]. A shift in story line killed off the character, and Meddine left the role of Sabrina in August 2008. In June 2009, due to the popularity of the Sabrina character, Meddine inked a deal with ''The Young & the Restless'' to appear on a recurring basis as Sabrina's \"ghost\".\n\nSome of her other acting roles include Isabelle in the Lebanese box office hit ''[[Bosta (film)|Bosta]]'' (2006), and as Wanda in the short award winning film ''Recycling Flo'' (2004). She also made a guest appearance as Kayla on the NBC TV series, ''[[She Spies]]'' alongside [[Natasha Henstridge]] in 2003. In 2009, Meddine guest starred on the hit CBS series, ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', and will appear in the upcoming film, ''[[When Worlds Collide (2012 film)|When Worlds Collide]]'', produced by [[Steven Spielberg]]. ''When Worlds Collide'' is in pre-production and is scheduled for release in 2010/2011.  Ms. Meddine recently appeared in a featured role in the hit summer movie \"[[Sex and the City 2]]\" opposite [[Sarah Jessica Parker]].\n\nIn January 2012, Meddine appeared on the pilot episode of the FOX television series, ''Touch'', starring [[Kiefer Sutherland]].\n\nIn 2018, Meddine started to host a program titled \"Bayneh W Baynek\", with [[Nadine Labaki]] as the first guest, in which she discussed women issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.annahar.com/article/257467-%D8%B1%D9%86%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%83-%D9%84%D8%A7-%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AE%D8%AC%D9%84|title=\u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646: \"\u0628\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0648\u0628\u064a\u0646\u0650\u0643\" \u0644\u0627 \u0645\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u0644\u062e\u062c\u0644|website=annahar.com|language=Arabic|date=6 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebanontraveler.com/en/magazine/rana-alamuddin/|title=From Hollywood Actress To Female Activist: Rana Alamuddin|website=Lebanon Traveler|date=8 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMeddine married Lebanese-Canadian<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0607/18/lkl.01.html|title=Larry King Live|website=CNN|date=29 June 2006}}</ref> director/writer Elie Karam in a civil marriage in [[Cyprus]] in 2004, they have two kids together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BKkJrrPAFlq/|title=12th year wedding anniversary today. May our present & future be as glorious as our past.|website=Instagram|date=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fernadez|first1=Rebecce|title=Inspiring Reinvention:Rana Alamuddin|url=http://thewomentakeover.com/inspiring-reinvention-rana-alamuddin/|website=thewomentakeover.com|publisher=The Women Take Over|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> She and her husband currently divide their time between their homes in Los Angeles and Paris.\n\n==Social awareness==\nMeddine is cultural ambassador for the [[Levantine Cultural Center]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=People in Film:Raya Meddine|url=http://www.dohafilminstitute.com/blog/people-in-film-raya-meddine-aka-rana-alamuddin|website=dohafilminstitute.com|publisher=Doha Film Institute|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Film\n* 2004: ''Baby's Momma Drama'' as N/A\n* 2004: ''Recycling Flo'' as Wanda\n* 2005: ''Bosta'' as Isabelle\n* 2010: ''[[Sex and the City 2]]'' as Annesha\n* 2017: ''Wajib''\n* 2017: ''Bonbone''\n* 2019: ''Beirut Hold'em''\n\n;TV series\n* 2003: ''She Spies'' as Kayla <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2008: ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' as [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]] <small>('''Role:''' February 28-August 4, 2008, September 24, 2008, June 2, 2009 to June 5, 2009, December 23, 2010</small>\n* 2008: ''[[CSI: Miami]]'' as Kate Hawkes <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2010: ''[[Rizzoli & Isles]]'' as Claire <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2012: ''Touch'' as Mrs. Kosta\n\n;Video games\n* 2012: ''[[Diablo III]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1375816}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meddine, Raya}}\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Druze people of Lebanese nationality]]\n[[Category:Lebanese American University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Raya Meddine\n| image =\n| caption = \n| birthname = Rana Alamuddin\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| yearsactive = 2003\u2013present\n| othername = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Elie Karam|2004}} \n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Rana Alamuddin''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}}), known professionally as '''Raya Meddine''', is a Lebanese American actress. She is known for her role as [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]] on ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[New York City]], Meddine is a [[Lebanese Druze]] who has lived in several countries due to her father's work in diplomatic missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hakawati.fm/episodes/view/23453?_branch_match_id=772109758862189678|title=Rana Alamuddin|website=Hakawati|language=Arabic|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> She speaks five languages: French, Italian, Arabic, Spanish and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archive/interview-victor-s-new-love/article_137c6c1a-06fa-50b8-a873-757a37b27666.html|title=Interview: Victor\u2019s new love|website=tulsaworld.com|date=22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRaya Meddine studied Media at the [[Lebanese American University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlUx_OImSu4#t=13m49s|title=\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d - \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u062b\u0644\u0629 \u0648\u0645\u0642\u062f\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0645\u062c \u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 |website=FutureTV News|language=Arabic|date=19 September 2018}}</ref> She initially worked at [[Orbit TV]] as a host and reporter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107233348/http://www.dohafilminstitute.com/blog/people-in-film-raya-meddine-aka-rana-alamuddin|title=People in Film: Raya Meddine aka Rana Alamuddin|website=dohafilminstitute.com|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> She has later worked in Paris, [[Beirut]] and Los Angeles. In February 2008, Meddine joined the cast of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' in the contract role of [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]]. A shift in story line killed off the character, and Meddine left the role of Sabrina in August 2008. In June 2009, due to the popularity of the Sabrina character, Meddine inked a deal with ''The Young & the Restless'' to appear on a recurring basis as Sabrina's \"ghost\".\n\nSome of her other acting roles include Isabelle in the Lebanese box office hit ''[[Bosta (film)|Bosta]]'' (2006), and as Wanda in the short award winning film ''Recycling Flo'' (2004). She also made a guest appearance as Kayla on the NBC TV series, ''[[She Spies]]'' alongside [[Natasha Henstridge]] in 2003. In 2009, Meddine guest starred on the hit CBS series, ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', and will appear in the upcoming film, ''[[When Worlds Collide (2012 film)|When Worlds Collide]]'', produced by [[Steven Spielberg]]. ''When Worlds Collide'' is in pre-production and is scheduled for release in 2010/2011.  Ms. Meddine recently appeared in a featured role in the hit summer movie \"[[Sex and the City 2]]\" opposite [[Sarah Jessica Parker]].\n\nIn January 2012, Meddine appeared on the pilot episode of the FOX television series, ''Touch'', starring [[Kiefer Sutherland]].\n\nIn 2018, Meddine started to host a program titled \"Bayneh W Baynek\", with [[Nadine Labaki]] as the first guest, in which she discussed women issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.annahar.com/article/257467-%D8%B1%D9%86%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A-%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%83-%D9%84%D8%A7-%D9%85%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AE%D8%AC%D9%84|title=\u0631\u0646\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646: \"\u0628\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0648\u0628\u064a\u0646\u0650\u0643\" \u0644\u0627 \u0645\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u0644\u062e\u062c\u0644|website=annahar.com|language=Arabic|date=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMeddine married Lebanese-Canadian<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0607/18/lkl.01.html|title=Larry King Live|website=CNN|date=29 June 2006}}</ref> director/writer Elie Karam in a civil marriage in [[Cyprus]] in 2004, they have two kids together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BKkJrrPAFlq/|title=12th year wedding anniversary today. May our present & future be as glorious as our past.|website=Instagram|date=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fernadez|first1=Rebecce|title=Inspiring Reinvention:Rana Alamuddin|url=http://thewomentakeover.com/inspiring-reinvention-rana-alamuddin/|website=thewomentakeover.com|publisher=The Women Take Over|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> She and her husband currently divide their time between their homes in Los Angeles and Paris.\n\n==Social awareness==\nMeddine is cultural ambassador for the [[Levantine Cultural Center]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=People in Film:Raya Meddine|url=http://www.dohafilminstitute.com/blog/people-in-film-raya-meddine-aka-rana-alamuddin|website=dohafilminstitute.com|publisher=Doha Film Institute|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Film\n* 2004: ''Baby's Momma Drama'' as N/A\n* 2004: ''Recycling Flo'' as Wanda\n* 2005: ''Bosta'' as Isabelle\n* 2010: ''[[Sex and the City 2]]'' as Annesha\n* 2017: ''Wajib''\n* 2017: ''Bonbone''\n* 2019: ''Beirut Hold'em''\n\n;TV series\n* 2003: ''She Spies'' as Kayla <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2008: ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' as [[Sabrina Costelana Newman]] <small>('''Role:''' February 28-August 4, 2008, September 24, 2008, June 2, 2009 to June 5, 2009, December 23, 2010</small>\n* 2008: ''[[CSI: Miami]]'' as Kate Hawkes <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2010: ''[[Rizzoli & Isles]]'' as Claire <small>(1 episode)</small>\n* 2012: ''Touch'' as Mrs. Kosta\n\n;Video games\n* 2012: ''[[Diablo III]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1375816}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meddine, Raya}}\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Druze people of Lebanese nationality]]\n[[Category:Lebanese 