{"title_page": "Mohamed Saad", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Mohamed Saad\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Mohamed Saad Ahmad\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|12|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Giza Governorate|Giza]], [[Egypt]]\n| othername = El-Limby\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive = 1988\u2013Present\n| spouse =\n| children = Nour El-Deen, Kareem and Yassin\n|domesticpartner = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Mohamed Saad''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0639\u062f}}; born 14 December 1968) is an Egyptian film actor.\n\n==Career==\nAfter several supporting roles, Saad took the lead in ''[[El-Limby]]'' (2002; the name, that of Saad's character, is a play on the name of one of Egypt's colonial figures, High Commissioner [[Edmund Allenby, 1st Viscount Allenby|Edmund Allenby]]). Playing the film's \"illiterate, inefficient, slow, stoned and drunk\" hero, Saad \"invests his first leading role with a hyperactive physical energy especially evident in dance sequences.\" The comedy became one of the highest-grossing films in [[Cinema of Egypt|Egyptian cinema]].<ref>El-Assyouti, Mohamed, \"[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2002/600/cu6.htm The wedding game]\", ''[[Al Ahram]] Weekly'', August 22\u201328, 2002</ref>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2005, Saad played similar characters in three further films including one of his most successful movies ''Ely Baly Balak''.\n\nIn 2006, Saad starred in ''Katkout'', in which he played a hopeless [[Upper Egypt]]ian who stumbles into a career as a boxer and crimefighter.<ref>\"[http://www.egypttoday.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=6840 At a Theater Near You - ''Katkout'']\", ''Egypt Today'', July 2006</ref> Cairo online magazine ''Yallabina'' criticized the film for relying on Saad's [[physical comedy]] at the expense of story and script.<ref>Farahat, Yasmine, [http://www.yallabina.com/Movies/Movie/Katkout.aspx \"Katkout\" (Review)], Yallabina.com</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''El-Tariq Ela [[Eilat]]'' - '''1997''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0625\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062a) - The Road to Eilat\n* ''[[El Nazer|El-Nazer]]'' - '''1999''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0638\u0631) - The Principal\n* ''55 Esaaf'' - '''2001''' (ar: \u0625\u0633\u0639\u0627\u0641 55) - Ambulance 55\n* ''[[El-Limby]]'' - '''2002''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0649)\n* ''Ely Baly Balak'' - '''2003''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0643)\n* ''Oukal'' - '''2004''' (ar: \u0639\u0648\u0643\u0644)\n* ''Bouha'' - '''2005''' (ar: \u0628\u0648\u062d\u0629)\n* ''Katkout'' - '''2006''' (ar: \u0643\u062a\u0643\u0648\u062a)\n* ''Karkar'' - '''2007''' (ar: \u0643\u0631\u0643\u0631)\n* ''Boshkash'' - '''2008''' (ar: \u0628\u0648\u0634\u0643\u0627\u0634, named after, but unrelated to [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s|Pusk\u00e1s]])\n* ''El-Limby 8 Gega'' - '''2011 ''' (ar: \u0627\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0649 8 \u062c\u064a\u062c\u0627)\n*   ''Tatah'' - '''2013''' (ar: \u062a\u062a\u062d)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saad, Mohamed}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Egyptian male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Egyptian male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Egyptian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Mohamed Saad\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Mohamed Saad Ahmad\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|12|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Port said Governorate|Port said]], [[Egypt]]\n| othername = El-Limby\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive = 1988\u2013Present\n| spouse =\n| children = Nour El-Deen, Kareem and Yassin\n|domesticpartner = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Mohamed Saad''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0639\u062f}}; born 9 January 1968) is an Egyptian film actor, active since 2000.\n<!-- Location ------------------>\nAfter several supporting roles, Saad took the lead in ''[[El-Limby]]'' (2002; the name, that of Saad's character, is a play on the name of one of Egypt's colonial figures, High Commissioner [[Edmund Allenby, 1st Viscount Allenby|Edmund Allenby]]). Playing the film's \"illiterate, inefficient, slow, stoned and drunk\" hero, Saad \"invests his first leading role with a hyperactive physical energy especially evident in dance sequences.\" The comedy became one of the highest-grossing films in [[Cinema of Egypt|Egyptian cinema]].<ref>El-Assyouti, Mohamed, \"[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2002/600/cu6.htm The wedding game]\", ''[[Al Ahram]] Weekly'', August 22\u201328, 2002</ref>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2005, Saad played similar characters in three further films including one of his most successful movies ''Ely Baly Balak''.\n\nIn 2006, Saad starred in ''Katkout'', in which he played a hopeless [[Sa'idi people|Upper Egyptian]] who stumbles into a career as a boxer and crimefighter.<ref>\"[http://www.egypttoday.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=6840 At a Theater Near You - ''Katkout'']\", ''Egypt Today'', July 2006</ref> Cairo online magazine ''Yallabina'' criticized the film for relying on Saad's [[physical comedy]] at the expense of story and script.<ref>Farahat, Yasmine, [http://www.yallabina.com/Movies/Movie/Katkout.aspx \"Katkout\" (Review)], Yallabina.com</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* ''El-Tariq Ela [[Eilat]]'' - '''1997''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0625\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062a) - The Road to Eilat\n* ''[[El Nazer|El-Nazer]]'' - '''1999''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0638\u0631) - The Principal\n* ''55 Esaaf'' - '''2001''' (ar: \u0625\u0633\u0639\u0627\u0641 55) - Ambulance 55\n* ''[[El-Limby]]'' - '''2002''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0649)\n* ''Ely Baly Balak'' - '''2003''' (ar: \u0627\u0644\u0644\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0643)\n* ''Oukal'' - '''2004''' (ar: \u0639\u0648\u0643\u0644)\n* ''Bouha'' - '''2005''' (ar: \u0628\u0648\u062d\u0629)\n* ''Katkout'' - '''2006''' (ar: \u0643\u062a\u0643\u0648\u062a)\n* ''Karkar'' - '''2007''' (ar: \u0643\u0631\u0643\u0631)\n* ''Boshkash'' - '''2008''' (ar: \u0628\u0648\u0634\u0643\u0627\u0634, named after, but unrelated to [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s|Pusk\u00e1s]])\n* ''El-Limby 8 Gega'' - '''2011 ''' (ar: \u0627\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0649 8 \u062c\u064a\u062c\u0627)\n*   ''Tatah'' - '''2013''' (ar: \u062a\u062a\u062d)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saad, Mohamed}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Egyptian male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Egyptian male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Egyptian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "119.195.164.105", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohamed_Saad"}
{"title_page": "List of Evanston Township High School alumni", "text_new": "[[Evanston Township High School]] (ETHS), is a public four-year [[high school]] located in [[Evanston, Illinois]], a [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] suburb of [[Chicago]], in the United States. It is part of Evanston Township High School District 202.\n\nNotable alumni of Evanston Township High School include:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Business==\n* [[Henry Engelhardt]], CEO of the Admiral Group\n* [[Lester Crown]], businessman\n* [[Bob Galvin]] (1940) was the [[CEO]] of [[Motorola]] (1959\u201386).<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf|title=ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award|author=Evanston Township High School|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |archivedate = 2007-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Film, television, and theatre==\n* [[Heather Burns]] (1993) is an actress who appeared in films such as ''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]'', ''[[Two Weeks Notice]]'', and ''[[You've Got Mail]]''.\n* [[Joan Cusack]] (1980) is a two-time [[Academy Award]]-nominated actress (''[[Working Girl]]'' and ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'') also known for such films as ''[[Addams Family Values]]'', ''[[Broadcast News (film)|Broadcast News]]'', ''[[School of Rock]]'', ''[[Toys (film)|Toys]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 2]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/09_KIT_spring%202000.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031117015016/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/09_KIT_spring%202000.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-11-17 |title=The Kit, Spring 2000 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[John Cusack]] (1984) is a [[Golden Globe Award]]-nominated actor (''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]''), also known for such films as ''[[Being John Malkovich]]'', ''[[Con Air]]'', ''[[Eight Men Out]]'', ''[[The Grifters (film)|The Grifters]]'' and ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil (film)|Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\">[http://www.suntimes.com/sports/preps/highschool/366683,CST-SPT-spot02.article ''A rich history -- win, lose or tie'';  2 May 2007;  ''Chicago Sun-Times''; accessed 2 May 2009]</ref><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1999\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/07_KIT_Spring%2099_8-pg.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030403084800/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/07_Kit_Spring%2099_8-pg.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-04-03 |title=The Kit, Spring 1999 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[Jules Engel]] (1957) was an animator whose work includes ''[[Popeye#Theatrical cartoons|Popeye the Sailor]]'', and the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney]] films ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' and ''[[Bambi]]''.<ref name=\"Obituary: Jules Engel\">{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/news/obituary/0,12723,1043498,00.html|title=Jules Engel|author=The Guardian|accessdate=2007-08-14 | location=London | date=2003-09-17}}</ref>\n* [[Karen Finley]] (1974) is an artist, actress, educator and performer, whose art is displayed in museums around the world.\n* [[Zach Gilford]] (2000) is an actor, best known for his role on the television series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Alicia Goranson]] (1992) is an actress, best known for her role as [[List of Roseanne characters#Rebecca \"Becky\" Conner Healy|Becky Conner]] on the television series ''[[Roseanne (television show)|Roseanne]]''.\n*[[Laura Harrier]] (2008) is an actress, best known for her role as [[Liz Allan|Liz]] in [[Spider-Man: Homecoming]].\n* [[Anders Holm]] (1999) is an actor and writer, best known for his role Anders \"Ders\" Holmvik on the television series ''[[Workaholics]]''.\n* [[Amanda Jones (Miss USA)|Amanda Jones]] (1968) was crowned [[Miss USA]] 1973.\n* [[Lauren Lapkus]] (2004) is an actress and comedian, best known for her role as Susan Fischer in the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Orange Is the New Black]].''\n* [[Jeffrey Lieber]] (1987) is a writer who is co-creator of the television series ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref name=\"Cast Away\">{{cite web|url=http://chicago.godengo.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-2007/Cast-Away/ |title=Jeffrey Lieber |author=Chicago Magazine |accessdate=2007-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921163843/http://chicago.godengo.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-2007/Cast-Away/ |archivedate=2007-09-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Michael Madsen]] (1976) is an actor best known for roles in films such as ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]'' and ''[[Kill Bill]]''.<ref name=\"ETHS Alumni Association Newsletter, Spring 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/11_KIT_Spring_2001.pdf|title=The Kit: Spring 2001|author=The Kit|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070709223611/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/11_KIT_Spring_2001.pdf |archivedate = 2007-07-09}}</ref>\n* [[Jessie Mueller]] (2001) is a [[Tony Award]]-winning and a two-time [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]]-nominated theatre actress best known for roles in Broadway musicals such as Melinda Wells in ''[[On a Clear Day You Can See Forever|On A Clear Day You Can See Forever]]'', Janet Conover/Helena Landless in ''[[The Mystery Of Edwin Drood]]'', and Billie Bendix in ''[[Nice Work If You Can Get It (musical)|Nice Work If You Can Get It]]''.\n* [[Ajay Naidu]] (1990) is an actor who has appeared in films such as ''[[Pi (1998)|Pi]]'', ''[[Office Space]]'', and the television series ''[[LateLine]]''.<ref name=newsletter>{{cite news |title=ETHS alumni shine in theatre, dance, music, film |date=Spring 1999 |work=The KIT \u2013 Keeping in Touch Newsletter |publisher= Evanston Township High School Alumni Association |page=4}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Neal]] (1932), was a stage, film and television actor and amateur boxer.<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Dowd|first=John |title=Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye: The Barbara Payton Story|year=2007|publisher=BearManor Media|isbn=1-593-93063-1|page=148}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Pink]] (1984) is a director, screenwriter, and producer who has worked on films such as ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'', ''[[Grosse Point Blank]]'', and ''[[Hot Tub Time Machine]]''.<ref name=\"The It List: Leaders of the Pack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273878_2,00.html|title=The It List: Leaders of the Pack|author=EW.com|accessdate=2007-08-14|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=1999-06-25}}</ref>\n* [[Jeremy Piven]] (1983) is an actor, best known for his roles as [[Ari Gold (Entourage)|Ari Gold]] on the television series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' and as [[Harry Gordon Selfridge]] on the series ''[[Mr. Selfridge]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Metromix: Jeremy Piven\">{{cite news|url=http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/news/celebrity/mmx-0701280546jan28,0,1394486.story?coll=mmx-celebrity_heds |title=Metromix: Jeremy Piven |author=Metromix.com |accessdate=2007-08-14 |work=Chicago Tribune |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208092246/http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/news/celebrity/mmx-0701280546jan28%2C0%2C1394486.story?coll=mmx-celebrity_heds |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Jeffrey Sweet]] (1967) is an award-winning member of the playwrights ensemble of the [[Victory Gardens Theater]] of Chicago, a member of the Council of the [[Dramatists Guild]], and the author of an oral history of [[The Second City|Second City]] called ''Something Wonderful Right Away''.\n* [[Dave VanDam]] (1973)  American voice impressionist.\n* [[Lena Waithe]] (2002) is a television writer, producer, and actress, currently playing Denise on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Master of None]]''\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (1969) is an actress, comedian, and writer.<ref name=newsletter/>\n* [[Jenniffer Weigel]] (1988) is a Chicago television and radio personality.\n* [[Rafer Weigel]] (1987) is a St. Louis television news anchor and former Chicago sportscaster.\n\n==Government and public service==\n* [[George Wildman Ball]] (1926) was U.S. [[Under Secretary of State]] under Presidents [[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon Baines Johnson|Johnson]].  He was briefly [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] under President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |title=ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award |author=Evanston Township High School |accessdate=2007-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |archivedate=2007-08-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Jason Carter (politician)|Jason Carter]] was a Georgia state senator and the 2014 Democratic nominee for governor of Georgia.\n* [[David E. Miller]] (1980) was elected five times as an Illinois state representative and was the 2010 Democratic nominee for Illinois comptroller.\n* [[Sue Mullins]] was an Iowa farmer and state legislator.\n* [[John Edward Porter]] (1953) was a [[United States Congressman]] representing [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]] (1980\u20132001).<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/>\n\n==Letters==\n* [[Jessica Abel]] (1987) is a [[comic book]] writer and artist.\n* [[James Atlas]] (1967) is the president of Atlas & Company, publishers, and founding editor of the Penguin Lives Series.\n* [[Graham Elwood]] (1987) is a comedian, actor, writer and documentarian, famous for ''Laffganistan'' and the [[Comedy Film Nerds]] podcast.\n* [[Cornelia Grumman]] (1981) is a 2003 [[Pulitzer Prize]]\u2013winning [[editorial]] writer.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Charles R. Johnson]] (1966) is an author.  His novel ''[[Middle Passage (novel)|Middle Passage]]'' won the 1990 [[National Book Award]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/>\n* [[Margaret Landon]] (1921) is an author whose book ''[[Anna and the King of Siam (book)|Anna and the King of Siam]]'' was adapted into the stage musical and film ''[[The King and I]]''.\n* [[Audrey Niffenegger]] (1980) is an artist and author of ''[[The Time Traveller's Wife]]''.\n* [[Jack N. Rakove]] (1964) received the 1997 Pulitzer Prize in History for the book ''[[Original Meanings: Politics and Ideas in the Making of the Constitution]]''.\n* [[Megan Twohey]] (1994) is an investigative reporter with ''[[The New York Times]]'' who published an investigation in 2017 detailing the sexual abuse allegations made against Harvey Weinstein.\n\n==Music==\n* [[David Burge]] (1947) is a composer, author, and pianist who works with contemporary music.<ref>[http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award; accessed 27 April 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |date=21 August 2007 }}</ref>\n*[[Bob Cranshaw]] is a [[jazz]] [[bass (instrument)|bass]] player.\n* [[Kay Davis]] is a jazz singer.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Brown |first=Carrie Moea |title=Kathryn Wimp's Musical Journey with Duke Ellington |work=Shorefront Volume 7 Number 3 |publisher=Shorefront |date=Spring 2006 |url=http://shorefrontlegacy.org/Shorefront_Links/Publications_files/Vol%207%20No%203%202006.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=September 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402082610/http://shorefrontlegacy.org/Shorefront_Links/Publications_files/Vol%207%20No%203%202006.pdf |archivedate=April 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Alexander Frey]] (James Alexander Frey) (1989) is an internationally renowned conductor, pianist, organist and recording artist.\n* [[Ezra Furman]] (2004) is the lead singer of the rock/folk band \"[[Ezra Furman and the Harpoons]]\"\n* [[Nancy Gustafson]] (1974) is an [[opera]] [[soprano]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award\"/>\n* [[Junior Mance]] (1945) is a jazz [[pianist]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2002.pdf |title=The Kit, Spring 2002 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2009-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061210175916/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2002.pdf |archivedate=December 10, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Science, technology, and education==\n* [[Robert Axelrod]] (1961), political science professor at the University of Michigan, recipient of 2012 [[National Medal of Science]]{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not mention this school|date=May 2018}}\n* [[Matthew Cook]] (1988), mathematician and computer scientist who proved Stephen Wolfram's conjecture that the Rule 110 cellular automaton is Turing-complete{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not mention this school|date=May 2018}}\n*[[William E. Cross Jr.]] (1959) <ref name=\"cuny.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gc.cuny.edu/Page-Elements/Academics-Research-Centers-Initiatives/Doctoral-Programs/Psychology/Faculty-Bios/William-Cross|title=William Cross Faculty Bio|website=City University of New York}}</ref> Academic and author.\n* [[Ann Hardy]] (1951), computer pioneer\n* [[Jay Rosenberg]] (1959) Philosopher, academic.\n\n==Sports==\n* [[Alex Agase]] (1941) was a [[American football|football]] [[Guard (American football)|guard]] and head coach at [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]] and [[Purdue University|Purdue]].  In 1963, he was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/01_Kit_Fall%201995.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030604170811/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/01_Kit_Fall%201995.pdf |archive-date=2003-06-04 |title=The Kit, Spring 1995 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Lou Agase]] (1943) was a standout college football player and later coach, who later briefly served as [[head coach]] of the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/05_KIT_Spring%201998.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030423173643/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/05_KIT_Spring%201998.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-04-23 |title=The Kit, Spring 1998 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[Paddy Driscoll]] (1914) was a [[quarterback]] who was elected to both the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] and College Football Hall of Fame.  He both played for and coached the [[Chicago Cardinals]] and [[Chicago Bears]].<ref name=\"High School of the Week\">{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/preps/highschool/366683,CST-SPT-spot02.article|title=High School of the Week|author=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=2007-08-14 | date=2007-05-02}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Foster (baseball)|Kevin Foster]] (1987) was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]] (1993\u201398, 2001), playing most of his career with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2004.pdf|title=The Kit, Spring 2004|author=ETHS Alumni Association|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061207040817/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2004.pdf |archivedate = 2006-12-07}}</ref>\n* [[Clint Frank]] was a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] at [[Yale University]].  He won the 1937 [[Heisman Trophy]] and was the first winner of the [[Maxwell Award]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Robert Gary]] (1991) is a 2-time Olympian ([[3,000 m steeplechase]]; [[Athletics at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3000 metre steeplechase|1996]], [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3000 metres steeplechase|2004]]) and current [[head coach]] of [[Furman University]]'s men's [[track & field]]  and [[Cross country running|cross country]] teams.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/coaches/Robert_Gary |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424154657/http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/coaches/Robert_Gary |archive-date=2019-04-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He formerly coached both sports at [[The Ohio State University]], where he competed as a collegian.\n*[[Dov Grumet-Morris]] (2000) was a professional ice hockey player\n* [[William Heusner]] (1944) was a swimmer who competed at the [[Swimming at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948 Summer Olympics]] and won two medals at the [[Swimming at the 1951 Pan American Games|1951 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Damon Jones (American football)|Damon Jones]] (1992) was an [[National Football League|NFL]] [[tight end]] (1997\u20132001), playing his entire career for the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>[http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=JonesDam01 Damon Jones stats and bio; databasefootbal.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218084020/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=JONESDAM01 |date=18 February 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Yonel Jourdain]] (1989) was a running back and kick returner for the [[Buffalo Bills]].<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JourYo20.htm Yonel Jourdain stats and bio; pro-football-reference.com; accessed 21-Oct-2015]</ref>\n* [[Mike Kenn]] (1974) was a 5-time NFL [[Pro Bowl]] [[Offensive tackle (American football)|offensive tackle]] (1978\u201394), playing his entire career for the [[Atlanta Falcons]].  His uniform number 78 was retired by the Falcons.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Football field to be named after Lazier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pioneerlocal.com/evanston/sports/483837,ev-lazierfield-072607-s1.article|title=Football field to be named after Lazier|author=Pioneer Press|accessdate=2007-08-14}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Lackey]] was a two-time [[All-American]] basketball player known as the \"Black Swan\", at [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette University]], who played two years for the [[New York Nets]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\"/><ref>[http://www.databasebasketball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LackeBo01 Bob Lackey stats and bio @ databasebasketball.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117133552/http://databasebasketball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LACKEBO01 |date=17 January 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Cecil Martin]] (1994) was an [[National Football League|NFL]] fullback (1999\u20132003) who played for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].\n* [[Ed Martin (American football)|Ed Martin]], USFL player\n* [[Emery Moorehead]] (1972) was an NFL tight end who played most of his career for the Chicago Bears.  He was the starting tight end for the [[Super Bowl XX]] champion Chicago Bears.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Sports, June 27, 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.evanstonroundtable.com/rt_062707/sports.html|title=Sports, June 27, 2007|author=Evanston Roundtable|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929044058/http://www.evanstonroundtable.com/rt_062707/sports.html |archivedate = 2007-09-29}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Parker (defensive end, born 1959)|Steve Parker]], NFL player\n* [[Dan Peterson]] (1954) is a professional basketball coach.  He retired after leading [[Olimpia Milano]] to the 1987 Grand Slam [[Euroleague|Champions Cup]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian Championship]] and [[Coppa Italia di pallacanestro maschile|Italian Cup]].  In 2011, Peterson was hired to coach his old team, [[Olimpia Milano]], for the second half of that season after the old coach was fired.\n* [[Jim Purnell]] (1960) was an NFL [[linebacker]] (1964\u201372), playing most of his career with the Chicago Bears.<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\"/><ref>[http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=PURNEJIM01 Jim Purnell stats and bio; database football.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215071820/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=PURNEJIM01 |date=15 February 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Richard Mason Rocca]] (1996) was a basketball player who played on the [[Italy national basketball team|Italian national team]] and for [[Olimpia Milano]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2002\"/>\n* [[Mike Rogodzinski]] (1966) was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1973\u201375).<ref name=\"Evanston Review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pioneerlocal.com/evanston/sports/highschools/839098,ev-hall-031308-s1.article|title='Murney's Men' lead induction parade|author=Evanston Review|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/R/Mike-Rogodzinski.shtml Mike Rogodzinski stats & bio; the baseballcube.com; accessed 23 June 2009]</ref>\n* [[Diane Simpson-Bundy]] is a two-time Olympic gymnast and television broadcaster.\n* [[Everette Stephens]] (1984) was an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[Guard (basketball)|guard]] (1988\u201391).<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1995\"/>\n* [[Ray Woods]] (1913), brother of Ralf, was a three-time men's basketball [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] (1915\u201317) and one-time [[Helms Foundation College Basketball Player of the Year|Helms National Player of the Year]] (1917) at [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|Illinois]].<ref name=WOODS1>{{Cite web | title = 2004\u201305 Illinois Men's Basketball Media Guide| publisher = University of Illinois| url = http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/04-05-tradition.pdf|format=PDF|year=2004|accessdate = December 5, 2010}}</ref><ref name=WOODS2>{{Cite book |last=Scott |first=Frank William| page=706 |title = The semi-centennial alumni record of the University of Illinois| publisher = University of Illinois| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OXEmAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA706&ots=qTBIEdEn4V&dq=ray%20woods%20basketball&pg=PA706#v=onepage&q=ray%20woods%20basketball&f=false|format=PDF|year=2004|accessdate = December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough]] (1994) was a [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] center (1998\u20132004) who played for the [[Charlotte Sting]],  [[Cleveland Rockers]], [[Miami Sol]], and [[Houston Comets]].\n* [[Miles Grosz]] (2017) was a Division 3 Wide Receiver at Coe College.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evanston Township High School Alumni}}\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni|*]]\n[[Category:People from Evanston, Illinois|*]]\n[[Category:Education in Evanston, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "[[Evanston Township High School]] (ETHS), is a public four-year [[high school]] located in [[Evanston, Illinois]], a [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] suburb of [[Chicago]], in the United States. It is part of Evanston Township High School District 202.\n\nNotable alumni of Evanston Township High School include:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Business==\n* [[Henry Engelhardt]], CEO of the Admiral Group\n* [[Lester Crown]], businessman\n* [[Bob Galvin]] (1940) was the [[CEO]] of [[Motorola]] (1959\u201386).<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf|title=ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award|author=Evanston Township High School|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |archivedate = 2007-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Cinema, stage, and television==\n* [[Heather Burns]] (1993) is an actress who appeared in films such as ''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]'', ''[[Two Weeks Notice]]'', and ''[[You've Got Mail]]''.\n* [[Joan Cusack]] (1980) is a two-time [[Academy Award]]-nominated actress (''[[Working Girl]]'' and ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'') also known for such films as ''[[Addams Family Values]]'', ''[[Broadcast News (film)|Broadcast News]]'', ''[[School of Rock]]'', ''[[Toys (film)|Toys]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 2]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/09_KIT_spring%202000.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031117015016/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/09_KIT_spring%202000.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-11-17 |title=The Kit, Spring 2000 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[John Cusack]] (1984) is a [[Golden Globe Award]]-nominated actor (''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]''), also known for such films as ''[[Being John Malkovich]]'', ''[[Con Air]]'', ''[[Eight Men Out]]'', ''[[The Grifters (film)|The Grifters]]'' and ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil (film)|Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\">[http://www.suntimes.com/sports/preps/highschool/366683,CST-SPT-spot02.article ''A rich history -- win, lose or tie'';  2 May 2007;  ''Chicago Sun-Times''; accessed 2 May 2009]</ref><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1999\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/07_KIT_Spring%2099_8-pg.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030403084800/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/07_Kit_Spring%2099_8-pg.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-04-03 |title=The Kit, Spring 1999 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[Jules Engel]] (1957) was an animator whose work includes ''[[Popeye#Theatrical cartoons|Popeye the Sailor]]'', and the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney]] films ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' and ''[[Bambi]]''.<ref name=\"Obituary: Jules Engel\">{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/news/obituary/0,12723,1043498,00.html|title=Jules Engel|author=The Guardian|accessdate=2007-08-14 | location=London | date=2003-09-17}}</ref>\n* [[Karen Finley]] (1974) is an artist, actress, educator and performer, whose art is displayed in museums around the world.\n* [[Zach Gilford]] (2000) is an actor, best known for his role on the television series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Alicia Goranson]] (1992) is an actress, best known for her role as [[List of Roseanne characters#Rebecca \"Becky\" Conner Healy|Becky Conner]] on the television series ''[[Roseanne (television show)|Roseanne]]''.\n* [[Anders Holm]] (1999) is an actor and writer, best known for his role Anders \"Ders\" Holmvik on the television series ''[[Workaholics]]''.\n* [[Amanda Jones (Miss USA)|Amanda Jones]] (1968) was crowned [[Miss USA]] 1973.\n* [[Lauren Lapkus]] (2004) is an actress and comedian, best known for her role as Susan Fischer in the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Orange Is the New Black]].''\n* [[Jeffrey Lieber]] (1987) is a writer who is co-creator of the television series ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref name=\"Cast Away\">{{cite web|url=http://chicago.godengo.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-2007/Cast-Away/ |title=Jeffrey Lieber |author=Chicago Magazine |accessdate=2007-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921163843/http://chicago.godengo.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-2007/Cast-Away/ |archivedate=2007-09-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Michael Madsen]] (1976) is an actor best known for roles in films such as ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]'' and ''[[Kill Bill]]''.<ref name=\"ETHS Alumni Association Newsletter, Spring 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/11_KIT_Spring_2001.pdf|title=The Kit: Spring 2001|author=The Kit|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070709223611/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/11_KIT_Spring_2001.pdf |archivedate = 2007-07-09}}</ref>\n* [[Jessie Mueller]] (2001) is a [[Tony Award]]-winning and a two-time [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]]-nominated theatre actress best known for roles in Broadway musicals such as Melinda Wells in ''[[On a Clear Day You Can See Forever|On A Clear Day You Can See Forever]]'', Janet Conover/Helena Landless in ''[[The Mystery Of Edwin Drood]]'', and Billie Bendix in ''[[Nice Work If You Can Get It (musical)|Nice Work If You Can Get It]]''.\n* [[Ajay Naidu]] (1990) is an actor who has appeared in films such as ''[[Pi (1998)|Pi]]'', ''[[Office Space]]'', and the television series ''[[LateLine]]''.<ref name=newsletter>{{cite news |title=ETHS alumni shine in theatre, dance, music, film |date=Spring 1999 |work=The KIT \u2013 Keeping in Touch Newsletter |publisher= Evanston Township High School Alumni Association |page=4}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Neal]] (1932), was a stage, film and television actor and amateur boxer.<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Dowd|first=John |title=Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye: The Barbara Payton Story|year=2007|publisher=BearManor Media|isbn=1-593-93063-1|page=148}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Pink]] (1984) is a director, screenwriter, and producer who has worked on films such as ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'', ''[[Grosse Point Blank]]'', and ''[[Hot Tub Time Machine]]''.<ref name=\"The It List: Leaders of the Pack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273878_2,00.html|title=The It List: Leaders of the Pack|author=EW.com|accessdate=2007-08-14|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=1999-06-25}}</ref>\n* [[Jeremy Piven]] (1983) is an actor, best known for his roles as [[Ari Gold (Entourage)|Ari Gold]] on the television series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' and as [[Harry Gordon Selfridge]] on the series ''[[Mr. Selfridge]]''.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Metromix: Jeremy Piven\">{{cite news|url=http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/news/celebrity/mmx-0701280546jan28,0,1394486.story?coll=mmx-celebrity_heds |title=Metromix: Jeremy Piven |author=Metromix.com |accessdate=2007-08-14 |work=Chicago Tribune |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208092246/http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/news/celebrity/mmx-0701280546jan28%2C0%2C1394486.story?coll=mmx-celebrity_heds |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Jeffrey Sweet]] (1967) is an award-winning member of the playwrights ensemble of the [[Victory Gardens Theater]] of Chicago, a member of the Council of the [[Dramatists Guild]], and the author of an oral history of [[The Second City|Second City]] called ''Something Wonderful Right Away''.\n* [[Dave VanDam]] (1973)  American voice impressionist.\n* [[Lena Waithe]] (2002) is a television writer, producer, and actress, currently playing Denise on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Master of None]]''\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (1969) is an actress, comedian, and writer.<ref name=newsletter/>\n* [[Jenniffer Weigel]] (1988) is a Chicago television and radio personality.\n* [[Rafer Weigel]] (1987) is a St. Louis television news anchor and former Chicago sportscaster.\n\n==Government and public service==\n* [[George Wildman Ball]] (1926) was U.S. [[Under Secretary of State]] under Presidents [[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon Baines Johnson|Johnson]].  He was briefly [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] under President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |title=ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award |author=Evanston Township High School |accessdate=2007-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |archivedate=2007-08-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Jason Carter (politician)|Jason Carter]] was a Georgia state senator and the 2014 Democratic nominee for governor of Georgia.\n* [[David E. Miller]] (1980) was elected five times as an Illinois state representative and was the 2010 Democratic nominee for Illinois comptroller.\n* [[Sue Mullins]] was an Iowa farmer and state legislator.\n* [[John Edward Porter]] (1953) was a [[United States Congressman]] representing [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]] (1980\u20132001).<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/>\n\n==Letters==\n* [[Jessica Abel]] (1987) is a [[comic book]] writer and artist.\n* [[James Atlas]] (1967) is the president of Atlas & Company, publishers, and founding editor of the Penguin Lives Series.\n* [[Graham Elwood]] (1987) is a comedian, actor, writer and documentarian, famous for ''Laffganistan'' and the [[Comedy Film Nerds]] podcast.\n* [[Cornelia Grumman]] (1981) is a 2003 [[Pulitzer Prize]]\u2013winning [[editorial]] writer.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Charles R. Johnson]] (1966) is an author.  His novel ''[[Middle Passage (novel)|Middle Passage]]'' won the 1990 [[National Book Award]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/>\n* [[Margaret Landon]] (1921) is an author whose book ''[[Anna and the King of Siam (book)|Anna and the King of Siam]]'' was adapted into the stage musical and film ''[[The King and I]]''.\n* [[Audrey Niffenegger]] (1980) is an artist and author of ''[[The Time Traveller's Wife]]''.\n* [[Jack N. Rakove]] (1964) received the 1997 Pulitzer Prize in History for the book ''[[Original Meanings: Politics and Ideas in the Making of the Constitution]]''.\n* [[Megan Twohey]] (1994) is an investigative reporter with ''[[The New York Times]]'' who published an investigation in 2017 detailing the sexual abuse allegations made against Harvey Weinstein.\n\n==Music==\n* [[David Burge]] (1947) is a composer, author, and pianist who works with contemporary music.<ref>[http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award; accessed 27 April 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821023107/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/alumniaward.pdf |date=21 August 2007 }}</ref>\n*[[Bob Cranshaw]] is a [[jazz]] [[bass (instrument)|bass]] player.\n* [[Kay Davis]] is a jazz singer.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Brown |first=Carrie Moea |title=Kathryn Wimp's Musical Journey with Duke Ellington |work=Shorefront Volume 7 Number 3 |publisher=Shorefront |date=Spring 2006 |url=http://shorefrontlegacy.org/Shorefront_Links/Publications_files/Vol%207%20No%203%202006.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=September 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402082610/http://shorefrontlegacy.org/Shorefront_Links/Publications_files/Vol%207%20No%203%202006.pdf |archivedate=April 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Alexander Frey]] (James Alexander Frey) (1989) is an internationally renowned conductor, pianist, organist and recording artist.\n* [[Ezra Furman]] (2004) is the lead singer of the rock/folk band \"[[Ezra Furman and the Harpoons]]\"\n* [[Nancy Gustafson]] (1974) is an [[opera]] [[soprano]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni Award\"/>\n* [[Junior Mance]] (1945) is a jazz [[pianist]].<ref name=\"ETHS Distinguished Alumni AwardJoe Moore- 1976-Member of the Chicago City Council\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2002.pdf |title=The Kit, Spring 2002 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2009-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061210175916/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2002.pdf |archivedate=December 10, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Science, technology, and education==\n* [[Robert Axelrod]] (1961), political science professor at the University of Michigan, recipient of 2012 [[National Medal of Science]]{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not mention this school|date=May 2018}}\n* [[Matthew Cook]] (1988), mathematician and computer scientist who proved Stephen Wolfram's conjecture that the Rule 110 cellular automaton is Turing-complete{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not mention this school|date=May 2018}}\n*[[William E. Cross Jr.]] (1959) <ref name=\"cuny.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gc.cuny.edu/Page-Elements/Academics-Research-Centers-Initiatives/Doctoral-Programs/Psychology/Faculty-Bios/William-Cross|title=William Cross Faculty Bio|website=City University of New York}}</ref> Academic and author.\n* [[Ann Hardy]] (1951), computer pioneer\n* [[Jay Rosenberg]] (1959) Philosopher, academic.\n\n==Sports==\n* [[Alex Agase]] (1941) was a [[American football|football]] [[Guard (American football)|guard]] and head coach at [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]] and [[Purdue University|Purdue]].  In 1963, he was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/01_Kit_Fall%201995.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030604170811/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/01_Kit_Fall%201995.pdf |archive-date=2003-06-04 |title=The Kit, Spring 1995 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Lou Agase]] (1943) was a standout college football player and later coach, who later briefly served as [[head coach]] of the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/05_KIT_Spring%201998.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030423173643/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/05_KIT_Spring%201998.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-04-23 |title=The Kit, Spring 1998 |author=ETHS Alumni Association |accessdate=2007-08-14 }}</ref>\n* [[Paddy Driscoll]] (1914) was a [[quarterback]] who was elected to both the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] and College Football Hall of Fame.  He both played for and coached the [[Chicago Cardinals]] and [[Chicago Bears]].<ref name=\"High School of the Week\">{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/preps/highschool/366683,CST-SPT-spot02.article|title=High School of the Week|author=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=2007-08-14 | date=2007-05-02}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Foster (baseball)|Kevin Foster]] (1987) was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]] (1993\u201398, 2001), playing most of his career with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2004.pdf|title=The Kit, Spring 2004|author=ETHS Alumni Association|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061207040817/http://www.eths.k12.il.us/alumni/pdfs/spring2004.pdf |archivedate = 2006-12-07}}</ref>\n* [[Clint Frank]] was a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] at [[Yale University]].  He won the 1937 [[Heisman Trophy]] and was the first winner of the [[Maxwell Award]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Robert Gary]] (1991) is a 2-time Olympian ([[3,000 m steeplechase]]; [[Athletics at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3000 metre steeplechase|1996]], [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3000 metres steeplechase|2004]]) and current [[head coach]] of [[Furman University]]'s men's [[track & field]]  and [[Cross country running|cross country]] teams.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/coaches/Robert_Gary |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424154657/http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/coaches/Robert_Gary |archive-date=2019-04-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He formerly coached both sports at [[The Ohio State University]], where he competed as a collegian.\n*[[Dov Grumet-Morris]] (2000) was a professional ice hockey player\n* [[William Heusner]] (1944) was a swimmer who competed at the [[Swimming at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948 Summer Olympics]] and won two medals at the [[Swimming at the 1951 Pan American Games|1951 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/>\n* [[Damon Jones (American football)|Damon Jones]] (1992) was an [[National Football League|NFL]] [[tight end]] (1997\u20132001), playing his entire career for the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>[http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=JonesDam01 Damon Jones stats and bio; databasefootbal.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218084020/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=JONESDAM01 |date=18 February 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Yonel Jourdain]] (1989) was a running back and kick returner for the [[Buffalo Bills]].<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JourYo20.htm Yonel Jourdain stats and bio; pro-football-reference.com; accessed 21-Oct-2015]</ref>\n* [[Mike Kenn]] (1974) was a 5-time NFL [[Pro Bowl]] [[Offensive tackle (American football)|offensive tackle]] (1978\u201394), playing his entire career for the [[Atlanta Falcons]].  His uniform number 78 was retired by the Falcons.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Football field to be named after Lazier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pioneerlocal.com/evanston/sports/483837,ev-lazierfield-072607-s1.article|title=Football field to be named after Lazier|author=Pioneer Press|accessdate=2007-08-14}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Lackey]] was a two-time [[All-American]] basketball player known as the \"Black Swan\", at [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette University]], who played two years for the [[New York Nets]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\"/><ref>[http://www.databasebasketball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LackeBo01 Bob Lackey stats and bio @ databasebasketball.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117133552/http://databasebasketball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=LACKEBO01 |date=17 January 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Cecil Martin]] (1994) was an [[National Football League|NFL]] fullback (1999\u20132003) who played for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].\n* [[Ed Martin (American football)|Ed Martin]], USFL player\n* [[Emery Moorehead]] (1972) was an NFL tight end who played most of his career for the Chicago Bears.  He was the starting tight end for the [[Super Bowl XX]] champion Chicago Bears.<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"Sports, June 27, 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.evanstonroundtable.com/rt_062707/sports.html|title=Sports, June 27, 2007|author=Evanston Roundtable|accessdate=2007-08-14 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929044058/http://www.evanstonroundtable.com/rt_062707/sports.html |archivedate = 2007-09-29}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Parker (defensive end, born 1959)|Steve Parker]], NFL player\n* [[Dan Peterson]] (1954) is a professional basketball coach.  He retired after leading [[Olimpia Milano]] to the 1987 Grand Slam [[Euroleague|Champions Cup]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian Championship]] and [[Coppa Italia di pallacanestro maschile|Italian Cup]].  In 2011, Peterson was hired to coach his old team, [[Olimpia Milano]], for the second half of that season after the old coach was fired.\n* [[Jim Purnell]] (1960) was an NFL [[linebacker]] (1964\u201372), playing most of his career with the Chicago Bears.<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1998\"/><ref>[http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=PURNEJIM01 Jim Purnell stats and bio; database football.com; accessed 2 May 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215071820/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=PURNEJIM01 |date=15 February 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Richard Mason Rocca]] (1996) was a basketball player who played on the [[Italy national basketball team|Italian national team]] and for [[Olimpia Milano]].<ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 2002\"/>\n* [[Mike Rogodzinski]] (1966) was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1973\u201375).<ref name=\"Evanston Review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pioneerlocal.com/evanston/sports/highschools/839098,ev-hall-031308-s1.article|title='Murney's Men' lead induction parade|author=Evanston Review|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/R/Mike-Rogodzinski.shtml Mike Rogodzinski stats & bio; the baseballcube.com; accessed 23 June 2009]</ref>\n* [[Diane Simpson-Bundy]] is a two-time Olympic gymnast and television broadcaster.\n* [[Everette Stephens]] (1984) was an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[Guard (basketball)|guard]] (1988\u201391).<ref name=\"Sun Times HS of the Week\"/><ref name=\"The Kit, Spring 1995\"/>\n* [[Ray Woods]] (1913), brother of Ralf, was a three-time men's basketball [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] (1915\u201317) and one-time [[Helms Foundation College Basketball Player of the Year|Helms National Player of the Year]] (1917) at [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|Illinois]].<ref name=WOODS1>{{Cite web | title = 2004\u201305 Illinois Men's Basketball Media Guide| publisher = University of Illinois| url = http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ill/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/04-05-tradition.pdf|format=PDF|year=2004|accessdate = December 5, 2010}}</ref><ref name=WOODS2>{{Cite book |last=Scott |first=Frank William| page=706 |title = The semi-centennial alumni record of the University of Illinois| publisher = University of Illinois| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OXEmAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA706&ots=qTBIEdEn4V&dq=ray%20woods%20basketball&pg=PA706#v=onepage&q=ray%20woods%20basketball&f=false|format=PDF|year=2004|accessdate = December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough]] (1994) was a [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] center (1998\u20132004) who played for the [[Charlotte Sting]],  [[Cleveland Rockers]], [[Miami Sol]], and [[Houston Comets]].\n* [[Miles Grosz]] (2017) was a Division 3 Wide Receiver at Coe College.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evanston Township High School Alumni}}\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni|*]]\n[[Category:People from Evanston, Illinois|*]]\n[[Category:Education in Evanston, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCinema, stage, and television", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Evanston_Township_High_School_alumni"}
{"title_page": "Les Frangines", "text_new": "'''Les Frangines''' are a French musical duo composed of female singers and guitarists Anne Coste and Jacinthe Madelin. Their sound can be described as acoustic pop-folk.<ref name=\"Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie | Culture TV5MONDE\" /><ref name=\"Les Frangines : Anne et Jacinthe sont-elles soeurs ? (VIDEO)\">{{cite web|title=Les Frangines : Anne et Jacinthe sont-elles soeurs ? (VIDEO)|url=https://www.programme-tv.net/news/musique/237991-les-frangines-anne-et-jacinthe-sont-elles-soeurs-video/|date=2019-08-16|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe duo is composed of two female friends, Anne Coste and Jacinthe Madelin.<ref name=\"Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie | Culture TV5MONDE\">{{cite web|title=Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie|url=https://culture.tv5monde.com/musique/biographies-artistes/les-frangines-13110|agency=[[TV5MONDE]]|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref> They have been friends since they were 12. They studied at the same school (near La Celle-Saint-Cloud in the Paris suburbs) and first met on their way there.\n\nOnly one of the two, Jacinthe, who took [[flute]] for 15 years, has formal musical training. Both studied philology at university. They learned to play the guitar by watching online video lessons.\n\nIn 2014 they launched their own [[YouTube]] channel and started uploading their own songs. They raised money for their first professional music video via [[crowdfunding]].\n\nThey were then noticed by the record label [[Jo & Co]] and signed. In March 2018 they released their debut [[single (music)|single]], titled \"Si j'osais\". Their first [[Extended play|EP]], ''Vagabondes'', followed on June 22, 2018.\n\nThe duo's first hit, \"Donnez-moi\", was co-written and composed with [[Vianney (singer)|Vianney]], who had been their friend for a long time. Released as a single on March 8, 2019, the song racked up over 500,000 streams in one month and reached the top 10 on [[iTunes]].\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! Charts\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|FRA<br /><ref name=\"lescharts.ch - Les Frangines - Les Frangines\">{{cite web|title=lescharts.ch - Les Frangines - Les Frangines|url=https://lescharts.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=Les+Frangines&titel=Les+Frangines&cat=a|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Les Frangines''\n* Released : 21 June 2019<ref name=\"Les frangines by Les Frangines on Apple Music\">{{cite web|title=Les frangines by Les Frangines on Apple Music|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/les-frangines/1462271862|date=2019-06-21|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n* Label : Jo&Co\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 18\n|rowspan=\"2\"| FRA: Gold<ref name=\"Les certifications - SNEP (Recherche : Album, Les Frangines)\">{{cite web|title=Les certifications - SNEP (Recherche : Album, Les Frangines)|url=https://snepmusique.com/les-certifications/?categorie=Albums&interprete=Les%20Frangines|language=fr-FR|date=2020|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Les Frangines (Version deluxe)''\n* Sortie : 29 November 2019<ref name=\"Les Frangines (Version deluxe) par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music\">{{cite web|title=Les Frangines (Version deluxe) par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music|url=https://music.apple.com/fr/album/les-frangines-version-deluxe/1489359535|date=2019-11-29|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n* Label : Jo&Co\n|}\n\n=== EPs ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"1\"| Album\n|-\n| ''Vagabondes''\n* Released : 22 June 2018<ref name=\"Vagabondes - EP par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music\">{{cite web|title=Vagabondes - EP par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music|url=https://music.apple.com/fr/album/vagabondes-ep/1398342143|date=2018-06-22|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n* Label : Jo&Co\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frangines, Les}}\n[[Category:French musical duos]]\n", "text_old": "'''Les Frangines''' are a French musical duo composed of female singers and guitarists Anne Coste and Jacinthe Madelin. Their sound can be described as acoustic pop-folk.<ref name=\"Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie | Culture TV5MONDE\" /><ref name=\"Les Frangines : Anne et Jacinthe sont-elles soeurs ? (VIDEO)\">{{cite web|title=Les Frangines : Anne et Jacinthe sont-elles soeurs ? (VIDEO)|url=https://www.programme-tv.net/news/musique/237991-les-frangines-anne-et-jacinthe-sont-elles-soeurs-video/|date=2019-08-16|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe duo is composed of two female friends, Anne Coste and Jacinthe Madelin.<ref name=\"Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie | Culture TV5MONDE\">{{cite web|title=Biographie LES FRANGINES, \u00e2ge et discographie|url=https://culture.tv5monde.com/musique/biographies-artistes/les-frangines-13110|agency=[[TV5MONDE]]|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref> They have been friends since they were 12. They studied at the same school (near La Celle-Saint-Cloud in the Paris suburbs) and first met on their way there.\n\nOnly one of the two, Jacinthe, who took [[flute]] for 15 years, has formal musical training. Both studied philology at university. They learned to play the guitar by watching online video lessons.\n\nIn 2014 they launched their own [[YouTube]] channel and started uploading their own songs. They raised money for their first professional music video via crowdfunding.\n\nThey were then noticed by the record label [[Jo & Co]] and signed. In March 2018 they released their debut [[single (music)|single]], titled \"Si j'osais\". Their first [[Extended play|EP]], ''Vagabondes'', followed on June 22, 2018.\n\nThe duo's first hit, \"Donnez-moi\", was co-written and composed with [[Vianney (singer)|Vianney]], who had been their friend for a long time. Released as a single on March 8, 2019, the song racked up over 500,000 streams in one month and reached the top 10 on [[iTunes]].\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! Charts\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|FRA<br /><ref name=\"lescharts.ch - Les Frangines - Les Frangines\">{{cite web|title=lescharts.ch - Les Frangines - Les Frangines|url=https://lescharts.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=Les+Frangines&titel=Les+Frangines&cat=a|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Les Frangines''\n* Released : 21 June 2019<ref name=\"Les frangines by Les Frangines on Apple Music\">{{cite web|title=Les frangines by Les Frangines on Apple Music|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/les-frangines/1462271862|date=2019-06-21|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n* Label : Jo&Co\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 18\n|rowspan=\"2\"| FRA: Gold<ref name=\"Les certifications - SNEP (Recherche : Album, Les Frangines)\">{{cite web|title=Les certifications - SNEP (Recherche : Album, Les Frangines)|url=https://snepmusique.com/les-certifications/?categorie=Albums&interprete=Les%20Frangines|language=fr-FR|date=2020|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Les Frangines (Version deluxe)''\n* Sortie : 29 November 2019<ref name=\"Les Frangines (Version deluxe) par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music\">{{cite web|title=Les Frangines (Version deluxe) par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music|url=https://music.apple.com/fr/album/les-frangines-version-deluxe/1489359535|date=2019-11-29|access-date=2020-02-28|publication-date=}}</ref>\n* Label : Jo&Co\n|}\n\n=== EPs ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"1\"| Album\n|-\n| ''Vagabondes''\n* Released : 22 June 2018<ref name=\"Vagabondes - EP par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music\">{{cite web|title=Vagabondes - EP par Les Frangines sur Apple\u00a0Music|url=https://music.apple.com/fr/album/vagabondes-ep/1398342143